INSERT INTO sat_questions (type, section, prompt, options, correct_answer, explanation, domain, difficulty_tier, module_number, set_number)
VALUES
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Both Min Jin Lee, a Korean American novelist, and Lisa Ko, a Chinese American writer, spent their early careers searching for stories that reflected the complexities of immigrant life. In 2017, ______ Pachinko and The Leavers brought widespread recognition to contemporary Asian American literature, highlighting themes of identity, displacement, and belonging across generations. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"their acclaimed novels,"},{"id":"B","text":"their acclaimed novels"},{"id":"C","text":"their—acclaimed—novels"},{"id":"D","text":"their, acclaimed, novels"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of commas to set off nonessential modifiers in a sentence. The comma after “novels” correctly separates the main clause (“In 2017, their acclaimed novels…brought widespread recognition…”) from the rest of the sentence, making the modifier “acclaimed” nonrestrictive and clarifying the sentence’s meaning. Choice B is incorrect because it omits the comma, which can make the sentence slightly harder to read and mislead the reader into thinking “acclaimed novels” is restrictive rather than descriptive. Choice C is incorrect because dashes are not needed to set off the adjective “acclaimed” and create an unnecessarily dramatic and informal tone that is inappropriate in this context. Choice D is incorrect because commas surrounding “acclaimed” without proper context disrupt the sentence’s flow and create grammatical inaccuracy.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'As the director of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Elena Morales has numerous duties. These include curating the museum’s European painting collection, which spans more than five centuries of artistic _______ the museum’s educational programs, which engage students and families through workshops and lectures; and coordinating international exhibitions, which bring rare artworks from around the world to New York City. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"development; overseeing"},{"id":"B","text":"development, overseeing"},{"id":"C","text":"development; overseeing"},{"id":"D","text":"development. Overseeing"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of elements in a complex series. In a series where individual items contain internal commas, it is conventional to use a semicolon to separate the main items. In this sentence, the semicolon after “development” correctly separates the first item (“curating the museum’s European painting collection, which spans more than five centuries of artistic development”) from the second item (“overseeing the museum’s educational programs, which engage students and families through workshops and lectures”) in the list of Elena Morales’s duties. Choice A is incorrect because it fails to use appropriate punctuation to separate the first and second items in the complex series. Choice B is incorrect because a comma after “development” does not match the semicolon later used to separate the second and third items in the series (“overseeing…lectures” and “and coordinating international exhibitions”). Choice D is incorrect because it results in a sentence fragment beginning with “Overseeing,” which is grammatically unacceptable.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A pioneering physicist and chemist, Marie Curie conducted transformative research on radioactivity that altered the trajectory of modern science. Bestowed the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1911, ______ established foundational principles for the study of radioactive decay and elemental transmutation. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Curie isolated the elements radium and polonium in 1898, and this work"},{"id":"B","text":"in 1898 Curie isolated radium and polonium, which"},{"id":"C","text":"Curie’s 1898 isolation of the elements radium and polonium"},{"id":"D","text":"the elements radium and polonium were isolated by Curie in 1898, and"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is modifier placement and logical parallelism between the introductory participial phrase and the sentence subject. The modifying phrase “Bestowed the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1911” must logically modify a noun that represents the achievement for which the honor was conferred. The noun phrase “Curie’s 1898 isolation of the elements radium and polonium” clearly identifies the scientific accomplishment and aligns grammatically and logically with the modifier. Choice A is incorrect because positioning “Curie” immediately after the modifier misleadingly implies that Curie herself, rather than her scientific work, was “bestowed the Nobel Prize.” Choice B is incorrect because introducing the temporal phrase “in 1898” directly after the modifier creates a dangling modifier, making it seem as though “in 1898” received the award. Choice D is incorrect because beginning the clause with “the elements radium and polonium” illogically suggests that the elements themselves—not Curie’s act of isolating them—were recipients of the Nobel Prize.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In studying volcanic activity, geologists often examine the role of magma chambers. What are magma chambers, and how ______________ Part of the Earth’s internal structure, magma chambers are large underground reservoirs of molten rock. Under certain conditions, these chambers can release their magma through volcanic eruptions. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"do they influence eruptions."},{"id":"B","text":"they do influence eruptions."},{"id":"C","text":"do they influence eruptions?"},{"id":"D","text":"they do influence eruptions?"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is end-of-sentence punctuation. This choice correctly uses a question mark to punctuate the coordinated interrogative clauses “What are magma chambers” and “how do they influence eruptions,” both of which ask direct questions. Choice A is incorrect because a period cannot be used to punctuate an interrogative clause like “how do they influence eruptions.” Choice B is incorrect because the sentence structure requires an interrogative clause, not a declarative one. Choice D is incorrect because the structure requires an interrogative clause at the end of the sentence, not a declarative clause with a question mark.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Deep beneath the Antarctic ice sheet, scientists have discovered networks of subglacial lakes—vast reservoirs of liquid water isolated for millennia—that appear to host unique microbial ecosystems. Nutrient gradients in the ______ chemical exchange sustain the microorganisms that thrive in these extreme environments. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"lakes sediments regulate the ecosystem’s"},{"id":"B","text":"lake’s sediments regulate the ecosystems"},{"id":"C","text":"lake’s sediments regulate the ecosystems’"},{"id":"D","text":"lakes’ sediments regulate the ecosystems’"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of plural and possessive nouns. The plural possessive noun “lakes’” and the plural possessive noun “ecosystems’” correctly indicate that the sediments belong to multiple lakes and that there are multiple ecosystems sustained by those sediments. Choice A is incorrect because the context requires the plural possessive noun “lakes’” and the plural possessive noun “ecosystems’,” not the plural noun “lakes” and the singular possessive noun “ecosystem’s.” Choice B is incorrect because the context requires the plural possessive noun “lakes’,” not the singular possessive noun “lake’s,” since multiple lakes are being discussed. Choice C is incorrect because the context requires the plural possessive noun “lakes’,” not the singular possessive noun “lake’s,” given that the passage refers to networks of lakes, not a single lake.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In her commentary on T.S. Eliot’s The Waste Land (1922), critic Maud Ellmann argues that the poem reflects “a civilization fractured by the mechanical rhythm of modern _________ an observation that captures the poem’s anxious oscillation between cultural decay and spiritual renewal. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"existence”; and"},{"id":"B","text":"existence” and"},{"id":"C","text":"existence,”"},{"id":"D","text":"existence”"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between a main clause and a supplementary noun phrase. This choice correctly uses a comma to mark the boundary between the main clause (“critic…existence”) and the supplementary noun phrase (“an observation…renewal”) that describes Ellmann’s argument about how The Waste Land reflects the fractured condition of modern civilization. Choice A is incorrect because a semicolon and the conjunction “and” can’t be used in this way to mark the boundary between a main clause and a supplementary noun phrase. Choice B is incorrect. Joining the main clause (“critic…existence”) and the following noun phrase with the conjunction “and” results in a confusing and illogical sentence that suggests that the poem itself is “an observation,” which doesn’t make sense in this context. Choice D is incorrect because it fails to mark the boundary between the main clause and the supplementary noun phrase with appropriate punctuation.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Hoping to commemorate the fiftieth anniversary of the Bauhaus movement, _______ an international exhibition that highlighted the school’s enduring influence on modern architecture and design. The show attracted thousands of visitors and was later adapted for display in several European cities. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"an exhibition featuring Bauhaus-inspired works was curated by the Museum of Modern Art"},{"id":"B","text":"a collection of Bauhaus artifacts was assembled by the Museum of Modern Art as part of"},{"id":"C","text":"the Museum of Modern Art organized an exhibition featuring Bauhaus-inspired works in"},{"id":"D","text":"a selection of modernist designs from Bauhaus alumni was displayed by the Museum of Modern Art in"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject-modifier placement. This choice makes the noun phrase “the Museum of Modern Art” the subject of the sentence and places it immediately after the modifying phrase “Hoping to commemorate the fiftieth anniversary of the Bauhaus movement.” In doing so, this choice clearly establishes that the Museum of Modern Art—and not another noun in the sentence—was hoping to commemorate the Bauhaus movement’s anniversary. Choice A is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “an exhibition” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the exhibition itself hoped to commemorate the anniversary. Choice B is incorrect because it also results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “a collection of Bauhaus artifacts” illogically suggests that the collection hoped to commemorate the anniversary. Choice D is incorrect because it too results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “a selection of modernist designs” immediately after the modifier illogically suggests that the selection of designs, rather than the museum, had the commemorative intent.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Marie Tharp was a pioneering geologist and oceanographer who mapped the floor of the Atlantic Ocean in the mid-20th century. She collaborated with geologist Bruce Heezen to create detailed maps that revealed underwater mountain ranges and rift valleys. Tharp also emphasized the importance of visual representation in scientific research. _______ she used color-coded maps to highlight variations in ocean depth and geological formations. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"In addition"},{"id":"B","text":"Surprisingly"},{"id":"C","text":"However"},{"id":"D","text":"Nevertheless"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “In addition” logically signals that the detail in this sentence—that Tharp used color-coded maps to highlight ocean features—adds to the information in the previous sentence. Specifically, the previous sentence indicates one way in which Tharp emphasized the importance of visual representation, and the claim that follows indicates a second, additional way. Choice B is incorrect because “surprisingly” illogically signals that the detail in this sentence is unexpected in light of the information in the previous sentence. Instead, the detail adds to the information, indicating a second, additional way in which Tharp emphasized visual representation. Choice C is incorrect because “however” illogically signals that the detail in this sentence contrasts with the information in the previous sentence. Instead, the detail adds to the information, indicating a second, additional way in which Tharp emphasized visual representation. Choice D is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically signals that the detail in this sentence is true despite the information in the previous sentence. Instead, the detail adds to the information, indicating a second, additional way in which Tharp emphasized visual representation.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Before an architect begins designing a new structure, the project team conducts a thorough site assessment, analyzing soil quality and environmental factors. Next, the architect drafts preliminary blueprints that outline the building’s layout and materials. _______ these blueprints are refined into final construction plans and submitted for approval. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"For example,"},{"id":"B","text":"Conversely,"},{"id":"C","text":"Previously,"},{"id":"D","text":"Finally,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “Finally” logically signals that the actions in this sentence—the refinement and submission of final construction plans—are the next and final steps in a process, following the earlier stages of site assessment and blueprint drafting. Choice A is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that the actions in this sentence are merely an example of the previous steps in the architectural process. Instead, they are the concluding steps. Choice B is incorrect because “conversely” illogically signals that the actions in this sentence contrast with the previous steps of site assessment and blueprint drafting. Instead, they follow those steps sequentially. Choice C is incorrect because “previously” illogically signals that the actions in this sentence occur before the actions in the previous sentences. Instead, the refinement and submission of final construction plans occur after those earlier steps in the process.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Astrophysicist Victoria Kaspi studies fast radio bursts (FRBs), extremely brief flashes of radio waves from deep space. • In 2018, Kaspi and her team used data from the CHIME radio telescope in Canada. • CHIME detected several unusually frequent repeating FRBs. • Before the analysis, Kaspi hypothesized that the repeating signals might originate from highly magnetized neutron stars called magnetars. • The 2018 study was designed to test whether magnetars could be the source of these repeating FRBs. The student wants to emphasize the aim of the research study. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The CHIME radio telescope in Canada detected multiple repeating fast radio bursts in 2018."},{"id":"B","text":"Before analyzing the CHIME data, Victoria Kaspi suspected that magnetars might be producing unusually frequent FRBs."},{"id":"C","text":"Victoria Kaspi’s 2018 study set out to determine whether highly magnetized neutron stars—magnetars—were responsible for repeating FRBs."},{"id":"D","text":"The analysis of CHIME data ultimately revealed several repeating signals from deep space."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The sentence emphasizes the aim of the research—the specific question Kaspi’s study was designed to investigate: whether magnetars could be the source of repeating fast radio bursts. Choice A is incorrect. While the sentence states what CHIME detected, it does not emphasize the goal of the research study. Choice B is incorrect. Although the sentence describes Kaspi’s earlier hypothesis, it does not indicate the explicit aim of the study. Choice D is incorrect. This sentence reports a research finding, not the purpose for which the study was conducted.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2019, New Zealand scientist Juliet Gerrard became the first woman appointed as Chief Science Advisor to the government in the country’s history. _______ only one other woman, France’s Anne Peyroche, had held a comparable national scientific advisory role, highlighting Gerrard’s groundbreaking achievement. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Consequently,"},{"id":"B","text":"Previously,"},{"id":"C","text":"Nevertheless,"},{"id":"D","text":"Similarly,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “Previously” logically signals that the event described in this sentence—Anne Peyroche holding a national scientific advisory role—occurred before Gerrard’s appointment. The fact that only one other woman had held a similar position puts Gerrard’s achievement in historical context. Choice A is incorrect because “consequently” illogically signals that Peyroche’s appointment occurred as a result of Gerrard’s appointment. Instead, it occurred earlier and provides historical context. Choice C is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically signals contrast or contradiction with Gerrard’s appointment. Instead, it gives historical perspective. Choice D is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that this sentence merely adds a second, comparable piece of information. Instead, it situates Gerrard’s achievement in a historical timeline, showing its rarity.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'At first glance, architect Lina Boon’s Skywalk Pavilion appears to hover several meters above the forest floor in Singapore, supported only by thin beams. _____ clever engineering and hidden support structures ensure that the pavilion is fully stable while maintaining the illusion of floating above the treetops. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Additionally,"},{"id":"B","text":"On the contrary,"},{"id":"C","text":"As a result,"},{"id":"D","text":"Next,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “On the contrary” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that clever engineering and hidden support structures keep the pavilion fully stable—is in contrast with the previous statement about a viewer’s possible assumption that the pavilion appears to hover unsupported. Choice A is incorrect because “additionally” illogically suggests that this sentence merely provides extra information about a viewer’s assumption. Instead, it emphasizes a contrast between the illusion and the reality of the pavilion’s support. Choice C is incorrect because “as a result” illogically signals that the stability of the pavilion is a consequence of a viewer’s assumption. In reality, it contrasts with the impression created by the design. Choice D is incorrect because “next” illogically suggests a sequential step in a process. Instead, the sentence explains the contrast between the pavilion’s appearance and its actual engineering.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Political scientist Robert Putnam’s analyses of civic engagement across diverse societies have rigorously illustrated that social capital—networks of trust and reciprocity—can flourish organically within communities (rather than being imposed top-down by state institutions or formal organizations). _________ Putnam’s research constitutes a challenge to the conventional notion that democratic participation inevitably deteriorates in the absence of strong governmental oversight. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"By contrast,"},{"id":"B","text":"For example,"},{"id":"C","text":"That said,"},{"id":"D","text":"As such,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “As such” correctly signals that the claim in this sentence—that Putnam’s research constitutes a challenge to the conventional notion about democratic participation—follows logically from the information about Putnam’s analyses in the previous sentence. According to that sentence, his studies demonstrate that social capital can flourish organically within communities rather than being imposed by formal institutions. Choice A is incorrect because “by contrast” illogically signals that the claim in this sentence opposes or contradicts the information about Putnam’s studies. Instead, the claim logically follows from that information. Choice B is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that the claim in this sentence merely exemplifies the information about Putnam’s studies. Instead, the claim is a logical consequence of that information. Choice C is incorrect because “that said” illogically signals that the claim in this sentence is an exception or qualification to the information about Putnam’s studies. Instead, the claim follows directly and logically from that information.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The United States has 63 national parks with distinct landscapes and ecological features. • Yellowstone National Park spans Wyoming, Montana, and Idaho and preserves a large, continuously functioning ecosystem. • Its geothermal features attract millions of visitors annually. • Grand Canyon National Park contains a vast canyon carved by the Colorado River over millions of years. • Portions of the Grand Canyon remain closed in 2025 because of the Dragon Bravo wildfire, limiting visitor access. The student wants to highlight an advantage of Yellowstone National Park for visitors. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Portions of the Grand Canyon remain inaccessible in 2025 due to the Dragon Bravo wildfire, limiting the areas visitors can explore."},{"id":"B","text":"Because Yellowstone preserves a large and continuously functioning ecosystem, visitors have access to extensive natural habitats across three different states."},{"id":"C","text":"Yellowstone’s geothermal features attract visitors annually, while the Grand Canyon’s dramatic views and river-rafting opportunities draw a different crowd."},{"id":"D","text":"The United States contains 63 national parks, each offering unique landscapes that visitors may choose among depending on their interests."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it emphasizes an advantage of Yellowstone for visitors: the park’s expansive, intact ecosystem spread across multiple states, allowing access to broad natural areas. Choice A is incorrect. It identifies a limitation of the Grand Canyon, not an advantage of Yellowstone. Choice C is incorrect. It simply contrasts the types of attractions in two parks; it does not explain a particular benefit of Yellowstone for visitors. Choice D is incorrect. It provides a general fact about all national parks, failing to show what specifically makes Yellowstone advantageous.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Philadelphia is home to one of the largest public mural programs in the United States. The city’s Mural Arts Program began in 1984 as an effort to reduce graffiti and transform public spaces. Over the years, thousands of murals have been painted on walls throughout the city, depicting scenes of local history, cultural heritage, and community life. Many murals are restored or repainted by new artists, allowing the collection to evolve over time. Today, Philadelphia’s murals are recognized not only as works of art but also as reflections of the city’s diverse communities and their stories. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To compare murals in Philadelphia with murals in other U.S. cities"},{"id":"B","text":"To provide an overview of the history and significance of Philadelphia’s murals"},{"id":"C","text":"To encourage citizens to participate in mural creation in Philadelphia"},{"id":"D","text":"To describe the methods used to restore murals in Philadelphia"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately states the main purpose of the text. The passage introduces the Mural Arts Program in Philadelphia, explains its origins in 1984, and highlights how murals depict local history and community life while evolving over time. The overall focus is to give readers an overview of both the history and cultural significance of Philadelphia’s murals. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not compare murals in Philadelphia to those in other cities. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not encourage public participation; it describes the murals and their significance. Choice D is incorrect because although the text mentions that murals are restored or repainted, it does not detail the methods used for restoration.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In coral reef ecosystems, "cleaner" species provide a vital service by removing dead skin and parasites from larger fish, known as clients. This interaction is mutually beneficial, as the cleaner gets a meal while the client stays healthy. "The bluestreak cleaner wrasse (Labroides dimidiatus) often performs a rhythmic ''dance'' to signal its peaceful intentions to a potential client fish before beginning the cleaning process." Once the client recognizes this signal, it will typically remain still—and sometimes even open its mouth or gill covers—to allow the wrasse safe access to sensitive areas. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined sentence in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It identifies a physical trait of the bluestreak cleaner wrasse that helps it hide from predators."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It describes the appearance of the coral reefs mentioned earlier in the text."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It offers a detail about how the cleaner wrasse carries out the behavior discussed in the text."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It explains how the client fish reacts to the cleaning behavior discussed in the text."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it best describes how the underlined sentence functions in the text as a whole. The first two sentences establish the general behavior of "cleaner" species providing a service to larger fish. The underlined sentence then provides a specific detail about a particular cleaner species, the bluestreak cleaner wrasse, explaining that it uses a rhythmic dance to signal its intentions. Thus, the underlined sentence offers a particular detail about how the wrasse carries out the cleaning interaction. Choice A is incorrect. The underlined sentence describes a behavior (a dance), not a "physical trait" (like color or fin shape), and it mentions signaling to clients rather than "hiding from predators." Choice B is incorrect. While the text mentions coral reefs, the underlined sentence focuses entirely on the interaction between the wrasse and the client fish; it does not provide any description of the "appearance" of the reef itself. Choice D is incorrect. The underlined sentence describes the behavior of the wrasse (the cleaner); it is the following sentence that addresses how the client fish reacts by remaining still or opening its mouth.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Since World War II, suburbanization has reshaped American cities, redistributing population, wealth, and political power. Although suburban areas have historically been more affluent and less diverse than central cities, recent scholarship suggests that many suburbs are becoming more racially and economically diverse. However, sociologists Elena Vesselinov and Renaud Le Goix argue that the rapid growth of gated communities complicates this narrative. Drawing on spatial and segregation analyses of metropolitan areas including Phoenix, Las Vegas, and Seattle, they contend that gated communities function as a new layer of suburbanization, concentrating affluence and reinforcing segregation even as surrounding suburbs diversify. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It outlines the historical development of suburbanization and then evaluates whether that process has ended in contemporary cities."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It lists the defining characteristics of gated communities and then proposes policy solutions to mitigate their effects."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It describes a shift in prevailing views about suburban diversity and then presents researchers’ findings that challenge that shift."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It compares suburban and urban neighborhoods and then argues that suburban inequality has surpassed urban inequality."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because the text first presents a commonly held scholarly view that suburban areas are becoming more diverse. It then introduces Vesselinov and Le Goix’s research, which challenges that view by arguing that gated communities introduce a new form of segregation within suburbs. Choice A is incorrect. While the text briefly mentions the postwar origins of suburbanization, it does not evaluate whether suburbanization has ended; instead, it argues that it has taken on a new form. Choice B is incorrect. The text does not enumerate characteristics of gated communities in isolation, nor does it propose policy solutions. Choice D is incorrect. Although inequality is discussed, the text does not compare suburban inequality to urban inequality or claim that one has surpassed the other.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Kate Chopin’s 1897 short story “A Pair of Silk Stockings.” Mrs. Sommers had been handling the fifteen dollars for some time, turning it over in her mind as carefully as she fingered it in her hand. It seemed to her a very small fortune, one that ought to be spent with the utmost prudence. She had planned, down to the last penny, how she would purchase new shoes for Janie, material for the boys’ shirts, and a pair of stockings for Mag. Those needs were clear in her mind. But when she entered the department store and felt the soft, cool fabric of the silk stockings that a clerk laid before her, she hesitated. “They don’t belong on me,” she murmured. And yet she lingered, her hand resting lightly on the shimmering pair, a faint flush of anticipation rising in her face. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To show how Mrs. Sommers carefully evaluates the quality of clothing sold in the department store"},{"id":"B","text":"To reveal Mrs. Sommers’s unexpected attraction to an indulgence that conflicts with her practical plans"},{"id":"C","text":"To describe the financial challenges Mrs. Sommers faces while raising her children"},{"id":"D","text":"To explain why Mrs. Sommers wishes to reconsider her responsibilities toward her family"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it captures the main purpose of the text: to show Mrs. Sommers’s conflicted response when an unplanned, indulgent purchase (the silk stockings) competes with her originally practical intentions. The passage details how she had carefully planned to spend the money on her children, then describes her unexpected hesitation and attraction when she encounters the stockings. This contrast illustrates her internal conflict. Choice A is incorrect because although the text mentions the fabric of the stockings, it does not focus on evaluating clothing quality. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not directly discuss financial hardship beyond her careful budgeting. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not suggest she is reconsidering her responsibilities—only that she is momentarily tempted by a personal luxury.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While contemporary scholarship has undermined claims that the poetry of eighteenth-century Japanese writer Matsuo Bashō was _______ the development of haiku, it is indisputable that his residence in rural Edo-period villages meant that his works were primarily accessible far from the major urban literary centers of his time. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"irrelevant to"},{"id":"B","text":"antagonistic toward"},{"id":"C","text":"imitated by"},{"id":"D","text":"controversial among"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Matsuo Bashō. As used in this context, “irrelevant to” means not significant to. According to the text, Bashō lived in rural Edo-period villages, far from major urban literary centers, which might have limited the circulation of his works. However, contemporary scholarship shows that his poetry was important to the development of haiku, undermining claims that it was irrelevant. Choice B is incorrect because the issue under consideration is not whether Bashō’s poetry was hostile or opposed to haiku development, but whether it was influential. Choice C is incorrect because “imitated by” would suggest that other poets actively modeled their poetry after Bashō, which the text does not claim. Choice D is incorrect because “controversial among” would imply that his poetry caused debate or dispute, whereas the passage focuses on the reach and significance of his work rather than disputes it provoked.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Some researchers have proposed that ambient temperature can meaningfully shape moral decision-making, suggesting that feelings of physical warmth or coldness subtly bias people’s judgments. However, these claims warrant caution. In a 2019 experiment, psychologist Martin S. Hagger and colleagues asked participants to make a series of moral evaluations while holding either a warm pack or a cold pack. Prior studies had reported that warmth is associated with more lenient judgments and coldness with harsher ones, effects often attributed to embodied cognition. Yet Hagger’s team found no statistically reliable differences between the warm-pack and cold-pack groups. Their findings raise the possibility that earlier results may not be as robust as once assumed. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To argue that embodied-cognition research has been methodologically flawed, as shown by Hagger’s experiment"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To present Hagger’s findings as evidence that broad claims about temperature’s influence on moral judgment should be approached carefully"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To explain how Hagger’s experiment resolves a longstanding debate regarding temperature’s effect on moral reasoning"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To compare the results of Hagger’s work with neuroscientific studies that explore physiological factors in moral judgment"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because the passage uses Hagger’s experiment to illustrate why broad claims about temperature shaping moral decision-making should not be overstated. The text begins by noting that some scholars argue that ambient temperature biases moral evaluations, then introduces Hagger’s 2019 replication attempt, which found no such effect. Together, these elements show that the purpose of the passage is to urge caution in interpreting earlier research. Choice A is incorrect because although the passage mentions that Hagger’s findings diverge from previous studies, it does not argue that embodied-cognition research as a whole is methodologically flawed. The text avoids critiquing earlier methods and instead emphasizes the need for careful interpretation. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not claim that Hagger’s study resolves any debate. It simply notes that his results failed to replicate prior findings, leaving the question open rather than settled. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not compare Hagger’s study with neuroscientific research. It focuses solely on contrasting earlier behavioral findings with Hagger’s replication attempt.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While examining early twentieth-century household goods from a mining settlement in Nevada, historical archaeologist Barbara Voss identified a collection of ceramic fragments imported from China. These ceramics, recovered from living quarters occupied by Chinese immigrant laborers, featured decorative motifs typically associated with family banquets and festival gatherings rather than with utilitarian, everyday use. Voss argues that the presence of these items indicates that Chinese workers deliberately maintained cultural culinary traditions despite the harsh demands and isolating conditions of industrial labor camps. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To describe how an unexpected archaeological finding changed scholars’ understanding of trade routes connecting Nevada mining camps to East Asia"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To discuss research showing that Chinese immigrant laborers in early twentieth-century Nevada adopted American dining customs to assimilate into local culture"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To evaluate the accuracy of a researcher’s interpretation of decorative motifs found on Chinese ceramic artifacts in Nevada mining communities"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To summarize the findings of a study examining why Chinese immigrant laborers in early twentieth-century Nevada preserved cultural dining practices through specific household objects"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because the passage clearly summarizes the findings of Voss’s study: that the decorative Chinese ceramics found in Nevada mining settlements illustrate how immigrant laborers preserved traditional cultural dining practices despite difficult working and living conditions. This matches the structure of the sample explanation, which identifies a passage as summarizing a study’s findings about a culturally meaningful practice. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not discuss shifts in scholarly views about trade networks, nor does it characterize the artifacts as an “unexpected” discovery. The text strictly focuses on cultural practices, not trade routes. Choice B is incorrect because the passage argues the opposite: the workers retained Chinese traditions rather than adopting American dining customs for assimilation. This mirrors the logic of eliminating Choice B in the sample, where the incorrect option reversed the passage’s argument. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not evaluate Voss’s interpretation; it simply describes her conclusions. It also does not scrutinize the accuracy of her reading of the decorative motifs. This matches the reasoning for eliminating evaluative answer choices in the sample.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The forest floor is a low-light environment where plants must compete fiercely for the small amount of sunlight that filters through the canopy. Biologists have traditionally measured the success of a forest-floor plant species by its "vertical growth rate"—how quickly it grows upward to reach more light. However, researcher Dr. Elena Rossi hypothesizes that the survival and spread of the wood sorrel (Oxalis acetosella) cannot be measured by its vertical growth alone. She suggests that the plant''s ability to reproduce and colonize new areas is primarily driven by its use of "cleistogamous" flowers—self-pollinating flowers that never open and are located near the soil. Which finding, if true, would most directly support Dr. Rossi’s hypothesis?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Wood sorrel plants that grow in the deepest shade produce significantly more self-pollinating cleistogamous flowers than they do upward-reaching stems."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The leaves of the wood sorrel contain a high concentration of chlorophyll, which allows the plant to perform photosynthesis more efficiently than many other forest-floor species."},{"id":"C","text":"C. In a five-year study, wood sorrel populations expanded into new areas of the forest mostly through seeds produced by flowers at the base of the plant rather than through the growth of taller stems."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Many insects that visit the forest floor are more attracted to the bright white petals of the wood sorrel’s open flowers than to the flowers of other nearby plants."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it provides direct evidence that the plant''s "success" (expansion and colonization) is not linked to vertical growth, but rather to the specific reproductive mechanism (flowers at the base) mentioned in the hypothesis. If the expansion happened through these seeds rather than taller stems, it confirms that vertical growth is not the primary measure of the species'' success. Choice A is incorrect. While this shows the plant produces these flowers in the shade, it does not provide evidence that these flowers are the primary driver of the plant''s "success" or "spread," which is what Dr. Rossi''s hypothesis claims. Choice B is incorrect. This finding describes a physiological advantage (chlorophyll efficiency) but does not address the specific hypothesis regarding the role of cleistogamous flowers versus vertical growth. Choice D is incorrect. This finding focuses on insect attraction to open flowers. This actually shifts the focus away from the self-pollinating, closed flowers that Dr. Rossi is investigating, and therefore does not support her claim.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Recent spectroscopic analysis of the Martian atmosphere by the ExoMars Trace Gas Orbiter has revealed localized, seasonal spikes in methane concentrations that do not align with known geological outgassing patterns. Utilizing high-resolution atmospheric simulations to account for wind dispersion and chemical degradation, planetary scientist Elena Moreno and her team have suggested that these fluctuations could potentially originate from microbial life thriving in subterranean aquifers. While these findings are provocative, Moreno emphasizes that further subsurface drilling missions are necessary to determine if biological processes or unconventional chemical reactions are the true source of the gas. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Moreno and her team have definitively proven that microbial life is responsible for the methane spikes detected on Mars."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Atmospheric simulations have demonstrated that methane on Mars cannot be produced by any known chemical or geological process."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Current research suggests that an anomaly in Martian methane levels might be attributable to biological activity beneath the planet''s crust."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Moreno and her team developed a new spectroscopic tool that identifies subterranean aquifers without measuring atmospheric gas concentrations."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The text indicates that the study is not definitive ("suggested," "could potentially"), but it explains that the unusual methane spikes might be explained by the presence of subterranean microbial life. This mirrors the logic of the Mimas ocean hypothesis. Choice A is incorrect. This choice goes too far beyond the information in the text. Moreno’s team suggested that the methane could originate from life and noted that more missions are needed for a "true" determination, but they have not confirmed or proven anything yet. Choice B is incorrect. This choice conflicts with the text. The research identifies a sign of potential life (the methane spikes) but does not state that chemical or geological processes have been ruled out entirely; in fact, it mentions "unconventional chemical reactions" as a possible alternative. Choice C is incorrect. This choice doesn''t reflect the text. The team used "high-resolution atmospheric simulations" to account for wind and chemistry to explain the spikes (the anomaly), rather than a tool that bypasses gas analysis entirely.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'André Bazin (1918–1958), widely regarded as one of the most consequential figures in the history of film criticism, exerted a transformative influence on the emergence of cinema studies as a serious intellectual discipline. His prodigious body of work—comprising more than 2,600 articles—was assembled after his death into the four-volume series Qu’est-ce que le cinéma? (What Is Cinema?), published between 1958 and 1962. Although a portion of these essays was translated into English in the late 1960s and early 1970s and subsequently became foundational in film curricula across the English-speaking world, those translations remained static and were never revised. In recent decades, however, renewed scholarly interest in Bazin has produced more comprehensive and accessible translations. These include André Bazin: Selected Writings 1943–1958 (2018), translated by Timothy Barnard, and The André Bazin Reader (2009), which introduced new translations of previously unavailable texts and offered extensive annotation and commentary. Another significant compilation, André Bazin, the Critic as Thinker: American Cinema from Early Chaplin to the Late 1950s, gathers much of Bazin’s writing on major American filmmakers such as Orson Welles, Charles Chaplin, Alfred Hitchcock, and Howard Hawks. Which choice best describes the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Bazin’s later translators introduced errors into his work that complicated its use in modern film scholarship."},{"id":"B","text":"Although Bazin wrote on a wide range of topics, his most enduring work concerns American cinema of the early twentieth century."},{"id":"C","text":"Bazin’s extensive and influential critical writings have continued to shape film studies, aided by significant new translations and collections."},{"id":"D","text":"Bazin’s early career as a journalist prepared him for his later work as a major theorist of the moving image."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately conveys the central idea of the passage. The text highlights the scale and influence of Bazin’s writings, noting that his thousands of essays helped solidify film studies as an intellectual field. It also emphasizes that new translations and curated collections—such as The André Bazin Reader and Selected Writings 1943–1958—have broadened access to his work and sustained his impact. Thus, the passage’s main purpose is to underscore the enduring significance of Bazin’s oeuvre and the role recent scholarship has played in preserving it. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not suggest that the newer translations introduced errors or created difficulties for scholars. Instead, it portrays the updated translations as expanding access and enhancing understanding. Choice B is incorrect because, although the passage mentions a volume focused on Bazin’s writings about American filmmakers, it does not imply that this was the primary or “most enduring” part of his work. The text emphasizes the breadth and overall influence of his writing rather than narrowing it to one topic. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not discuss Bazin’s early career or describe journalism as preparation for later theoretical work. His background prior to his critical writings is not presented as a central theme.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Psychologist Carol Dweck and colleagues have investigated how "growth mindset" interventions—programs that teach students that intelligence can be developed—affect academic resilience. The researchers hypothesized that students who participate in a growth mindset workshop that includes a "self-transcendent" purpose for learning (learning to help others or society) would exhibit higher levels of academic persistence during difficult tasks than students who receive a standard mindset intervention or no intervention at all. To test this, researchers assigned students to one of three groups and measured their persistence (measured by the average number of minutes spent on unsolvable math problems). Which choice best describes data from the graph that support the researchers’ conclusion?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. None of the average persistence scores for the three groups reached or exceeded 15.0 minutes."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The students in the control group exhibited only slightly less persistence on average than the students in the two experimental groups did."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The students who received the growth mindset intervention combined with a self-transcendent purpose exhibited more persistence on average than the students in the other two groups did."},{"id":"D","text":"D. All three groups exhibited significantly more persistence on average than the researchers had initially predicted prior to the study."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it describes data from the table that support the researchers’ conclusion that their hypothesis was correct. The researchers hypothesized that a growth mindset combined with a "self-transcendent" purpose would lead to higher persistence than other methods. The table shows that the "Growth Mindset + Purpose" group had an average persistence of 14.8 minutes, which is higher than both the "Growth Mindset Only" group (11.2 minutes) and the "Control" group (10.9 minutes). Choice A is incorrect. While it is factually true that no score reached 15.0, this observation does not support the researchers'' hypothesis. A hypothesis about which group will perform best is supported by comparing the groups to each other, not by noting that they all fell below an arbitrary numerical threshold. Choice B is incorrect. While the control group (10.9) was indeed lower than the "Growth Mindset + Purpose" group (14.8), it was only marginally lower than the "Growth Mindset Only" group (11.2). More importantly, the researchers'' hypothesis specifically predicted that the combination group would be superior; a statement suggesting the control group was "only slightly less" persistent than both experimental groups actually tends to minimize the impact of the interventions, which would weaken rather than support the researchers'' conclusion. Choice D is incorrect because there is no data in the table or the text regarding the researchers'' numerical predictions. The SAT requires you to stay strictly within the evidence provided; you cannot assume what the researchers "expected" without explicit values.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Text 1 The International Standard Book Number (ISBN) system, established in the 1970s, has provided a robust framework for tracking global literary output. Because every published book is assigned a unique, permanent identifier, librarians and historians can effortlessly trace a text’s publication history, even across multiple decades and international borders. This rigorous standardization ensures that the bibliographic record remains a stable and reliable resource for anyone studying the evolution of print culture. Text 2 Archivists of digital-only media face a daunting task due to the "link rot" and lack of persistent identifiers common in web-based publishing. Unlike traditional print media, digital articles and databases frequently migrate to new URLs or vanish entirely when hosting platforms are restructured. Without a centralized, mandatory indexing system, the history of early internet journalism is becoming increasingly fragmented, making it nearly impossible for researchers to verify original sources or construct an accurate timeline of digital discourse. Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 1 most likely respond to the discussion in Text 2?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. By suggesting that digital archivists adopt the ISBN system to categorize websites, as this would immediately solve the problem of platforms vanishing."},{"id":"B","text":"B. By noting that the preservation challenges described in Text 2 are primarily the result of a lack of interest from the general public in digital journalism."},{"id":"C","text":"C. By observing that a specific organizational practice used in print media effectively mitigates the data loss issues currently hindering digital researchers."},{"id":"D","text":"D. By arguing that the history of print culture is more intellectually significant than the history of digital discourse due to its superior stability."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it accurately reflects the connection between the two texts. Text 1 describes how the "rigorous standardization" of the ISBN system (a specific organizational practice) creates a "stable and reliable resource" for tracing history. Text 2 describes a "daunting task" where digital history is "fragmented" because it lacks "persistent identifiers." Therefore, the author of Text 1 would likely respond by pointing out that the widespread use of standardized identifiers in their field prevents the exact problem (the inability to trace history or verify records) that the digital archivists in Text 2 are currently facing. Choice A is incorrect. While Text 1 praises the ISBN system, it does not suggest that it could be directly applied to "websites" to prevent them from "vanishing." The author mentions the ISBN tracks "literary output," but "link rot" is a technical hosting issue that a numbering system alone might not solve. Choice B is incorrect. Neither text discusses the "interest of the general public." The focus is strictly on the technical and organizational systems (or lack thereof) used by professionals to track data. Choice D is incorrect. While Text 1 describes print records as "stable," it does not make a value judgment regarding the "intellectual significance" of one medium over the other. The author of Text 1 focuses on the utility of the record-keeping system, not the inherent worth of the content.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'During the Late Cretaceous, the continent of Laramidia (now western North America) was characterized by a wide range of latitudes, from subtropical southern regions to Arctic northern regions. Paleontologists have debated whether large, herbivorous Hadrosaurids (duck-billed dinosaurs) were "residents" that lived year-round in the high-latitude Arctic or "migrants" that traveled thousands of kilometers seasonally to avoid the polar winter. Dr. Anthony Fiorillo and his colleagues hypothesized that Arctic Hadrosaurids were year-round residents. They claim that these dinosaurs possessed specific physiological adaptations—such as a specialized bone microstructure that allowed for continuous growth even during periods of low light and cold—enabling them to endure the polar winter without migrating south. Which finding, if true, would most directly support Fiorillo’s hypothesis?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Fossilized Hadrosaurid trackways found in northern Laramidia show a high density of juvenile footprints alongside those of adults, suggesting that these herds moved in large social groups."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Comparative analysis of Hadrosaurid fossils from both high-latitude and mid-latitude regions shows that the teeth of northern specimens exhibit significantly different wear patterns than those of southern specimens."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Bone histology of Arctic Hadrosaurid fossils reveals the absence of \"lines of arrested growth\" (LAGs) typically found in animals that undergo seasonal metabolic shifts or long-distance migrations to avoid resource scarcity."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Oxygen isotope analysis of Hadrosaurid tooth enamel indicates that the average body temperature of individuals found in Arctic regions was consistently higher than the surrounding ambient temperature of the Late Cretaceous Arctic winter."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. To support the hypothesis of year-round residency based on continuous growth, one must find evidence that the animal''s biological processes did not pause or slow down due to seasonal stress. In paleontology, "lines of arrested growth" (LAGs) are like tree rings that indicate a stop in growth (often due to migration or winter dormancy). The absence of these lines in Arctic specimens directly supports the claim that they maintained continuous growth and physiological activity throughout the year in the polar environment. Choice A is incorrect. While juvenile footprints suggest social behavior or a nursery area, they do not provide evidence regarding whether the group stayed in the Arctic year-round or migrated south for the winter. Choice B is incorrect. Different wear patterns on teeth suggest different diets (e.g., eating Arctic lichen vs. southern ferns), but this could be true for seasonal migrants who eat different things at different ends of their journey. It doesn''t prove year-round residency. Choice D is incorrect. While this finding suggests endothermy (the ability to maintain a high body temperature), it does not address the residency vs. migration debate. Even a warm-blooded animal might choose to migrate to follow food sources rather than stay in the dark, snowy Arctic winter.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 1, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In her pioneering research on cognitive linguistics, American scholar Lera Boroditsky has explored how the grammatical structures of different languages influence perception and reasoning. Her 2011 study How Language Shapes ______ investigates how speakers of languages with gendered nouns unconsciously assign masculine or feminine qualities to inanimate objects. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Thought—"},{"id":"B","text":"Thought,"},{"id":"C","text":"Thought:"},{"id":"D","text":"Thought"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between a subject and a verb. When, as in this case, a subject (“Her 2011 study How Language Shapes Thought”) is immediately followed by a verb (“investigates”), no punctuation is needed. Choice A is incorrect because no punctuation is needed between the subject and the verb. Choice B is incorrect because no punctuation is needed between the subject and the verb. Choice C is incorrect because no punctuation is needed between the subject and the verb.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'French photographer Yann Arthus-Bertrand is known for capturing sweeping aerial landscapes. His photograph of the Sahara _______ is part of a permanent exhibition at the Museum of Natural History in Paris. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Desert:"},{"id":"B","text":"Desert—"},{"id":"C","text":"Desert"},{"id":"D","text":"Desert,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation use between a subject and its verb. No punctuation is needed when a subject (“His photograph of the Sahara Desert”) is immediately followed by a main verb (“is part of a permanent exhibition”). Choice A is incorrect because a colon is unnecessary and interrupts the subject-verb relationship. Choice B is incorrect because an em dash is not needed between the subject and verb. Choice D is incorrect because a comma incorrectly separates the subject from its main verb.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Blending artistic precision with scientific observation, the seventeenth-century botanical illustrations of Maria Sibylla Merian revolutionized natural history by depicting insects and plants within their ecological contexts, a departure from the isolated specimens typical of her contemporaries. Her work belongs to a tradition of early scientific art _______ by its synthesis of aesthetic composition and empirical documentation, a fusion that anticipated the modern disciplines of entomology and ecology. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"has been distinguished"},{"id":"B","text":"will be distinguished"},{"id":"C","text":"distinguished"},{"id":"D","text":"is distinguished"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of finite and nonfinite verb forms within a sentence. The nonfinite past participle “distinguished” is correctly used within a modifying phrase that defines the tradition of early scientific art described in the main clause. This construction creates a concise, dependent modifier (“_______ by its synthesis...”) that adds descriptive detail without introducing a second independent clause. Choice A is incorrect because the finite present perfect verb “has been distinguished” creates a second independent clause, producing a comma splice when attached to the main clause by the comma before “by its synthesis.” Choice B is incorrect because the finite future verb “will be distinguished” also forms a second independent clause, again causing a comma splice. Choice D is incorrect because the finite present verb “is distinguished” likewise creates an additional independent clause, resulting in a comma splice that incorrectly joins two complete thoughts with only a comma.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In his acclaimed installations The Weather Project and Your Blind Passenger, artist Olafur Eliasson explored themes ________ perception, environment, and collective experience by manipulating light, color, and space and by incorporating natural elements, such as mist and sunlight, into immersive, large-scale environments. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"of"},{"id":"B","text":"of,"},{"id":"C","text":"of—"},{"id":"D","text":"of:"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between a preposition and its complement. No punctuation is needed between the preposition “of” and its complement, the noun phrase “perception, environment, and collective experience.” Choice B is incorrect because a comma cannot separate a preposition from its complement. Choice C is incorrect because a dash is unnecessary and incorrect between a preposition and its complement. Choice D is incorrect because a colon cannot follow a preposition directly; the colon would incorrectly suggest that what follows is an independent clause or an explanation rather than the complement of “of.”', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The migratory patterns of whales differ widely by species. For example, the short-finned pilot whale travels only a few hundred miles each ______ the gray whale undertakes a journey of more than ten thousand miles between feeding and breeding grounds. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"year; whereas"},{"id":"B","text":"year, whereas"},{"id":"C","text":"year whereas"},{"id":"D","text":"year. Whereas"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation with a subordinating conjunction (“whereas”) connecting two contrasting independent clauses. This choice correctly places a comma before “whereas” to join two clauses that contrast: “the short-finned pilot whale travels only a few hundred miles each year, whereas the gray whale undertakes a journey of more than ten thousand miles between feeding and breeding grounds.” Choice A is incorrect because a semicolon cannot properly precede a subordinating conjunction like “whereas”; semicolons link independent clauses not introduced by such words. Choice C is incorrect because omitting the comma before “whereas” fails to mark the boundary between the two clauses, creating a punctuation error. Choice D is incorrect because a period creates a sentence fragment: “Whereas the gray whale undertakes…” cannot stand alone as a complete sentence.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Physicist Lise Meitner, sometimes in collaboration with chemist Otto Hahn, _______ recognized for her role in the discovery of nuclear fission. Although Hahn received the 1944 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, Meitner’s contributions were essential in interpreting the experimental results and explaining the underlying physics. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"are"},{"id":"B","text":"have been"},{"id":"C","text":"are being"},{"id":"D","text":"is"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject–verb agreement. The singular verb “is recognized” agrees in number with the singular subject “physicist Lise Meitner.” Choice A is incorrect because the plural verb “are recognized” does not agree in number with the singular subject “physicist Lise Meitner.” Choice B is incorrect because the plural verb “have been recognized” does not agree in number with the singular subject. Choice C is incorrect because the plural verb “are being recognized” does not agree in number with the singular subject.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Everyone agreed that the school cafeteria served healthy meals; _______ deciding on a new menu for the coming year was more challenging. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"however"},{"id":"B","text":"however,"},{"id":"C","text":"however;"},{"id":"D","text":"however:"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of punctuation to join two main clauses with a transitional word. Choice B correctly uses a comma after the transitional word “however” to connect the first main clause (“Everyone agreed that the school cafeteria served healthy meals”) with the second main clause (“deciding on a new menu for the coming year was more challenging”), showing contrast between the two ideas. Choice A is incorrect because the word “however” needs a comma to separate it from the main clause. Choice C is incorrect because a semicolon after “however” is unnecessary and incorrect with a transitional word. Choice D is incorrect because a colon is not used to connect contrasting main clauses in this context.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A pioneering oceanographer, Sylvia Earle is celebrated for her extensive research on marine ecosystems and for leading the 1970 Tektite II project, which ______ valuable data about underwater habitats. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"produced"},{"id":"B","text":"having produced"},{"id":"C","text":"to produce"},{"id":"D","text":"producing"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the correct use of finite and nonfinite verb forms within a sentence. A main clause requires a finite verb to express the action of the subject (“the 1970 Tektite II project”), and this choice provides the finite past tense verb “produced,” indicating what the project accomplished. Choice B is incorrect because the nonfinite participle “having produced” cannot serve as the main verb of the clause. Choice C is incorrect because the infinitive form “to produce” also fails to provide a main verb. Choice D is incorrect because the present participle “producing” does not complete the clause as an independent sentence.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Expanding access to artificial intelligence is transforming the field of medicine, according to Stanford’s Fei-Fei Li. The pioneering innovations of Li, renowned for her breakthroughs in computer vision and ethical AI design,________ to the potential of inclusive technological leadership in advancing discoveries that benefit global health. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"attests"},{"id":"B","text":"has attested"},{"id":"C","text":"is attesting"},{"id":"D","text":"attest"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject-verb agreement. The plural verb “attest” agrees in number with the plural subject “ pioneering innovations .” Choice A is incorrect because the singular verb “attests” doesn’t agree in number with the plural subject “ pioneering innovations .” Choice B is incorrect because the singular verb “has attested” again doesn’t agree in number with the plural subject. Choice C is incorrect because the singular verb “is attesting” doesn’t agree in number with the plural subject “pioneering innovations.”', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In her acclaimed study Mapping the Heavens: The Radical Scientific Ideas That Reveal the Cosmos, astrophysicist Priyamvada Natarajan draws on telescope data, gravitational lensing measurements, computer simulations, and ____________ that reshaped humanity’s understanding of black holes, dark matter, and the structure of the universe. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"historical account’s to trace the discoveries"},{"id":"B","text":"historical accounts to trace the discovery’s"},{"id":"C","text":"historical accounts to trace the discoveries"},{"id":"D","text":"historical accounts’ to trace the discoveries"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of plural and possessive nouns. The plural nouns “accounts” and “discoveries” correctly indicate that the study draws on multiple historical records to trace multiple scientific findings. Choice A is incorrect because the context requires the plural noun “accounts,” not the singular possessive noun “account’s.” Choice B is incorrect because the context requires the plural noun “discoveries,” not the singular possessive noun “discovery’s.” Choice D is incorrect because the context requires the plural noun “accounts,” not the plural possessive noun “accounts’.”', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Consider the process of sound localization: the brain determines the direction of a sound based on subtle differences in timing and intensity between the ears. A diagram of auditory pathways reveals how this ________ sound waves reach each ear at slightly different times and volumes, the brain can pinpoint the source of the sound, allowing precise spatial awareness. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"works because"},{"id":"B","text":"works. Because"},{"id":"C","text":"works, it’s because"},{"id":"D","text":"works: it’s because"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation use between sentences. In this choice, the period is used to correctly mark the boundary between one sentence (“A diagram…reveals how this works”) and another (“Because sound waves…awareness”). Choice A is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence: the two sentences are fused without proper punctuation or conjunction. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a comma splice; a comma cannot properly connect these two main clauses. Choice D is incorrect because the colon followed by “it’s” creates an improper clause structure, resulting in a punctuation error between two independent ideas.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In a 2012 study at Columbia University, psychologist Daniel Kahneman analyzed how people evaluate experiences that contain both pleasure and discomfort. The participants’ final judgments of enjoyment depended on one key______ they rated the overall experience higher when it ended pleasantly, even if earlier moments had been unpleasant. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"factor,"},{"id":"B","text":"factor:"},{"id":"C","text":"factor, since"},{"id":"D","text":"factor since"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of a colon within a sentence. In this choice, the colon is used in a conventional way to introduce the following explanation of what the one key factor was—how participants rated the experience based on how it ended. Choice A is incorrect because it creates a comma splice. A comma can’t be used in this way to join two main clauses (“the participants’ final judgments…depended on one key factor” and “they rated…”). Choice C is incorrect because it results in an illogical and confusing sentence. Using the conjunction “since” to join the main clause (“depended on one key factor”) with the following clause’s description implies an incorrect causal relationship. Choice D is incorrect because it results in an illogical and confusing sentence. Using “since” in this way suggests that the dependence occurred during the time when participants rated experiences, but the sentence clearly indicates that what follows “factor” is a description of that factor, not a separate, simultaneous event.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'During the Harlem Renaissance, a number of literary journals emerged to showcase the work of African American writers and artists. Among the most influential of these publications ______ The Crisis, edited by W. E. B. Du Bois. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"was"},{"id":"B","text":"were"},{"id":"C","text":"are"},{"id":"D","text":"have been"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject–verb agreement in sentences beginning with “among” or “there.” Although the plural noun phrase “the most influential of these publications” might tempt readers to choose a plural verb, the true subject of the clause is the singular noun The Crisis. Therefore, the singular verb “was” correctly agrees with the singular subject. Choice B is incorrect because the plural verb “were” does not agree with the singular subject The Crisis. Choice C is incorrect because the present tense verb “are” fails to match the past time frame indicated by “During the Harlem Renaissance.” Choice D is incorrect because the present perfect verb “have been” also conflicts with the past context and pluralizes the verb unnecessarily.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'According to oceanographer Silvia Macias of the University of Cádiz, the reason microscopic plastic fragments can remain suspended in seawater while ______ is that their irregular surfaces increase drag, preventing them from settling on the ocean floor. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"drifting,"},{"id":"B","text":"drifting:"},{"id":"C","text":"drifting;"},{"id":"D","text":"drifting"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of a participial phrase within a sentence. In this choice, no punctuation is needed between “while” and “is” because the clause “while drifting” functions as part of the larger grammatical structure and should not be separated by a comma, colon, or semicolon. Choice A is incorrect because a comma after “drifting” would incorrectly separate the dependent clause (“while drifting”) from its verb (“is”), disrupting the sentence’s grammatical flow. Choice B is incorrect because a colon cannot grammatically follow a subordinating conjunction like “while.” Choice C is incorrect because a semicolon separates two independent clauses, but “while drifting” is not an independent clause.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Like many species adapted to arid environments, the Gila monster (Heloderma suspectum) relies on specialized physiological mechanisms to endure seasonal scarcity. During prolonged droughts, when prey becomes scarce and surface temperatures soar, the lizard _______ by metabolizing fat stored in its tail, a process that provides both energy and water. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"had survived"},{"id":"B","text":"survived"},{"id":"C","text":"would survive"},{"id":"D","text":"survives"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the correct use of verb tense to describe general scientific facts and biological adaptations. The simple present tense verb “survives” is appropriate because the sentence explains a recurring, characteristic behavior of the Gila monster rather than a single historical event. Scientific and factual statements are conventionally expressed in the present tense to indicate their ongoing validity. Choice A is incorrect because the past perfect “had survived” refers to an action completed before another past event, which does not fit a general description. Choice B is incorrect because the simple past “survived” limits the statement to a specific period rather than expressing a general truth. Choice C is incorrect because “would survive” suggests a hypothetical or conditional scenario, not an established physiological process.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the historical novel The Book Thief, German author Markus Zusak uses a unique narrative perspective rather than a traditional first-person narrator ____ the story of Liesel Meminger’s experiences during World War II. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"tells"},{"id":"B","text":"told"},{"id":"C","text":"is telling"},{"id":"D","text":"to tell"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of finite and nonfinite verb forms within a sentence. The nonfinite to-infinitive “to tell” is correctly used to form a nonfinite clause that explains the reason Zusak uses a unique narrative perspective in his novel. Choice A is incorrect because the finite present tense verb “tells” cannot be used in this way to explain the purpose of the narrative perspective. Choice B is incorrect because the finite past tense verb “told” cannot be used in this way to explain the reason for the narrative choice. Choice C is incorrect because the finite present progressive verb “is telling” cannot be used in this way to indicate purpose.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Egyptian architect Hassan Fathy’s Architecture for the Poor (1973), a manifesto advocating for sustainable, community-centered building design, _______ the ways scholars and urban planners think about environmental responsibility in architecture. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"has transformed"},{"id":"B","text":"are transforming"},{"id":"C","text":"have transformed"},{"id":"D","text":"transform"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject–verb agreement. The singular subject “Architecture for the Poor” requires a singular verb. Choice A correctly uses the present perfect singular verb “has transformed”, which conveys that Fathy’s work continues to influence architectural thinking from its publication to the present. Choice B is incorrect because the plural verb “are transforming” does not agree with the singular subject. Choice C is incorrect because the plural verb “have transformed” also fails to agree with the singular subject. Choice D is incorrect because the plural verb “transform” does not agree in number with the singular subject and fails to capture the ongoing influence implied by the context.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Electrons in a cathode-ray tube accelerate rapidly until they ______ a fluorescent screen, causing the screen to glow and produce an image. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"will strike"},{"id":"B","text":"strike"},{"id":"C","text":"had struck"},{"id":"D","text":"are striking"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the correct use of verb tense to describe scientific facts or processes. The simple present tense verb “strike” appropriately indicates a general truth—something that happens whenever electrons accelerate in this way. Scientific descriptions of repeated or universal phenomena are conventionally expressed in the present tense. Choice A is incorrect because the future tense verb “will strike” suggests a specific future event rather than a general process. Choice C is incorrect because the past perfect verb “had struck” implies an action completed before another past action, which does not fit the general, ongoing description of the phenomenon. Choice D is incorrect because the present progressive verb “are striking” implies an action happening right now, not a general scientific fact.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Early automobiles were powered by steam engines, which required frequent water refills. Steam-powered cars were common in the late nineteenth _______ they were eventually replaced by gasoline-powered vehicles. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"century"},{"id":"B","text":"century,"},{"id":"C","text":"century, but"},{"id":"D","text":"century that"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the coordination of main clauses within a sentence. Choice C correctly uses a comma and the coordinating conjunction “but” to join the first main clause (“Steam-powered cars were common in the late nineteenth century”) and the second main clause (“they were eventually replaced by gasoline-powered vehicles”). Choice A is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence, fusing two independent clauses without punctuation or a conjunction. Choice B is incorrect because it creates a comma splice, joining two main clauses with only a comma and no conjunction. Choice D is incorrect because using “that” introduces a subordinating clause, which creates an ungrammatical and illogical sentence in this context.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Although honeybees rely on ultraviolet light patterns to locate flowers, many species can also detect electric fields around blossoms. A 2021 experiment ______ how bees use these electric cues to distinguish between flowers that contain nectar and those that do not. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"demonstrates"},{"id":"B","text":"demonstrating"},{"id":"C","text":"having demonstrated"},{"id":"D","text":"to demonstrate"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the correct use of verb tense and clause structure. The main clause (“A 2021 experiment ______ how bees use these electric cues…”) requires a finite verb to complete the sentence, and the present tense verb “demonstrates” correctly describes a recent scientific finding that remains valid at present. In academic or scientific contexts, writers often use the present tense to convey the continuing relevance of research results. Choice B is incorrect because the present participle “demonstrating” cannot function as the main verb of the sentence. Choice C is incorrect because the perfect participle “having demonstrated” also fails to supply a main verb. Choice D is incorrect because the infinitive “to demonstrate” does not complete the clause grammatically.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2015, marine biologist Dr. Sahana Rao was studying coral reefs off the coast of Belize when she observed unusual patterns of bleaching on several coral colony _______ careful laboratory analysis, she determined that a combination of rising water temperatures and ocean acidification was responsible for the damage. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"surfaces, and with"},{"id":"B","text":"surfaces with"},{"id":"C","text":"surfaces so with"},{"id":"D","text":"surfaces. With"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation use between sentences. The period after “surfaces” is used correctly to mark the boundary between the first sentence (“In 2015…on several coral colony surfaces”) and the second sentence (“With careful laboratory analysis…was responsible for the damage”), which begins with a supplementary phrase. Choice A is incorrect because it creates a comma splice. A comma cannot be used to join two independent clauses in this way. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence. The two clauses are fused without proper punctuation or a conjunction. Choice C is incorrect because, without a comma preceding “so,” the conjunction cannot correctly join the two clauses.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'For centuries, artisans in West Africa ______ indigo dye extracted from plants to color cloth, creating textiles of remarkable depth and beauty. Historical records suggest that the techniques for preparing the dye were passed down through generations of skilled families. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"to use"},{"id":"B","text":"have used"},{"id":"C","text":"having used"},{"id":"D","text":"using"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the distinction between finite and nonfinite verb forms within a sentence. A main clause requires a finite verb to express the action of the subject (“artisans in West Africa”), and this choice provides the finite present perfect verb “have used” to indicate what these artisans did over time. Choice A is incorrect because the infinitive “to use” cannot serve as the main verb of the clause. Choice C is incorrect because the perfect participle “having used” does not supply a finite verb needed to complete the clause. Choice D is incorrect because the present participle “using” also fails to function as the main verb of the sentence.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79 CE buried the Roman cities of Pompeii and Herculaneum under layers of ash and pumice. For centuries afterward, these sites _______ undisturbed until their rediscovery in the eighteenth century. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"remain"},{"id":"B","text":"remained"},{"id":"C","text":"will remain"},{"id":"D","text":"are remaining"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of verb tense to indicate time. In this choice, the past tense verb “remained” correctly indicates that the cities stayed undisturbed for centuries following the eruption, an event that occurred in the distant past. Choice A is incorrect because the present tense “remain” implies that the sites are still undisturbed, which is inconsistent with their rediscovery in the eighteenth century. Choice C is incorrect because the future tense “will remain” suggests the cities will stay undisturbed in the future, which does not align with the past time frame. Choice D is incorrect because the present progressive “are remaining” implies an ongoing action in the present, conflicting with the historical context of the sentence.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the 1920s, an engineer named John Logie Baird was experimenting with ways to transmit moving images electronically when his colleague William Taynton assisted him in testing the first working television system. In addition, Taynton ______ appearing in Baird’s earliest public demonstrations of the invention. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"volunteered"},{"id":"B","text":"volunteers"},{"id":"C","text":"had volunteered"},{"id":"D","text":"was volunteering"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The simple past tense “volunteered” correctly indicates that Taynton’s participation occurred in the same general period as Baird’s experiments, aligning with the past tense “was experimenting” used earlier. Choice B is incorrect because the present tense “volunteers” does not refer to a past event. Choice C is incorrect because “had volunteered” incorrectly suggests that volunteering took place before another past action, which is not supported by the context. Choice D is incorrect because “wa', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The modern strategy game Settlers of Catan is a reimagining of older resource-trading games developed in nineteenth-century Germany. In both, players advance their positions by acquiring essential materials; successfully negotiating a trade with another player ________ one to expand territories and move closer to overall victory. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"allows"},{"id":"B","text":"are allowing"},{"id":"C","text":"have allowed"},{"id":"D","text":"allow"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject–verb agreement. The singular verb “allows” agrees in number with the singular subject “negotiating” (“successfully negotiating a trade with another player allows one to expand…”). Choice B is incorrect because the plural progressive verb “are allowing” does not agree with the singular subject “negotiating.” Choice C is incorrect because the plural perfect verb “have allowed” does not agree with the singular subject “negotiating.” Choice D is incorrect because the plural verb “allow” does not agree with the singular subject “negotiating.”', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Archaeologists recently uncovered a network of limestone tunnels beneath the ruins of Teotihuacán, once the largest city in pre-Columbian Mesoamerica. Believed to have served as a ritual passageway for priests and rulers, ________ obsidian, and seashells arranged along its walls. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"the tunnels are lined with offerings of jade,"},{"id":"B","text":"the tunnels, lined with offerings of jade,"},{"id":"C","text":"the tunnels, are lined with offerings of jade"},{"id":"D","text":"the tunnels lined with offerings of jade,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is sentence completeness and punctuation between an introductory modifier and a main clause. The phrase “Believed to have served as a ritual passageway for priests and rulers” is an introductory participial phrase that must be followed by a complete independent clause. Choice A provides that clause with the subject “the tunnels” and the verb “are lined,” forming a complete, grammatically correct sentence. Choice B is incorrect because it produces a sentence fragment, lacking a main verb. The phrase “the tunnels, lined with offerings of jade,” does not express a complete thought. Choice C is incorrect because the comma before “are lined” incorrectly separates the subject from its verb, violating standard punctuation conventions. Choice D is incorrect because it also forms a fragment; “lined” functions as a past participle, not a main verb, so the sentence lacks a complete predicate. Choice A is therefore correct because it creates a complete and properly punctuated sentence while maintaining the logical connection between the introductory phrase and the main clause.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Themes of memory and identity frequently appear in Kazuo Ishiguro’s novels. In The Remains of the Day, for instance, the narrator Stevens reflects on his past decisions with quiet regret, while in Never Let Me Go, the character of Kathy ______ her memories as a way of understanding who she is. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"examined"},{"id":"B","text":"had examined"},{"id":"C","text":"examines"},{"id":"D","text":"will be examining"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of verb tense. The present tense verb “examines” is consistent with the other present tense verbs (“reflects,” “appears”) used to describe events and themes in Ishiguro’s novels. It is conventional to use the present tense when discussing the content of literary works. Choice A is incorrect because the past tense verb “examined” is inconsistent with the present tense context. Choice B is incorrect because the past perfect verb “had examined” implies an event completed before another past event, which doesn’t fit this literary discussion. Choice D is incorrect because the future progressive verb “will be examining” is inconsistent with the present tense narrative convention used to describe literature.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Compared to that of terrestrial plants, _______ the algae receive so little sunlight that they must rely on alternative chemical reactions to survive. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"deep-sea algae are at a significant limitation due to their far less efficient photosynthetic process:"},{"id":"B","text":"deep-sea algae have a far less efficient photosynthetic process, resulting in a significant limitation:"},{"id":"C","text":"a significant limitation of deep-sea algae is that their photosynthetic process is far less efficient:"},{"id":"D","text":"deep-sea algae’s photosynthetic process is far less efficient, resulting in a significant limitation:"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject–modifier placement. This choice makes “deep-sea algae’s photosynthetic process” the subject of the sentence and places it immediately after the modifying phrase “compared to that of terrestrial plants.” In doing so, this choice clearly establishes that deep-sea algae’s photosynthetic process—and not another noun in the sentence—is being compared to the photosynthetic process (“that”) of terrestrial plants. Choice A is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “deep-sea algae” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the algae themselves (rather than their photosynthetic process) are being compared to the photosynthetic process of terrestrial plants. Choice B is incorrect because it produces the same error: the noun “deep-sea algae” appears directly after the modifying phrase, suggesting an illogical comparison between algae and photosynthetic process. Choice C is incorrect because it also results in a dangling modifier. The noun phrase “a significant limitation” immediately following the modifier incorrectly implies that a limitation is being compared to the photosynthetic process of terrestrial plants.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'American physicists Richard Feynman and Murray Gell-Mann won the Nobel Prize in part for their groundbreaking work on quantum electrodynamics, but it is inaccurate to say that Feynman and Gell-Mann developed the entire theory independently. _______ insights were built upon earlier calculations and experiments conducted by scientists such as Julian Schwinger and Sin-Itiro Tomonaga. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"They’re"},{"id":"B","text":"It’s"},{"id":"C","text":"Their"},{"id":"D","text":"Its"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of possessive determiners. The plural possessive determiner “their” agrees in number with the plural conjoined noun phrase “Feynman and Gell-Mann” and correctly indicates that the insights were those of Feynman and Gell-Mann. Choice A is incorrect because “they’re” is a contraction for “they are,” not a possessive determiner. Choice B is incorrect because “it’s” is a contraction for “it is” or “it has,” not a possessive determiner. Choice D is incorrect because the singular possessive determiner “its” does not agree in number with the plural conjoined noun phrase “Feynman and Gell-Mann.”', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Psychologists Eleanor Maguire and Katherine Woollett examined how extensive navigation training affects the human brain. In their 2011 study of London taxi drivers, they sought to determine how _______ when mastering complex spatial environments. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"do people’s brains adapt to new spatial demands."},{"id":"B","text":"do people’s brains adapt to new spatial demands?"},{"id":"C","text":"people’s brains adapt to new spatial demands?"},{"id":"D","text":"people’s brains adapt to new spatial demands."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is end-of-sentence punctuation. This choice correctly uses a period to punctuate a declarative sentence that asks an indirect question (“they sought to determine how people’s brains adapt to new spatial demands”). Choice A is incorrect. The structure of the sentence requires a declarative clause at the end that reports what Maguire and Woollett investigated, not an interrogative clause that asks a direct question such as “how do people’s brains adapt to new spatial demands.” Choice B is incorrect. The structure of the sentence requires a declarative clause, not a direct question ending with a question mark, such as “how do people’s brains adapt to new spatial demands?” Choice C is incorrect. It is unconventional to use a question mark to punctuate a declarative sentence that asks an indirect question, such as “they sought to determine how people’s brains adapt to new spatial demands.”', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The literary accomplishments of Toni Morrison, best known for her 1987 novel Beloved and the critical discourse it generated, _______ confined to fiction: she first distinguished herself as an editor, where her commitment to nurturing African American voices—a practice she described as “essential for cultural preservation”—shaped her enduring influence on American letters. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. hasn’t been"},{"id":"B","text":"B. wasn’t"},{"id":"C","text":"C. isn’t"},{"id":"D","text":"D. aren’t"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The subject “accomplishments” is plural, and so is the verb “aren’t”: “The literary accomplishments…aren’t confined.” Choice A is incorrect because the plural subject “accomplishments” does not agree with the singular verb “hasn’t been.” Choice B is incorrect because the plural subject “accomplishments” does not agree with the singular past-tense verb “wasn’t.” Choice C is incorrect because the plural subject “accomplishments” does not agree with the singular verb “isn’t.”', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Building upon decades of research in quantum information theory, physicist John Preskill—who coined the term quantum supremacy—formulated a framework describing how entangled qubits could outperform classical processors in certain computational tasks, _______ a paradigm that continues to challenge long-held assumptions about the limits of algorithmic efficiency. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"to propose"},{"id":"B","text":"proposing"},{"id":"C","text":"proposed"},{"id":"D","text":"and proposing"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of finite and nonfinite verb forms within a sentence. The nonfinite to-infinitive “to propose” is correctly used to form an infinitive clause that explains why Preskill formulated the framework—namely, to propose a paradigm that continues to challenge assumptions about computational limits. Choice B is incorrect. Without a comma separating the main clause (“physicist John Preskill…classical processors”) from the participle “proposing,” this choice illogically suggests that the framework itself is proposing a paradigm, which is nonsensical. Choice C is incorrect. Without a coordinating conjunction such as “and” preceding it, the finite past-tense verb “proposed” cannot be used to connect grammatically with the earlier finite verb “formulated.” Choice D is incorrect. If read as a finite verb, the present participle “proposing” is inconsistent with the past-tense verbs used elsewhere in the sentence to describe Preskill’s actions. If read as a nonfinite verb, the participle “proposing” cannot be used in this way because there is no following main clause for it to modify.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Ornithologists Priya Nair and Alejandro Vargas have investigated why certain migratory birds deviate from their expected flight paths during seasonal journeys. Observing that birds rely on geomagnetic cues to navigate, ________ Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. the researchers propose that urban light pollution disrupts these natural signals, causing the birds to adjust their headings repeatedly while passing over illuminated cityscapes."},{"id":"B","text":"B. the researchers’ theory is that urban light pollution interferes with geomagnetic cues, causing migratory birds to repeatedly adjust their flight paths over illuminated cityscapes."},{"id":"C","text":"C. urban light pollution interferes with geomagnetic cues and causes migratory birds to repeatedly adjust their flight paths over illuminated cityscapes, the researchers theorize."},{"id":"D","text":"D. migratory birds repeatedly adjust their flight paths over illuminated cityscapes, the researchers theorize, because urban light pollution interferes with geomagnetic cues."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject-modifier placement. This choice makes the noun phrase “the researchers” the subject of the sentence and places it immediately after the modifying phrase “observing that birds rely on geomagnetic cues to navigate.” In doing so, this choice clearly establishes that the researchers—and not another noun in the sentence—observe and interpret the effects of urban light pollution on migratory birds. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “the researchers’ theory” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the theory itself observes that birds rely on geomagnetic cues. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun “urban light pollution” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the pollution observes that birds rely on geomagnetic cues. Choice D is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun “migratory birds” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the birds themselves observe that they rely on geomagnetic cues.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Philosopher John Rawls’s 1971 work A Theory of Justice transformed modern political thought with its arguments for fairness and equality, while later scholars, such as Amartya Sen and Martha Nussbaum, ______ these ideas to develop broader frameworks of human capability and well-being. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"were expanding"},{"id":"B","text":"have expanded"},{"id":"C","text":"had expanded"},{"id":"D","text":"expand"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is verb tense to indicate time relationships between past and continuing actions. The present perfect tense verb “have expanded” correctly shows that Sen and Nussbaum’s engagement with Rawls’s ideas began after the publication of A Theory of Justice and continues to influence contemporary discussions. This tense links past intellectual developments to their ongoing relevance. Choice A is incorrect because the past progressive “were expanding” suggests an action happening simultaneously with Rawls’s work in 1971, which distorts the timeline. Choice C is incorrect because the past perfect “had expanded” implies their work was completed before Rawls’s, which is logically inconsistent. Choice D is incorrect because the simple present “expand” would suggest that the action occurs universally or habitually, not as an ongoing intellectual development rooted in past scholarship.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While giving his report, Dr. Ellison carefully avoided the _____________________ the committee members shifted in their seats, glancing at one another—anywhere but at the head researcher. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"chairmen’s gaze;"},{"id":"B","text":"chairman’s gaze;"},{"id":"C","text":"chairman’s gaze:"},{"id":"D","text":"chairmen’s gaze,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of supplementary elements within a sentence. This choice correctly uses a semicolon to separate two independent clauses: the main clause (“Dr. Ellison carefully avoided the chairman’s gaze”) and the second clause describing the committee members’ actions (“the committee members shifted in their seats, glancing at one another—anywhere but at the head researcher”). The apostrophe placement correctly indicates singular possession, referring to the gaze of a single chairman. Choice A is incorrect because “chairmen’s” indicates plural possession, which does not match the singular chairman in the sentence. Choice C is incorrect because a colon is not conventionally used to join two independent clauses in this context. Choice D is incorrect because “chairmen’s” is plural and the comma does not correctly link two independent clauses.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In Kara Walker’s 1997 installation Darkytown Rebellion, absent are the overtly historical references that characterized the artist’s earlier silhouettes. In _______ place is a deeply psychological focus: shadowy cutouts depicting complex narratives of power, race, and identity. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"its"},{"id":"B","text":"they’re"},{"id":"C","text":"their"},{"id":"D","text":"it’s"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of possessive determiners. The plural possessive determiner “their” agrees in number with the plural noun “references” and thus indicates that the more personal, psychologically focused subject matter of Walker’s 1997 installation takes the place of the historical references in her earlier work. Choice A is incorrect because the singular possessive determiner “its” does not agree in number with the plural noun “references.” Choice B is incorrect because “they’re” is a contraction for “they are,” not a possessive determiner. Choice D is incorrect because “it’s” is a contraction for “it is” or “it has,” not a possessive determiner.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'When Japan introduced high-speed rail service in 1964, the country’s average travel time between major cities dropped by nearly half _______ rapid transit became a defining feature of Japan’s postwar modernization and technological identity. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":", and the"},{"id":"B","text":"; the"},{"id":"C","text":". The"},{"id":"D","text":", the"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between two independent clauses. This choice correctly uses a period to separate two complete sentences: “When Japan introduced high-speed rail service in 1964, the country’s average travel time between major cities dropped by nearly half” and “The rapid transit became a defining feature of Japan’s postwar modernization and technological identity.” Each clause has its own subject and verb, so they must be divided by terminal punctuation. Choice A is incorrect because “, and the” unnecessarily uses a coordinating conjunction, making the sentence wordy and stylistically weaker. Choice B is incorrect because a semicolon here would incorrectly connect clauses whose relationship is better expressed with a clear stop rather than a close link; stylistically, “The rapid transit…” begins a new idea. Choice D is incorrect because the comma alone creates a comma splice, joining two independent clauses without appropriate punctuation or a conjunction.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The Monterey Bay Aquarium in the United States and the Okinawa Churaumi Aquarium in Japan are two of many marine institutions around the world dedicated to showcasing ocean _______ supporting marine conservation research; and educating the public about the importance of protecting aquatic ecosystems. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"biodiversity, both local and global,"},{"id":"B","text":"biodiversity, both local and global;"},{"id":"C","text":"biodiversity; both local and global,"},{"id":"D","text":"biodiversity both local and global,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of items in a complex series (a series including internal punctuation). The semicolon after “global” is correctly used to separate the first item (“showcasing ocean biodiversity, both local and global”) and the second item (“supporting marine conservation research”) in the series of things that marine institutions are dedicated to. Further, the comma after “biodiversity” is correctly used to separate the noun phrase “ocean biodiversity” and the supplementary phrase “both local and global” that modifies it. Choice A is incorrect because a comma (specifically, the comma after “global”) can’t be used in this way to separate items in a complex series. Choice C is incorrect because a semicolon can’t be used in this way to separate the noun phrase “ocean biodiversity” and the supplementary phrase “both local and global” that modifies it. Further, a comma can’t be used in this way to separate items in a complex series. Choice D is incorrect because it fails to use appropriate punctuation to separate the noun phrase “ocean biodiversity” and the supplementary phrase “both local and global” that modifies it. Further, a comma can’t be used in this way to separate items in a complex series.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The first rays of dawn had just broken over the city, and the few early risers wandering the quiet streets were abruptly interrupted by the sound of sirens, as a police officer hurried past, shouting, “Clear the area! Let no one enter! A fire has _________ to approach the building.” Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"erupted, and nobody’s"},{"id":"B","text":"erupted, and nobodies"},{"id":"C","text":"erupted, and nobody is"},{"id":"D","text":"erupted, and nobodies"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is correct coordination of clauses and subject-verb agreement. The first clause, “A fire has erupted,” is correctly linked with “and nobody is to approach the building,” forming a grammatically correct compound sentence. Choice A is incorrect because “nobody’s” incorrectly contracts “nobody is” in this formal context and creates an awkward dependent clause. Choice B is incorrect because “nobodies” is not standard English. Choice D is incorrect for the same reason: “nobodies” is not correct usage.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'With a sigh of satisfaction, Captain Reynolds stepped back onto the deck and, warding off the eager questions of the sailors who had been too hesitant to climb the ____________ toward the helm to assume command of the ship. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"rigging—moved deliberately"},{"id":"B","text":"rigging moved deliberately"},{"id":"C","text":"rigging moved deliberately,"},{"id":"D","text":"rigging, moved deliberately"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is correct coordination of clauses and punctuation for nonessential information. The phrase starting with “warding off” and ending with “rigging” is extra information that is not crucial to the main structure of the sentence. Such nonessential phrases should be set off with commas, dashes, or parentheses. Since there is a comma before “warding off,” a comma after “rigging” correctly brackets the phrase, allowing the main clause “Captain Reynolds…moved deliberately toward the helm” to remain grammatically complete. Choice A is incorrect because the em dash is unnecessary and changes the tone, making it less formal. Choice B is incorrect because omitting punctuation creates a confusing and run-on structure. Choice C is incorrect because placing a comma after “moved deliberately” does not properly set off the nonessential phrase and interrupts the flow of the main clause.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the history of Caribbean literature, Jamaican author Marlon James’s 2015 novel A Brief History of Seven Killings commands attention. A historical epic, a political exposé, and a penetrating exploration of violence and identity, _________ confronts social inequities with striking narrative force. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The novel, spanning decades of Jamaican history,"},{"id":"B","text":"B. James’s work, which spans decades of Jamaican history,"},{"id":"C","text":"C. Marlon James wrote a novel that, spanning decades of Jamaican history,"},{"id":"D","text":"D. Spanning decades of Jamaican history, Marlon James wrote a novel that"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. Subject-modifier placement requires a modifier and its subject to be next to each other. The subject of the modifier “A historical epic, a political exposé, and a penetrating exploration of violence and identity” is Marlon James’s novel A Brief History of Seven Killings, so the subject “James’s work” fits perfectly after this introductory modifying phrase. Choice A is incorrect. Modifiers and their subjects must go next to each other. The introductory modifier describes the novel, not “The novel” as a general term in isolation, which creates slight ambiguity in emphasis. Choice C is incorrect. Placing “Marlon James wrote a novel that” after the modifier incorrectly shifts focus from the novel itself to the author, breaking the intended modifier-subject connection. Choice D is incorrect. The modifier describes the novel, but this choice places the author, Marlon James, immediately after the modifier, which misaligns the descriptive focus from the novel to the author.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'For several tense hours the deliberations of the council produced little clarity. The ambassador was circumspect—more circumspect far than customary—and the aides, constrained to disclose any details beyond the official communiqué, offered only cautious speculations to offer. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"customary—and the aides, constrained"},{"id":"B","text":"customary,and the aides, constrained"},{"id":"C","text":"customary—and the aides—constrained"},{"id":"D","text":"customary, and the aides—constrained"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the correct use of punctuation to set off nonessential phrases. The phrase “more circumspect far than customary” is extra information and is correctly enclosed with em dashes. The second nonessential phrase, “the aides, constrained to disclose any details beyond the official communiqué,” is properly set off with commas, maintaining clarity while keeping the sentence grammatically complete.Choice B is incorrect because the missing space after the comma and lack of em dash disrupt proper punctuation and make the sentence confusing.Choice C is incorrect because using em dashes around “the aides—constrained” unnecessarily emphasizes the phrase and changes the formal tone. Choice D is incorrect because the combination of a comma and em dash incorrectly punctuates the nonessential phrases, breaking the flow of the sentence.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Established in 1975 to promote economic cooperation among oil-exporting countries, the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) originally included twelve member nations. By the early 2000s, the organization ______ its membership to include several additional states. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"has expanded"},{"id":"B","text":"had expanded"},{"id":"C","text":"expands"},{"id":"D","text":"will expand"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of verb tense to indicate the proper sequence of past events. The past perfect verb “had expanded” correctly shows that the expansion of OPEC’s membership occurred before a later time reference (“by the early 2000s”). Choice A is incorrect because the present perfect verb “has expanded” suggests that the expansion continues into the present, which conflicts with the past time frame of the sentence. Choice C is incorrect because the simple present verb “expands” fails to indicate that the action occurred in the past. Choice D is incorrect because the future tense “will expand” implies an event that has not yet occurred, which is inconsistent with the time marker “by the early 2000s.”', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Materials scientist Dr. Keiko Aramura developed a nanoscale filtration membrane by layering strands of graphene oxide along a titanium substrate and embedding catalytic nanoparticles between the ______ After the polymerization process was complete, the resulting structure displayed exceptional selectivity for separating ions in high-salinity environments. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"strands’ lattice’s."},{"id":"B","text":"strand’s lattices."},{"id":"C","text":"strand’s lattice’s."},{"id":"D","text":"strands lattices’."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of plural and possessive nouns. The singular possessive noun “strand’s” and the plural noun “lattices” correctly indicate that there is only one strand and it has multiple lattice structures within it. Choice A is incorrect because the context requires the singular possessive noun “strand’s,” not the plural possessive noun “strands’.” Choice C is incorrect because the context requires the plural noun “lattices,” not the singular possessive noun “lattice’s.” Choice D is incorrect because the context requires the singular possessive noun “strand’s” and the plural noun “lattices,” not the plural noun “strands” or the plural possessive noun “lattices’.”', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Although widely available, inexpensive, and lightweight, ________ they can leach into waterways, causing nutrient pollution, and their overuse can degrade soil health over time. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. there are two problems associated with synthetic fertilizers:"},{"id":"B","text":"B. two problems are associated with synthetic fertilizers:"},{"id":"C","text":"C. synthetic fertilizers’ two associated problems are that"},{"id":"D","text":"D. synthetic fertilizers have two associated problems:"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject-modifier placement. This choice ensures that the modifying phrase “although widely available, inexpensive, and lightweight” appears immediately before the noun it modifies, “synthetic fertilizers,” clearly establishing that the fertilizers—and not another noun in the sentence—are being described as widely available, inexpensive, and lightweight. Choice A is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the function word “there” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that “there” is widely available, inexpensive, and lightweight. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun “two problems” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the “problems” are widely available, inexpensive, and lightweight. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “synthetic fertilizers’ two associated problems” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the “problems” are widely available, inexpensive, and lightweight.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Photographer Vik Muniz’s mixed-media works span an impressive variety of materials and scales. In 2008, Muniz assembled tiny fragments of magazine paper to recreate classic paintings on _______ in 2016, he used thousands of discarded plastic objects to construct a massive mural, later photographing it from above to transform it into a striking commentary on consumer waste. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"canvas later,"},{"id":"B","text":"canvas;"},{"id":"C","text":"canvas,"},{"id":"D","text":"canvas, later,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the coordination of main clauses within a sentence. This choice uses a semicolon correctly to join the two independent clauses: the first (“In 2008...canvas”) and the second (“in 2016...waste”). Choice A is incorrect because it results in a comma splice. The adverb “later” cannot connect two independent clauses without a conjunction. Choice C is incorrect for the same reason—it joins two complete sentences with just a comma, which is grammatically incorrect. Choice D is also incorrect because it still creates a comma splice; “later” functions as an adverb, not a conjunction, and cannot by itself join two main clauses.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The ancient city of Machu Picchu, which was abandoned in the 16th century and rediscovered in 1911, continues to be studied by historians and archaeologists. Unfortunately, as ______ attest, preservation efforts and tourist activity have altered the site, threatening valuable information about Inca architecture and culture. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"experts, Hiram Bingham and Julio C. Tello,"},{"id":"B","text":"experts, Hiram Bingham and Julio C. Tello"},{"id":"C","text":"experts Hiram Bingham and Julio C. Tello"},{"id":"D","text":"experts Hiram Bingham, and Julio C. Tello"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of restrictive appositive phrases. In this sentence, the names “Hiram Bingham and Julio C. Tello” are essential to identify which experts are being referenced. Because the appositive is restrictive, it should not be set off with commas. Choice A is incorrect because the commas make the appositive nonrestrictive, implying that the specific experts are additional, nonessential information, which changes the intended meaning of the sentence. Choice B is incorrect for the same reason—it treats the appositive as nonrestrictive and fails to reflect that the names are essential to identify the experts. Choice D is incorrect because the comma before “and Julio C. Tello” incorrectly separates elements of the essential appositive, creating a grammatical error.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'American inventors Orville and Wilbur Wright are celebrated for achieving the first powered flight in 1903, but it is inaccurate to claim that the Wright brothers invented flight itself. _______ innovation built upon decades of aerodynamic research conducted by earlier pioneers such as Otto Lilienthal and Octave Chanute. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"They’re"},{"id":"B","text":"It’s"},{"id":"C","text":"Their"},{"id":"D","text":"Its"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the proper use of possessive determiners. The plural possessive determiner “their” correctly agrees in number with the plural compound subject “Orville and Wilbur Wright” and indicates that the innovation belonged to both brothers. Choice A is incorrect because “they’re” is a contraction of “they are,” not a possessive determiner. Choice B is incorrect because “it’s” is a contraction of “it is” or “it has,” not a possessive form. Choice D is incorrect because “its” is singular and does not agree in number with the plural compound subject “Orville and Wilbur Wright.”', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Dubbed the planet’s “hidden lungs,” mangrove forests are dense coastal ecosystems supported by salt-tolerant trees, shrubs, and specialized root systems. Stabilizing shorelines in tropical regions against storm surges, ________ Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. recent research indicates that these forests sequester carbon at rates up to four times higher than terrestrial forests."},{"id":"B","text":"B. an estimated fourfold increase in carbon sequestration compared with terrestrial forests is achieved by these forests, according to recent research."},{"id":"C","text":"C. these forests sequester carbon at rates up to four times higher than terrestrial forests, according to recent research."},{"id":"D","text":"D. recent research has found that these forests sequester carbon at rates up to four times higher than terrestrial forests."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The subject of the modifier "stabilizing shorelines in tropical regions against storm surges" is "mangrove forests." Subject-modifier placement requires a modifier and its subject to be next to each other, so "mangrove forests" or some variant meaning "mangrove forests" (in this case, "these forests") must begin the missing clause. Choice A is incorrect. Modifiers and their subjects must go next to each other. The subject of the modifier "stabilizing shorelines in tropical regions against storm surges" is "mangrove forests," not "recent research." Choice B is incorrect. Modifiers and their subjects must go next to each other. The subject of the modifier "stabilizing shorelines in tropical regions against storm surges" is "mangrove forests," not "an estimated fourfold increase." Choice D is incorrect. Modifiers and their subjects must go next to each other. The subject of the modifier "stabilizing shorelines in tropical regions against storm surges" is "mangrove forests," not "recent research."', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Usually, cracks, discoloration, and faded varnish diminish a painting’s _______ when the artwork is an authentic Renaissance masterpiece, however, such signs of age can enhance its historical allure and market appeal. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"value, but"},{"id":"B","text":"value"},{"id":"C","text":"value,"},{"id":"D","text":"value but"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between two contrasting independent clauses. This choice correctly uses a comma followed by the coordinating conjunction “but” to connect two independent clauses that contrast with each other: “cracks, discoloration, and faded varnish diminish a painting’s value” and “such signs of age can enhance its historical allure and market appeal.” Choice B is incorrect because it omits needed punctuation and a conjunction, creating a run-on sentence. Choice C is incorrect because the comma alone produces a comma splice, joining two independent clauses without a coordinating conjunction. Choice D is incorrect because “but” alone is insufficient; a comma is required before it to correctly join the two clauses.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'To most observers, it does not seem that the cuttlefish relies on active signaling to communicate with its ______ rather, the cephalopod’s rapid color shifts and pattern changes suggest an intricate visual language used to warn competitors or attract mates. Recent marine studies have revealed that these displays are governed by a sophisticated neural network beneath the skin. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"peers, rather,"},{"id":"B","text":"peers rather,"},{"id":"C","text":"peers, rather;"},{"id":"D","text":"peers; rather,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the coordination of main clauses within a sentence. The semicolon is correctly used to join the first main clause (“To most observers…peers”) and the second main clause (“rather…the cephalopod’s rapid color shifts and pattern changes…”). Further, the comma after the adverb “rather” is correctly used to separate the adverb from the main clause (“the cephalopod’s rapid color shifts…”) it modifies, logically indicating that the information in this clause (how the cuttlefish actually communicates) is contrary to the information in the previous clause (how it appears to most observers). Choice A is incorrect because it results in a comma splice. Without a conjunction following it, a comma can’t be used in this way to join two main clauses. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence. The two main clauses are fused without appropriate punctuation and/or a conjunction. Choice C is incorrect. Placing the comma between the first main clause (“To most observers…peers”) and the adverb “rather” illogically indicates that the information in the first main clause is contrary to what came before, which doesn’t make sense in this context.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Historian Celeste Romero serves on the advisory committee responsible for selecting artifacts to be displayed in the National Museum of Indigenous Histories, which houses objects ranging from pre-Columbian pottery to contemporary textile art. Romero doesn’t determine these selections single-handedly, however; every exhibition proposal must be reviewed and approved by a council of ten additional scholars specializing in anthropology, ethnography, conservation, and cultural heritage policy. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"single-handedly, however"},{"id":"B","text":"single-handedly; however,"},{"id":"C","text":"single-handedly, however,"},{"id":"D","text":"single-handedly however"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of a supplementary word or phrase between two main clauses. This choice correctly uses a comma to separate the supplementary adverb “however” from the preceding main clause (“Romero doesn’t determine these selections single-handedly”) and a semicolon to join the next main clause (“every exhibition proposal must be reviewed and approved by a council of ten additional scholars”) to the rest of the sentence. Further, placing the semicolon after “however” correctly indicates that the information in the preceding main clause (Romero doesn’t determine these selections single-handedly) contrasts with what might be expected from the information in the previous sentence (Romero serves on the advisory committee responsible for selecting artifacts). Choice B is incorrect because placing the semicolon after “single-handedly” and the comma after “however” illogically suggests that the contrast lies between “Romero doesn’t determine these selections single-handedly” and “however,” which is not a clause but an adverb. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a comma splice—commas can’t be used in this way to punctuate a supplementary adverb between two main clauses. Choice D is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence; the two main clauses are fused without the necessary punctuation or conjunction to separate them.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'On March 15, 1965, civil rights leader John Lewis and more than 600 marchers crossed the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, Alabama. After years of advocating for voting rights with little progress, ____________ facing brutal opposition from law enforcement. Ultimately, their actions helped propel the Voting Rights Act of 1965 into law. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. pressure on state officials increased when the demonstrators organized a peaceful march to the state capital,"},{"id":"B","text":"B. a peaceful march organized by the demonstrators increased pressure on state officials,"},{"id":"C","text":"C. state officials came under increased pressure when the demonstrators organized a peaceful march to the capital,"},{"id":"D","text":"D. the demonstrators intensified their efforts by organizing a peaceful march to the state capital,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject-modifier placement. This choice makes the noun phrase “the demonstrators” the subject of the sentence and places it immediately after the modifying phrase “After years of advocating for voting rights with little progress.” In doing so, this choice clearly establishes that the demonstrators—and not another noun in the sentence—were facing brutal opposition from law enforcement. Choice A is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “pressure on state officials” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the “pressure” was advocating for voting rights. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “a peaceful march” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the march was advocating for voting rights. Choice C is incorrect because the placement of the noun phrase “state officials” immediately after the modifying phrase suggests that “state officials” were advocating for voting rights. While officials could support legislation, the context strongly suggests that it was the demonstrators who had been advocating for voting rights for years.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2019, environmental architect Lina Torres spearheaded an ambitious urban renewal initiative in São Paulo, overseeing the retrofitting of numerous high-rise office complexes with vertical botanical façades—living architectural systems engineered to mitigate heat absorption and purify polluted air. By enhancing atmospheric quality and diminishing reliance on mechanical cooling systems, _______ Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"the alleviation of both thermal load and airborne contaminants has been accomplished by the vertical façades."},{"id":"B","text":"the vertical façades have alleviated both thermal load and airborne contaminants within the city’s dense commercial districts."},{"id":"C","text":"the vertical façades’ alleviation of both thermal load and airborne contaminants has been accomplished."},{"id":"D","text":"both the thermal load and airborne contaminants have been alleviated by the vertical façades."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject–modifier placement. This choice correctly makes “the vertical façades” the subject of the sentence and places it immediately after the introductory modifying phrase “By enhancing atmospheric quality and diminishing reliance on mechanical cooling systems.” In doing so, this choice clearly establishes that the vertical façades—and not any other element in the sentence—are performing the actions described. Choice A is incorrect because it produces a dangling modifier: the noun phrase “the alleviation of both thermal load and airborne contaminants” follows the modifier in a way that obscures what entity is enhancing atmospheric quality. Choice C is incorrect for the same reason—the placement of “the vertical façades’ alleviation...” makes it ambiguous whether the façades themselves or their effects are improving air quality. Choice D is incorrect because it also results in a dangling modifier, illogically implying that “the thermal load and airborne contaminants” are responsible for enhancing atmospheric quality and reducing energy dependence.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 1),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Interest in optogenetics, the technique by which light is used to control cells in living tissue, is growing because of pioneering research by neurobiologists—many of whom, like Stanford’s Karl Deisseroth, ________ this technique to better understand how neural circuits influence behavior and brain function. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"is investigating"},{"id":"B","text":"has investigated"},{"id":"C","text":"investigate"},{"id":"D","text":"investigates"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of verb forms within a sentence. The plural verb “investigate” agrees in number with the plural subject “many” and correctly indicates the ongoing research activities of these neurobiologists. Choice A is incorrect because the singular verb “is investigating” does not agree in number with the plural subject “many.” Choice B is incorrect because the singular verb “has investigated” does not agree in number with the plural subject “many.” Choice D is incorrect because the singular verb “investigates” does not agree in number with the plural subject “many.”', 'standard-english', 'easy', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Though Japanese author Murasaki Shikibu is best known for writing The Tale of Genji (c. 1010), she also contributed to Heian court culture through her diaries, the record of ______ the intricate rituals, poetic exchanges, and political hierarchies that defined aristocratic life. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"daily life; reflecting"},{"id":"B","text":"daily life. Reflecting"},{"id":"C","text":"daily life reflecting"},{"id":"D","text":"daily life, reflecting"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation use between two supplementary phrases following the coordinate clause (“but she also contributed to Heian court culture through her diaries”). This choice correctly uses a comma to mark the boundary between the supplementary noun phrase (“the record of daily life”) that defines the term “diaries” and the supplementary participial phrase (“reflecting…the aristocratic life”) that provides additional information about the nature of those records. Choice A is incorrect because a semicolon can’t be used in this way to join two supplementary phrases following a coordinate clause. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a rhetorically unacceptable sentence fragment beginning with “reflecting.” Choice C is incorrect. The lack of punctuation results in a sentence that illogically suggests that the record of daily life itself is reflecting the rituals, rather than that the diaries—as descriptive works—reflect them.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In a 2023 study, researchers documented a fascinating behavior in the aquatic plant Elodea densa. When exposed to low levels of light, the plant’s ______ the cellular organs that generate energy from light—reshuffled to form a tightly packed, glass-like surface ideal for collecting more light. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"chloroplasts"},{"id":"B","text":"chloroplasts;"},{"id":"C","text":"chloroplasts,"},{"id":"D","text":"chloroplasts—"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of a supplementary element within a sentence. The dash after "chloroplasts" pairs with the dash after "from light" to separate the supplementary element "the cellular organs that generate energy from light" from the rest of the sentence. This supplementary element functions to define the term "chloroplasts," and the pair of dashes indicates that this element could be removed without affecting the grammatical coherence of the sentence. Choice A is incorrect because it fails to use appropriate punctuation to separate the supplementary element from the rest of the sentence. Choice B is incorrect because a semicolon can’t be paired with a dash in this way to separate the supplementary element from the rest of the sentence. Choice C is incorrect because a comma can’t be paired with a dash in this way to separate the supplementary element from the rest of the sentence.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In summer, the foraging patterns of Arctic foxes are determined more by prey availability than by prey preference. Although the foxes favor lemmings and small rodents, those food sources may become scarce due to shifting snowmelt and seasonal migration, ______ the foxes to scavenge along coastal areas for fish and seabird eggs. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"forces"},{"id":"B","text":"to force"},{"id":"C","text":"forcing"},{"id":"D","text":"forced"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of finite and nonfinite verb forms within a sentence. The nonfinite present participle “forcing” is correctly used to form a participial phrase that supplements the main clause (“those food sources may become scarce”), describing the effect on Arctic foxes of the limited availability of preferred prey. Choice A is incorrect because the finite present-tense verb “forces” cannot be used in this way to supplement the main clause (“those food sources may become scarce”). Choice B is incorrect because, while the nonfinite to-infinitive “to force” could form a subordinate clause, to-infinitives conventionally express purpose, and nothing in the sentence suggests that the scarcity of food exists for the purpose of forcing foxes to scavenge. Choice D is incorrect because the finite past-tense verb “forced” cannot be used in this way to supplement the main clause (“those food sources may become scarce”).', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Historians often refer to Mary Wollstonecraft as the “mother of feminism,” a label that has endured for more than two centuries. Wollstonecraft herself rejected the “feminist” _______ insisting that her arguments for women’s education stemmed from Enlightenment rationalism rather than modern political ideology. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"label; however,"},{"id":"B","text":"label, however,"},{"id":"C","text":"label, however"},{"id":"D","text":"label; however"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the correct punctuation of an interrupter (the adverb “however”) within a sentence. This choice correctly sets off “however” with commas on both sides to mark it as a parenthetical transition: “Wollstonecraft herself rejected the ‘feminist’ label, however, insisting that her arguments for women’s education stemmed from Enlightenment rationalism rather than modern political ideology.” Choice A is incorrect because the semicolon before “however” incorrectly separates two parts that do not form independent clauses; the phrase following “label” (“however, insisting…”) is not a standalone sentence. Choice C is incorrect because it omits the second comma after “however,” breaking the symmetry of the interrupter and creating a punctuation error. Choice D is incorrect because it uses a semicolon before “however” without following it with an independent clause, which violates standard punctuation rules for conjunctive adverbs.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'After suffering numerous rejections early in her career, Oprah Winfrey was told she didn’t have the personality for television. Defying all odds, Winfrey didn’t just appear on TV, she ______ her decades-long career as a talk show host, she inspired millions of viewers and became one of the most influential figures in media history. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"connected—deeply—during"},{"id":"B","text":"connected—deeply during"},{"id":"C","text":"connected—deeply, during"},{"id":"D","text":"connected—deeply. During"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation use between sentences. In this choice, the period is used correctly to mark the boundary between one sentence (“Defying...deeply”) and another sentence that begins with a supplementary phrase (“During...career”). Choice A is incorrect. When a dash is present in a sentence (“connected—deeply”), it’s not conventional to use another dash (“deeply—during”) to mark the boundary between sentences because it creates a confusing and nonstandard structure. In this context, a period, semicolon, or colon would be clear and more conventional. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence. The sentences (“Defying...deeply”) and (“During...career”) are fused without appropriate punctuation or a coordinating conjunction. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a comma splice. A comma cannot be used to join two independent clauses without a coordinating conjunction.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'When a given sector—public transportation is a common example—requires extensive government regulation and funding that make private competition impractical, _______ of only one main operator in each city. Such sectors are often referred to as public service monopolies. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"these usually consist"},{"id":"B","text":"they usually consist"},{"id":"C","text":"it usually consists"},{"id":"D","text":"this usually consists"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is pronoun–antecedent agreement. The singular pronoun “it” agrees in number with the singular antecedent “sector” and clearly indicates that the sector consists of only one main operator in each city. Choice A is incorrect. The plural pronoun “these” neither agrees in number with the singular antecedent sector nor clearly indicates that the sector—rather than another plural noun in the sentence such as regulations or funding—consists of only one main operator. Choice B is incorrect because the plural pronoun “they” doesn’t agree in number with the singular antecedent sector. Choice D is incorrect because the singular pronoun “this” is ambiguous in this context; the resulting sentence leaves unclear what consists of only one main operator in each city.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In her 2015 novel Between the World and Me, American author Ta-Nehisi Coates explores the experiences of young Black men in the United States. The narrator reflects on his own adolescence in Baltimore, grappling with systemic racism and social pressures. _______ his childhood friend, Sam, moves to Atlanta to attend college, seeking a different path. However, he soon realizes that racial and economic challenges follow him there as well. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Meanwhile,"},{"id":"B","text":"Nevertheless,"},{"id":"C","text":"Secondly,"},{"id":"D","text":"In fact,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Meanwhile” logically signals that the action in this sentence (Sam’s move to Atlanta) occurs simultaneously with the narrator’s reflections on his adolescence in Baltimore. The first sentence establishes that the experiences of the narrator and his friend are parallel but geographically divergent. Choice B is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically suggests that Sam’s move happens despite the narrator’s experiences. Instead, the two actions are parallel and concurrent. Choice C is incorrect because “secondly” illogically signals that Sam’s move is a sequential point unrelated to the narrator’s experience. Instead, the sentence emphasizes a simultaneous, parallel occurrence. Choice D is incorrect because “in fact” illogically signals that Sam’s move serves to emphasize or clarify the narrator’s experience. Instead, the focus is on parallel experiences rather than reinforcement.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Renowned Japanese swordsmith Masamune (circa 13th century) crafted blades noted for their exceptional strength and beauty using a process called differential hardening. This technique involves cooling the edge of the blade more rapidly than the spine. _________ the sword develops a razor-sharp cutting edge while maintaining a flexible core. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"On the contrary,"},{"id":"B","text":"For example,"},{"id":"C","text":"Previously,"},{"id":"D","text":"As a result,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “As a result” logically signals that the information in this sentence—the sword developing a razor-sharp cutting edge while maintaining a flexible core—is a result of the cooling process described in the previous sentence. Choice A is incorrect because “on the contrary” illogically signals that the information in this sentence directly opposes the cooling process in the previous sentence. Instead, the blade’s qualities arise as a result of that process. Choice B is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is merely an example of the cooling process described earlier. Instead, the blade’s qualities are the outcome of that process. Choice C is incorrect because “previously” illogically signals that the information in this sentence occurs earlier in a chronological sequence than the cooling process described in the previous sentences. Instead, the blade’s qualities occur as a result of that process.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'At birth, human newborns can detect smells and tastes but have very limited vision and hearing. Domestic cats, _______ can see, hear, and smell quite well within the first two weeks of life. This early sensory development may help explain why kittens often explore their surroundings more confidently than human infants. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"In other words,"},{"id":"B","text":"For instance,"},{"id":"C","text":"By contrast,"},{"id":"D","text":"Consequently,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “By contrast” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that kittens can see, hear, and smell well within two weeks—contrasts with the preceding information that human newborns have very limited vision and hearing at birth. Choice A is incorrect because “in other words” illogically suggests that the information about kittens restates or paraphrases the information about human newborns. Instead, it contrasts with it. Choice B is incorrect because “for instance” illogically signals that the information about kittens serves as an example of the human newborns’ sensory abilities. In fact, it highlights a difference rather than an example. Choice D is incorrect because “consequently” illogically suggests that the kittens’ sensory development results from the information about human newborns. Instead, it is presented to emphasize a contrast between the two species’ early sensory abilities.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Astronomers use different space telescopes to study distant galaxies and detect signals from the early universe. • The Hubble Space Telescope captures visible and ultraviolet light, producing high-resolution images of galaxies. • Many of Hubble’s observations revealed the structure and evolution of galaxies formed billions of years after the Big Bang. • The James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) primarily observes in infrared wavelengths. • JWST can detect extremely faint, early galaxies whose light has been stretched by cosmic expansion. The student wants to distinguish what the Hubble Space Telescope reveals about galaxies from what the James Webb Space Telescope reveals. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Both the Hubble Space Telescope and the James Webb Space Telescope allow astronomers to investigate distant galaxies."},{"id":"B","text":"Although both telescopes observe galaxies, Hubble captures visible and ultraviolet light from later-forming galaxies, whereas JWST detects far older, faint galaxies in the infrared."},{"id":"C","text":"The James Webb Space Telescope, which primarily observes in infrared wavelengths, has detected extremely faint early galaxies."},{"id":"D","text":"The Hubble Space Telescope produces high-resolution visible-light images showing the structure of galaxies."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The sentence contrasts what each telescope reveals about galaxies, noting that the Hubble Space Telescope captures visible and ultraviolet light from later-forming galaxies, whereas the James Webb Space Telescope detects much older, extremely faint galaxies in the infrared. Choice A is incorrect. The sentence highlights a similarity between Hubble and JWST—that both investigate distant galaxies—rather than distinguishing what each reveals. Choice C is incorrect. While the sentence provides a description of JWST’s abilities, it doesn’t mention the Hubble Space Telescope or contrast the two telescopes. Choice D is incorrect. While the sentence provides a description of Hubble’s capabilities, it doesn’t mention the James Webb Space Telescope or contrast what the two telescopes reveal.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) classifies species according to their risk of extinction. • A species facing a very high risk of extinction in the wild is listed as Endangered. • A species facing an extremely high risk of extinction in the wild is listed as Critically Endangered. • The Hawksbill sea turtle (Eretmochelys imbricata) faces threats including habitat loss and illegal trade. • These threats place the Hawksbill sea turtle in the category associated with an extremely high risk of extinction. The student wants to identify which IUCN category the Hawksbill sea turtle falls under, based on how extinction risk is classified. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Because the Hawksbill sea turtle faces habitat loss and illegal trade, the IUCN evaluates its status using criteria related to extinction risk."},{"id":"B","text":"The IUCN assigns species to categories such as Endangered and Critically Endangered depending on the severity of threats they face in the wild."},{"id":"C","text":"Facing threats severe enough to pose an extremely high risk of extinction, the Hawksbill sea turtle is listed by the IUCN as Critically Endangered."},{"id":"D","text":"Habitat degradation and illegal trade affect numerous marine species and are among the factors the IUCN considers when assessing extinction risk."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. It directly identifies the category the student needs—Critically Endangered—and ties it explicitly to the threat level described in the notes (an extremely high extinction risk). Choice A is incorrect. It mentions threats and evaluation criteria but does not state which category the Hawksbill belongs to. Choice B is incorrect. It describes the classification system, not the Hawksbill’s specific category. Choice D is incorrect. It notes factors influencing extinction risk but fails to name the category applied to the Hawksbill sea turtle.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Glass-bottom walkways built along cliff edges are known as skywalks, a term popularized by tourism developers in the early 2000s. As visiting these walkways has shifted from a sightseeing stop to a thrill-seeking activity, modern skywalks are rarely constructed solely to offer a simple viewing platform. ________ new designs prioritize excitement over function, aiming to create a vertigo-inducing experience or highlight dramatic geological formations. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Additionally,"},{"id":"B","text":"On the other hand,"},{"id":"C","text":"More often,"},{"id":"D","text":"Nonetheless,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “More often” logically signals that the claim in this sentence—that new skywalk designs prioritize excitement over function—clarifies how modern versions differ from older ones, reinforcing the previous statement that skywalks today are “rarely constructed solely to offer a simple viewing platform.” In doing so, it emphasizes the shift from practical sightseeing structures to thrill-oriented attractions. Choice A is incorrect because “additionally” illogically signals that this sentence introduces a new, separate point rather than reinforcing the earlier claim about modern skywalks being rarely built for simple viewing. Instead, the statement that new designs prioritize excitement over function directly supports and expands on that earlier claim. Choice B is incorrect because “on the other hand” illogically signals a contrast or opposition to the previous sentence’s point about modern skywalks’ changing purpose. Instead, the idea that new designs emphasize excitement over function strengthens the same point. Choice D is incorrect because “nonetheless” illogically signals that this sentence’s claim is true despite the previous claim about skywalks rarely serving as simple viewing platforms. Instead, the description of new designs prioritizing excitement over function reinforces—not contradicts—the previous statement.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In hindsight, one of the key takeaways from the 2012 Human Microbiome Project is that human health is influenced not only by our own cells but also by the vast communities of microorganisms living within us. _________ rather than studying human physiology in isolation, researchers now aim to understand how interactions between human and microbial genes contribute to metabolism, immunity, and disease. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"In other words,"},{"id":"B","text":"That said,"},{"id":"C","text":"For example,"},{"id":"D","text":"Accordingly,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “Accordingly” logically signals that this sentence states a result or consequence of the previous information about the 2012 Human Microbiome Project. Taking into account the key lesson of that project—that human health depends on interactions between human cells and microbial communities—researchers have begun to study physiology in relation to microbial genes rather than in isolation. Choice A is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is merely a paraphrase or restatement of the previous information about the 2012 Human Microbiome Project. Instead, this sentence states a result or consequence of that information. Choice B is incorrect because “that said” illogically signals that the information in this sentence qualifies or contrasts with the previous information about the 2012 Human Microbiome Project. Instead, this sentence states a result or consequence of that information. Choice C is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that this sentence provides an instance or illustration of the previous information about the 2012 Human Microbiome Project. Instead, this sentence states a result or consequence of that information.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'For decades, many archaeologists assumed that the dense jungles of northern Guatemala were sparsely populated by ancient people. "Researchers once believed that the Maya civilization consisted only of small, isolated settlements separated by vast wilderness." However, archaeologist Marcello Canuto and his team used LiDAR (Light Detection and Ranging) technology to peer through the thick forest canopy. Their findings revealed a massive, interconnected network of over 60,000 houses, palaces, and elevated highways, proving that the region was actually home to millions of people. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined sentence in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It identifies a belief held by researchers that Canuto and his team showed to be wrong."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It describes the specific technical settings of the LiDAR equipment used by the team."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It emphasizes a disagreement between Canuto and the other members of his research team."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It provides the final data results that support the team''s new claim about the Maya."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately describes how the underlined sentence functions in the text as a whole. The first sentence establishes that archaeologists had certain assumptions about the population of the Guatemalan jungle. The second sentence, which is underlined, describes what those researchers specifically believed—that the Maya lived in small, isolated settlements. The rest of the text establishes that this was incorrect by citing Canuto’s discovery of a massive, connected city. Thus, the purpose of the underlined sentence is to identify a belief that the new research showed to be wrong. Choice B is incorrect. While the text mentions that Canuto used LiDAR technology, the underlined sentence does not describe the "technical settings" or the design of the equipment; it describes an old archaeological theory. Choice C is incorrect because the underlined sentence presents a general belief held by past researchers; the text never mentions a "disagreement" between Canuto and his own team members. Choice D is incorrect because the underlined sentence presents an old, incorrect theory rather than the "final data results." The actual data (the discovery of 60,000 structures) is presented in the sentence that follows the underlined portion.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1947, Jackie Robinson became the first Black player to compete in Major League Baseball in the modern era when he joined the Brooklyn Dodgers. Robinson’s success on the field broke the “color barrier” in professional baseball, challenging long-standing racial segregation in the sport. His presence and achievements provided a powerful example of integration and inspired both other Black athletes and the broader civil rights movement. Robinson continued to use his platform to advocate for racial equality throughout his life. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To argue that Jackie Robinson should have faced fewer obstacles in Major League Baseball"},{"id":"B","text":"To describe how Jackie Robinson’s career influenced racial integration in baseball and beyond"},{"id":"C","text":"To explain why the Brooklyn Dodgers were the first team to hire a Black player"},{"id":"D","text":"To discuss the statistics of Jackie Robinson’s performance during his rookie season"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the passage focuses on Robinson’s role in breaking the color barrier and how his achievements inspired integration in baseball and contributed to the civil rights movement. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not argue that Robinson should have faced fewer obstacles; it reports on his historic achievements and influence. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not explain why the Dodgers were the first team to hire a Black player; it focuses on Robinson’s broader impact. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not provide statistical details about Robinson’s performance; it highlights the significance of his presence in Major League Baseball.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Beginning in 1908, Georges Braque and Pablo Picasso developed the first phase of Cubism, later termed Analytic Cubism, which focused on breaking objects into fragmented planes. In the summer of 1912, however, Braque departed from this approach after encountering factory-printed oil cloth while working on a drawing of a guitar. Rather than rendering the instrument’s wood grain by hand, he incorporated the pre-printed material directly into the work. This decision introduced collage into fine art and signaled a broader shift in Cubism, as Braque—and soon Picasso—used mass-produced elements to challenge assumptions about artistic skill, originality, and the boundary between commercial and fine art. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It presents a general characterization of an artistic movement, then illustrates a pivotal change within that movement through a specific example."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It traces a chronological biography of two artists, then evaluates the lasting influence of their careers."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It contrasts two artistic techniques, then argues that one is aesthetically superior to the other."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It describes a single artwork in detail, then explains how viewers are meant to interpret it."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately describes how the passage is organized. The text begins by characterizing an early phase of Cubism as an analytical approach focused on fragmenting form. It then narrows to a specific example—Braque’s use of oil cloth collage—to demonstrate a decisive shift in artistic practice, showing how that innovation altered assumptions about technique, originality, and the nature of fine art. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not offer a biographical account of Braque and Picasso’s lives or assess their entire careers; instead, it focuses on a particular moment and its artistic significance. Choice C is incorrect because although two approaches to Cubism are mentioned, the text does not argue that one is aesthetically superior. Rather, it explains how a change in method expanded the conceptual aims of the movement. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not describe a single artwork in detailed visual terms or instruct readers on how to interpret it; instead, it uses an example to illustrate a broader shift in artistic thinking.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from Frank Bidart’s poem “Golden State.” It’s in many ways a relief to have you dead. I have more money. Bakersfield is easier: life isn’t so nude, now that I no longer have to face you each evening: mother is progressing beautifully in therapy, I can almost convince myself a good analyst would have saved you: for I need to believe, as always, that your pervasive sense of disappointment proceeded from trivial desires: but I fear that beneath the wish to be a movie star, cowboy, empire builder, all those cheap desires, lay radical disaffection from the very possibilities of human life … Your wishes were too simple: or too complex. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The speaker recounts personal improvements following a loss and then argues that those improvements were inevitable."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The speaker criticizes another person’s ambitions and then proposes a remedy that might have prevented the outcome."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The speaker lists superficial explanations for another person’s dissatisfaction and then rejects those explanations in favor of a more troubling conclusion."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The speaker expresses relief at another person’s absence and then celebrates the emotional clarity that absence provides."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. In the first part of the text, the speaker attempts to explain the other person’s lifelong disappointment by attributing it to “trivial desires,” such as wanting to be a movie star or empire builder. In the second part, the speaker undermines this explanation by acknowledging a deeper cause: a “radical disaffection from the very possibilities of human life.” Thus, the structure moves from a surface-level explanation to the rejection of that explanation in favor of a more unsettling conclusion. Choice A is incorrect. Although the speaker mentions practical improvements after the person’s death, the text does not argue that these improvements were inevitable or justify them as such. Choice B is incorrect. While the speaker briefly suggests that therapy might have helped, the text does not primarily propose a solution; instead, it focuses on the limits of explanation. Choice D is incorrect. Although the poem opens with an expression of relief, the speaker does not celebrate emotional clarity; rather, the poem becomes increasingly uncertain and conflicted.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'According to historian Elizabeth Anne Leonard, the "Hello Girls"—bilingual telephone operators in the U.S. Army Signal Corps—were indispensable to military operations during World War I. At a time when rapid communication was vital for coordinating troop movements across the Western Front, the unique linguistic and technical skills of these women provided them with unprecedented institutional leverage. As the military relied increasingly on their efficiency to manage the overburdened switchboards, "the operators successfully negotiated for specialized uniforms and status equivalent to that of male soldiers, which the War Department, desperate to maintain seamless communication lines, officially sanctioned." Consequently, the Signal Corps became a site where women could transcend traditional gender roles through essential technical labor. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined portion in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It elaborates on a claim about the influence of a specific group of workers made earlier in the text."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It provides further details about the ethnic and linguistic identities of the operators discussed earlier in the text."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It offers a broader context for the general military expansion that occurred during World War I."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It identifies a significant exception to the professional gains achieved by women in the early twentieth century."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it accurately describes how the underlined portion functions within the overall structure of the text. The earlier part of the passage claims that the "unique linguistic and technical skills" of the Hello Girls gave them "unprecedented institutional leverage." The underlined portion then provides specific evidence of this leverage in action: the operators negotiated for better status and uniforms, and the War Department complied. Thus, the underlined portion elaborates on the claim regarding the workers'' influence. Choice B is incorrect. While the text mentions earlier that the operators were "bilingual," the underlined portion itself focuses on the outcome of their negotiations (uniforms and status) rather than providing further details about their specific identities, such as their names, nationalities, or specific languages spoken. Choice C is incorrect. The passage focuses specifically on the Signal Corps and the leverage of female operators. The underlined portion does not describe a general trend of military expansion; rather, it details a specific labor negotiation within a single department. Choice D is incorrect. The underlined portion describes a successful negotiation and a professional gain. Therefore, it serves as a supporting example of the progress mentioned in the text, not as an "exception" to it.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the early 1960s, psychologist Stanley Milgram conducted a series of laboratory studies at Yale University ostensibly concerned with the effects of punishment on learning. Participants were instructed to administer electric shocks of escalating intensity to another individual for incorrect responses, following a standardized protocol overseen by an authoritative experimenter. Although the stated purpose emphasized learning outcomes, the study’s design foregrounded the experimenter’s insistence that participants continue despite the learner’s increasingly distressed reactions. Analyses of participant behavior later prompted scholars to argue that the findings illuminate the extent to which institutional authority can suppress personal ethical resistance. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It describes the methodology of a psychological experiment, evaluates competing explanations for participant behavior, and then rejects those explanations as insufficient."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It presents an experimental scenario, emphasizes the emotional consequences experienced by participants, and then critiques the moral assumptions underlying the study."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It summarizes a historical investigation, contrasts its stated objectives with its actual outcomes, and then challenges the validity of the conclusions drawn from it."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It introduces a research study, outlines the procedural framework through which it was conducted, and then conveys a scholarly interpretation of what the findings reveal."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The text first introduces Milgram’s research study, then describes the procedural structure by which participants administered shocks under an experimenter’s authority, and then reports how later scholars interpreted the results as demonstrating the power of institutional authority over ethical judgment. Choice A is incorrect. The text does not present or weigh multiple competing explanations for participant behavior. Instead, it reports a single interpretive claim about the implications of obedience to authority.Choice B is incorrect. While the passage refers to participants’ distress, it does not focus on emotional consequences as its primary concern, nor does it critique the moral assumptions of the experiment itself. Instead, it summarizes the study and conveys subsequent scholarly interpretation. Choice C is incorrect. Although the passage notes a difference between the experiment’s stated purpose and its underlying design, it does not question the validity of the conclusions drawn from the study. Rather, it presents those conclusions as interpretations offered by scholars.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Thomas Sankara is often described as an unlikely revolutionary, having emerged from a military environment not typically associated with original political thought. After seizing power in Upper Volta in 1983, Sankara rejected the corruption and foreign dependence that had characterized earlier regimes and initiated sweeping reforms, including land redistribution, environmental restoration, and expanded rights for women. Though his rule ended abruptly with his assassination in 1987, Sankara’s assertion that “you cannot kill ideas” has come to symbolize the enduring influence of his vision beyond his brief time in power. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It introduces a historical figure, outlines key actions taken during his leadership, and suggests why his legacy has endured."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It describes a political ideology, explains how that ideology was implemented through policy, and evaluates the long-term success of those policies."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It recounts a nation’s colonial history, details the causes of political instability, and explains how a military leader came to power."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It presents a quotation, explains the circumstances under which it was delivered, and argues that the quotation has been misunderstood."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The passage begins by introducing Thomas Sankara as an unusual and noteworthy figure, then describes several defining actions he took during his leadership, including political, social, and environmental reforms. It concludes by suggesting why his influence persisted after his death, emphasizing the symbolic power of his ideas rather than the duration of his rule. Choice B is incorrect. Although the passage mentions reforms associated with Sankara’s leadership, it does not systematically describe a political ideology or evaluate the long-term success of specific policies. Choice C is incorrect. While colonial history and political instability are part of the broader background, the passage does not recount that history in detail or explain the causes of instability; instead, it focuses on Sankara himself. Choice D is incorrect. Although the passage ends with a quotation, the text is not primarily concerned with interpreting or correcting misunderstandings about that quotation; rather, the quotation serves to reinforce the significance of Sankara’s legacy.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In many bird species, the incubation of eggs requires a highly consistent thermal environment to ensure embryo survival. Ecologists have long observed that "cavity nesters"—birds that build nests inside tree hollows or rock crevices—produce fledglings with higher survival rates than "open-cup nesters" do, due to the stable microclimate and protection from predators provided by the cavity. Consequently, some researchers hypothesized that cavity-nesting species would exhibit a higher degree of "clutch size plasticity," meaning they would be able to successfully raise a larger number of eggs per nesting attempt across a wider variety of environmental temperatures than open-cup nesters can. Which finding, if true, would most directly support the researchers’ hypothesis?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. In a study of several hundred avian species, open-cup nesters were found to migrate longer distances on average than cavity-nesters to find optimal seasonal temperatures for breeding."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Cavity-nesting species typically utilize a wider variety of lining materials, such as feathers and mammal fur, than open-cup nesting species do to further insulate their eggs."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Observations revealed that while cavity nests provide more protection from rain, they are significantly more likely to be infested by parasitic mites than open-cup nests are."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Data showed that cavity-nesters maintained a consistent number of successfully hatched eggs regardless of fluctuating ambient temperatures, whereas open-cup nesters saw a significant decrease in hatched eggs as temperatures deviated from the seasonal average."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it provides direct evidence of "clutch size plasticity" in relation to environmental stability. If cavity-nesters maintain a consistent hatch rate "regardless of fluctuating ambient temperatures" while open-cup nesters do not, it supports the idea that the cavity environment allows the birds to maintain reproductive success (clutch size) across a wider range of conditions. Choice A is incorrect. While migration habits are an interesting behavioral adaptation, they do not provide evidence regarding the "clutch size" or the "plasticity" of the nesting attempt itself. Choice B is incorrect. This describes a method of insulation (the materials used) but does not provide evidence of the result of that insulation—namely, whether it actually allows for larger or more stable clutch sizes as hypothesized. Choice C is incorrect. This finding identifies a disadvantage of cavity nesting (parasites). It does not address the researchers'' hypothesis concerning environmental temperature and reproductive plasticity.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A student is investigating the relationship between extreme urban heat and home cooling infrastructure in a large metropolitan area. The student claims that despite the health risks associated with high temperatures, a significant portion of the population in the hottest regions still lacks access to central air conditioning, noting that even in the area with the highest peak heat index, the percentage of households with central air conditioning is only ______ Which choice most effectively uses data from the table to complete the student’s claim?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. 48%."},{"id":"B","text":"B. 74%."},{"id":"C","text":"C. 118.3%."},{"id":"D","text":"D. 90%."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it effectively uses data from the table to complete the student''s claim about the highest percentage of households with central air conditioning in the areas represented. The student’s claim refers to the area with the "highest peak heat index." According to the table, the highest temperature listed is 118.3°F. For that specific area, the table indicates that 74% of households have central air conditioning. Since 74% is the highest value in the percentage column, it correctly completes the claim that "only" this much of the population has access, implying that 26% still lacks it. Choice A is incorrect because 48% is the lowest percentage of households with central air conditioning listed in the table, which corresponds to the area with the lowest heat index (94.4°F). The student’s claim specifically focuses on the area with the highest peak heat index. Choice C is incorrect because 118.3 is a temperature value (in degrees Fahrenheit), not a percentage of households. The student''s claim requires a percentage to complete the thought regarding the portion of the population with access to cooling. Choice D is incorrect because the percentage 90% does not appear in the table. The highest percentage actually recorded in this study was 74%.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Archaeological evidence suggests that the Lapita people—ancestors of many Pacific Island populations—began expanding eastward across the Pacific around 1500 B.C.E. One key site of Lapita settlement is on the island of Efate in what is now Vanuatu. A recent isotopic analysis of chicken bones excavated from early settlements in Tonga showed a dietary pattern nearly identical to that of chickens raised by Lapita communities on Efate, with no such pattern appearing in Tonga before approximately 900 B.C.E. These findings indicate that domesticated chickens in Tonga share a direct lineage with those maintained by Lapita settlers on Efate. Thus, researchers concluded that _______ Which choice most logically completes the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"climate conditions on Efate and in Tonga must have differed significantly prior to 900 B.C.E."},{"id":"B","text":"early Tongan communities relied almost entirely on imported animals for their food supply."},{"id":"C","text":"some Lapita groups traveled from Efate to Tonga around 900 B.C.E., bringing domesticated chickens with them."},{"id":"D","text":"Lapita communities originally learned domestication techniques from island groups farther west in the Pacific."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically follows from the text’s discussion of Lapita expansion and the genetic relationship between chicken populations. The passage states that the Lapita people expanded eastward across the Pacific and that chickens in Tonga exhibit isotopic signatures directly matching those of Lapita-raised chickens on Efate—signatures not found in Tonga before about 900 B.C.E. This combination of settlement history and biological evidence strongly supports the conclusion that Lapita groups migrated from Efate to Tonga around 900 B.C.E. and brought their domesticated chickens with them, explaining the sudden appearance of the matching isotopic pattern. Choice A is incorrect because the passage never compares the climate of Efate with that of Tonga, either before or after 900 B.C.E., and climate conditions play no role in the argument about chicken lineage. Choice B is incorrect. The text indicates only that chickens in Tonga after 900 B.C.E. descended from chickens kept by Lapita settlers on Efate. It does not claim that early Tongan communities depended almost entirely on imported animals, nor does it address the origins of other species in their food supply. Choice D is incorrect. The passage does not mention where Lapita domestication techniques originated or whether they learned them from western island groups. Instead, it presents evidence that the Lapita people transported domesticated chickens from Efate to Tonga, not that they adopted these practices from elsewhere.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the early twentieth century, ethnomusicologist Frances Densmore made some of the earliest audio recordings of Native American music using wax cylinders. Many of these cylinders, recorded between 1907 and 1930 for the Smithsonian Institution, captured songs that had never before been documented in writing. Because the cylinders produced faint and often distorted sound, Densmore later described her transcription work as painstaking: she had to replay single phrases dozens of times to distinguish subtle rhythms and words. Her efforts were crucial to preserving musical traditions that, at the time, had only limited written documentation. What does the passage most strongly suggest about the songs Densmore recorded?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. They had previously been widely circulated in print before Densmore documented them."},{"id":"B","text":"B. They would have been impossible to study had the Smithsonian not restored the cylinders."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Few dependable written versions of the songs existed when Densmore began her transcription work."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Densmore believed the singers altered the songs significantly from one performance to another."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because the passage states that many of the songs Densmore recorded “had never before been documented in writing” and that her work was “crucial to preserving” traditions with “only limited written documentation.” This strongly implies that reliable written versions of these songs were scarce when she began her research, making transcription necessary and difficult. Choice A is incorrect. The passage explicitly contradicts this: the songs were not widely printed, and many had no written documentation at all. It would be inaccurate to claim they circulated in print. Choice B is incorrect. Although the recordings were faint and distorted, the passage never states that the Smithsonian restored them or that the songs would have been impossible to study otherwise. It only emphasizes the difficulty of transcription, not its impossibility. Choice D is incorrect. The passage describes Densmore’s difficulty distinguishing rhythms and words due to poor audio quality, not because the singers performed different versions of the songs. No evidence is provided about variation between performances.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In a study of autonomous self-healing materials, Nancy Sottos et al. describe a method for repairing structural microcracks using a network of microcapsules embedded within a polymer matrix. In this system, when a crack forms, it ruptures the embedded capsules, releasing a liquid healing agent into the damaged area. This agent then comes into contact with a chemical catalyst pre-dispersed in the polymer, triggering a polymerization reaction that seals the crack. Traditional methods for repairing structural damage in polymers often require external intervention, such as the manual application of heat or ultraviolet radiation to the site of the fracture—a requirement that may be bypassed by microencapsulated systems, which the researchers characterize as "inherently responsive and self-sustaining." What does the text most strongly suggest about traditional methods for repairing structural damage in polymers?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. They are typically more effective at preventing the initial formation of microcracks than microencapsulated systems are."},{"id":"B","text":"B. They are likely less conducive to maintaining the integrity of materials in inaccessible or remote environments than the method described by Sottos et al. may be."},{"id":"C","text":"C. They generally involve a higher concentration of chemical catalysts than do the autonomous systems developed by researchers."},{"id":"D","text":"D. They are considered \"concise and practical\" by researchers only when the damage is limited to the surface of the polymer matrix."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it presents a statement about traditional repair methods that is supported by the text. The text contrasts traditional methods, which require "external intervention" (like manual heat or UV application), with the microencapsulated system, which is "self-sustaining." Because traditional methods require a person or machine to manually apply a stimulus to the crack, they would logically be less suitable for environments where such intervention is difficult or impossible (inaccessible or remote locations). Choice A is incorrect because the text focuses on the repair of cracks after they have formed, not the prevention of the initial formation of cracks. There is no data provided to compare the preventative capabilities of the two methods. Choice C is incorrect. While the text mentions that the autonomous system uses a "pre-dispersed" catalyst, it provides no information regarding the concentration of catalysts used in traditional methods, nor does it even state that traditional methods use catalysts at all (mentioning only heat and UV). Choice D is incorrect because the text does not use the phrase "concise and practical" to describe traditional methods; in fact, those descriptors were used in the reference text for a different topic entirely. Furthermore, the text does not distinguish between surface damage and internal damage in terms of the practicality of traditional methods.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The cyprinid fish Onychostoma macrolepis has long been grouped with other species exhibiting temperature-dependent sex determination (TSD), a phenomenon in which ambient temperature biases the development of gonadal sex. Until recently, no fish had been shown to possess bidirectional TSD, in which both unusually low and unusually high temperatures alter sex ratios in opposite directions. In a controlled study, researchers documented that O. macrolepis produced roughly equal numbers of males and females at 24 °C, but that exposure to 28 °C yielded over 80% females, while exposure to 20 °C generated approximately 75% males. Further transcriptomic analyses identified calcium-channel genes and the epigenetic regulator kdm6bb as central mediators of this dual response, a conclusion reinforced by experiments in which inhibiting calcium influx prevented high-temperature feminization and inhibiting Kdm6bb activity blocked low-temperature masculinization. Moreover, the species displayed unexpected transcriptional patterns: canonical male-pathway genes such as dmrt1 and gsdf were more highly expressed at high rather than low temperatures, and aromatase inhibitors—which typically induce masculinization—failed to produce sex reversal at either temperature. Based on these convergent findings, the research team proposes that O. macrolepis likely _______. Which choice most logically completes the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"evolved temperature-insensitive downstream gene networks that buffer against calcium-mediated changes in kdm6bb expression."},{"id":"B","text":"shares with conventionally studied TSD fishes a unidirectional masculinization pathway that is activated only at the lowest developmental temperatures."},{"id":"C","text":"relies primarily on aromatase suppression to trigger sex reversal, regardless of whether environmental temperatures are high, moderate, or low."},{"id":"D","text":"uses a mechanistically distinct, bidirectional temperature-sensing system in which calcium signaling and kdm6bb jointly modulate sexual fate in ways unlike established TSD models."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the temperature-dependent sex determination (TSD) system in Onychostoma macrolepis. The text first establishes that O. macrolepis differs from all previously studied fishes because it exhibits bidirectional TSD—a pattern in which both unusually high and unusually low temperatures shift sex ratios, but in opposite directions. The text then describes the evidence researchers gathered to understand this unusual pattern: at 24 °C the species shows an even sex ratio, whereas 28 °C produces predominantly females and 20 °C produces predominantly males. The text continues by presenting the molecular findings that explain this atypical temperature response. Transcriptomic data highlight calcium-channel genes and the epigenetic regulator kdm6bb as crucial mediators of the contrasting effects of high and low temperatures, and targeted inhibitor experiments show that blocking calcium influx prevents high-temperature feminization while blocking Kdm6bb function prevents low-temperature masculinization. The researchers also observed transcriptional patterns unexpected under conventional TSD models—such as higher dmrt1 and gsdf expression at high rather than low temperatures—and found that aromatase inhibition failed to induce sex reversal under any condition. Taken together, these findings indicate that O. macrolepis does not follow the standard unidirectional TSD mechanisms documented in other fishes. Thus, the researchers conclude that the species most likely uses a mechanistically distinct, bidirectional temperature-sensing system in which calcium signaling and kdm6bb jointly regulate sexual development in ways that differ from established TSD models. Choice A is incorrect because the text shows that temperature-driven changes in calcium signaling and kdm6bb expression directly do affect sex determination in O. macrolepis. The researchers therefore would not propose that the species evolved temperature-insensitive downstream pathways that buffer against these changes. Choice B is incorrect because the text explicitly states that O. macrolepis does not follow the conventional unidirectional masculinization pattern. Instead, it shows a bidirectional system in which both high and low temperatures alter sex ratios in opposite directions. Choice C is incorrect because aromatase inhibitors—which ordinarily induce masculinization—failed to cause sex reversal at any temperature in the study. Therefore, the researchers would not claim that aromatase suppression is the primary mechanism for sex reversal in this species.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 1, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'To reduce the amount of space debris orbiting Earth, aerospace engineers have suggested launching satellites equipped with small propulsion systems. These systems would push the satellites into Earth’s atmosphere at the end of their missions and _______ their safe disintegration on reentry. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"ensures"},{"id":"B","text":"ensure"},{"id":"C","text":"ensuring"},{"id":"D","text":"ensured"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of non-finite (untensed) verb forms in a sentence. The modal “would,” which expresses a hypothetical or future action from a past perspective, must be followed by a non-finite plain form verb. In this choice, the verb “ensure” correctly matches the form of the verb “push” earlier in the sentence to describe what the systems would do. Choice A is incorrect because the finite present tense verb “ensures” cannot be used with the modal “would.” Choice C is incorrect because the present participle “ensuring” cannot grammatically follow the modal “would” in this context. Choice D is incorrect because the past tense verb “ensured” cannot be used with the modal “would” to describe a hypothetical or future action.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Recent sediment studies of Lake Tanganyika have led some scientists to propose that the lake’s water levels remained stable for millennia. This hypothesis, __________ that certain fish species, such as Tropheus moorii, thrived without major ecological disruptions throughout the Late Holocene, cannot hold, researchers Anna Müller and David Kim argue, unless alternative explanations are carefully excluded. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"suggesting"},{"id":"B","text":"suggested"},{"id":"C","text":"suggests"},{"id":"D","text":"has suggested"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of verb forms within a sentence. The nonfinite present participle “suggesting” is correctly used to form a participial phrase (“suggesting that certain fish species…thrived…”) within the main clause (“This hypothesis…cannot hold…”). This participial phrase functions as part of the sentence’s subject, providing essential identifying information about what the hypothesis states—namely, that certain fish species thrived without major ecological disruptions throughout the Late Holocene. Choice B is incorrect because the finite verb “suggested” cannot be used in this way within the subject of the sentence, making it ungrammatical. Choice C is incorrect because the finite verb “suggests” also cannot function as a participial phrase within the subject. Choice D is incorrect because the finite verb phrase “has suggested” cannot be used within the subject in this way and results in an ungrammatical sentence.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Chinua Achebe (1930–2013), a renowned Nigerian novelist, is widely celebrated for his literary works that _______ the depiction of African cultures, traditions, and oral storytelling in modern literature. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"revolutionized;"},{"id":"B","text":"revolutionized,"},{"id":"C","text":"revolutionized"},{"id":"D","text":"revolutionized:"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation use between a verb and its object. No punctuation is needed between the verb “revolutionized” and its object “the depiction of African cultures, traditions, and oral storytelling,” because the object completes the meaning of the verb. Inserting any punctuation between the verb and its object would make the sentence ungrammatical. Choice A is incorrect because the semicolon is unnecessary and interrupts the direct connection between the verb and its object. Choice B is incorrect because the comma is unnecessary and grammatically incorrect here. Choice D is incorrect because a colon is not needed; a colon is used to introduce a list, explanation, or amplification, not to separate a verb from its object.', 'standard-english', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • In 1889, Vincent van Gogh painted The Starry Night, an oil painting depicting a swirling night sky above a quiet village. • The painting measures 29 × 36 1/4 inches. • In 2012, contemporary artist Julie Mehretu painted Stadia II, a large-scale abstract painting inspired in part by van Gogh’s expressive use of movement. • Mehretu’s painting measures 72 × 108 inches. • Stadia II portrays overlapping forms of stadium architecture and crowds, evoking the chaos and energy of large events. The student wants to emphasize a similarity between the two paintings. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Van Gogh painted The Starry Night in 1889, while Mehretu completed Stadia II in 2012."},{"id":"B","text":"Both The Starry Night and Stadia II are large-scale paintings that use dynamic movement to create visual energy."},{"id":"C","text":"Mehretu’s painting portrays crowded stadiums, while van Gogh’s depicts a quiet village."},{"id":"D","text":"Stadia II was inspired in part by van Gogh’s work, but the subjects of the paintings are very different."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The sentence emphasizes a similarity between the two paintings, noting that both paintings are large in scale and use dynamic movement to create visual energy. Choice A is incorrect. The sentence provides the completion dates of the two paintings; it does not emphasize a similarity between them. Choice C is incorrect. The sentence emphasizes a difference between the paintings’ subjects; it does not emphasize a similarity. Choice D is incorrect. While the sentence notes that Stadia II was inspired by van Gogh’s painting, it focuses on differences in subject matter rather than a similarity between the two works.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • In 1841, the short story “The Murders in the Rue Morgue” was published in the United States. • The story is widely considered the first modern detective story. • When it was published, the author was listed as Edgar A. Poe. • Edgar A. Poe was a literary signature commonly used by the American writer Edgar Allan Poe. • Poe introduced the character C. Auguste Dupin, who later appeared in two additional stories. The student wants to identify the author of “The Murders in the Rue Morgue.” Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The author of “The Murders in the Rue Morgue” was Edgar Allan Poe, who published the story under the signature Edgar A. Poe."},{"id":"B","text":"“The Murders in the Rue Morgue” introduced the detective C. Auguste Dupin, who appeared in two later stories."},{"id":"C","text":"The title page of “The Murders in the Rue Morgue” listed Edgar A. Poe as the story’s author."},{"id":"D","text":"The signature Edgar A. Poe was commonly used by a writer who helped establish the modern detective genre."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. It clearly identifies the author—Edgar Allan Poe—and explains that the story was published using his recognized signature, Edgar A. Poe.Choice B is incorrect. It describes a character introduced in the story but does not identify the story’s author. Choice C is incorrect. It reports the name on the title page, but this is just the signature and does not explicitly identify the real author, Edgar Allan Poe. Choice D is incorrect. It indicates that the signature belonged to a writer in the detective genre, but it does not identify that writer by name or directly state the author of the story.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) maintains the Red List of Threatened Species. • Species on the Red List are assigned categories based on level of extinction risk. • A species facing an extremely high risk of extinction in the wild is classified as critically endangered. • A species facing a high risk of extinction in the wild is classified as endangered. • The Sumatran orangutan (Pongo abelii) is categorized by the IUCN as critically endangered. The student wants to indicate the Sumatran orangutan’s IUCN classification category. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The IUCN Red List includes species that are classified into categories such as endangered and critically endangered."},{"id":"B","text":"The Sumatran orangutan (Pongo abelii) appears on the IUCN’s Red List of Threatened Species."},{"id":"C","text":"According to the IUCN, the Sumatran orangutan is endangered, facing a high risk of extinction in the wild."},{"id":"D","text":"Facing an extremely high risk of extinction in the wild, the Sumatran orangutan is classified as critically endangered by the IUCN."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. It directly states the Sumatran orangutan’s IUCN classification—critically endangered—and accurately reflects the definition provided in the notes. Choice A is incorrect. It explains the categories used on the Red List but does not specify the Sumatran orangutan’s classification. Choice B is incorrect. It notes that the Sumatran orangutan appears on the Red List but fails to indicate its category. Choice C is incorrect. It incorrectly labels the species as endangered rather than critically endangered, making it factually inaccurate.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The Brooklyn Bridge connects Manhattan and Brooklyn in New York City. • Construction began in 1869 and was completed in 1883. • The bridge spans a total length of 1,595 feet. • It was the first steel-wire suspension bridge ever built. The student wants to emphasize the total length of the Brooklyn Bridge. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The Brooklyn Bridge, spanning 1,595 feet, connects the New York City boroughs of Manhattan and Brooklyn."},{"id":"B","text":"The Brooklyn Bridge was the first steel-wire suspension bridge ever constructed."},{"id":"C","text":"Completed in 1883, the Brooklyn Bridge linked two major New York City boroughs."},{"id":"D","text":"Work on the Brooklyn Bridge began in 1869 under the supervision of engineer John A. Roebling."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The sentence emphasizes the total length of the Brooklyn Bridge by stating that it spans 1,595 feet while also identifying the boroughs it connects. Choice B is incorrect. The sentence highlights the bridge’s engineering significance, not its length. Choice C is incorrect. The sentence mentions when the bridge was completed and what it connected but does not emphasize how long the bridge is. Choice D is incorrect. The sentence emphasizes when construction began and who supervised the project; it does not emphasize the bridge’s length.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Maria Reiche was a German-born scientist who worked in Peru. • Reiche devoted her career to studying the geometric lines and figures etched into the desert in southern Peru. • These ancient ground markings are known as the Nazca Lines. • A scientist who studies ancient human-made structures and artifacts is called an archaeologist. The student wants to identify what type of scientist Reiche was. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The Nazca Lines are large geometric figures carved into the Peruvian desert."},{"id":"B","text":"Many scientists study ancient structures such as the Nazca Lines."},{"id":"C","text":"Some scientists, known as archaeologists, study artifacts created by ancient cultures."},{"id":"D","text":"Reiche was an archaeologist."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. It directly identifies the type of scientist Reiche was: an archaeologist. Choice A is incorrect. It describes a feature of the Nazca Lines but does not identify Reiche’s scientific role. Choice B is incorrect. It states that many scientists study ancient structures but does not specify Reiche’s type of science. Choice C is incorrect. While it defines “archaeologist,” it does not apply that classification to Reiche.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'To ensure the safety and consistency of medications, pharmaceutical companies must produce drugs under tightly controlled conditions. _______ regulatory agencies established Good Manufacturing Practices (GMP), a set of international standards that define the precise conditions under which medicines must be produced and tested. These practices help guarantee that every batch of a drug meets the same quality standards. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"In contrast,"},{"id":"B","text":"Regardless,"},{"id":"C","text":"In addition,"},{"id":"D","text":"For this reason,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “For this reason” logically signals that the information that follows—that regulatory agencies established GMP standards—is a result of the previous claim that pharmaceutical companies must produce drugs under tightly controlled conditions to ensure safety and consistency. Choice A is incorrect because “in contrast” illogically signals that the information that follows contrasts with the previous claim about producing drugs under controlled conditions. Instead, the establishment of GMP standards is a direct result of that need. Choice B is incorrect because “regardless” illogically signals that the information that follows is true despite the previous claim about controlled production conditions. Instead, the establishment of GMP standards is a result of that claim. Choice C is incorrect because “in addition” illogically signals that the information that follows is merely an additional fact related to the previous claim. Instead, the establishment of GMP standards is a consequence of the need for controlled drug production.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Before the launch of the James Webb Space Telescope in 2021, astronomers could observe only nearby galaxies in limited detail using existing instruments. _______ they can study distant galaxies formed billions of years ago with unprecedented clarity. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Similarly,"},{"id":"B","text":"Therefore,"},{"id":"C","text":"Today,"},{"id":"D","text":"Nevertheless,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “Today” logically signals that the information in the sentence—that astronomers can now study distant galaxies formed billions of years ago—is true in the present day after the previously mentioned launch of the James Webb Space Telescope in 2021. Choice A is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that the information in the sentence describes something comparable to astronomers’ earlier ability to observe only nearby galaxies. Instead, the sentence describes what astronomers can do now, after the telescope’s launch. Choice B is incorrect because “therefore” illogically signals that the present-day ability to study distant galaxies is a direct conclusion rather than a temporal update following the launch. Instead, the sentence contrasts the past limitation with the present capability. Choice D is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically signals that the present-day ability to study distant galaxies is true despite the earlier limitation. Instead, the sentence explains the current situation after technological progress.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Egyptian mathematician Hypatia taught mathematics and astronomy in Alexandria. • She wrote commentaries on works by earlier mathematicians, including Diophantus and Apollonius. • Her commentary on Apollonius’s Conics is believed to have been completed around 400 CE. The student wants to specify when Hypatia completed her commentary on Apollonius’s work. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Around 400 CE, Hypatia completed her commentary on Apollonius’s Conics."},{"id":"B","text":"Hypatia, who taught mathematics and astronomy in Alexandria, wrote commentaries on several earlier authors."},{"id":"C","text":"Hypatia was an Egyptian mathematician known for producing influential scholarly commentaries."},{"id":"D","text":"In addition to teaching mathematics and astronomy, Hypatia wrote a commentary on Apollonius’s Conics."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. It directly specifies when Hypatia completed her commentary—around 400 CE—exactly satisfying the goal. Choice B is incorrect. It notes that Hypatia wrote commentaries but does not specify when she completed the one on Conics. Choice C is incorrect. It gives general background about Hypatia but fails to mention the timing of the commentary. Choice D is incorrect. It describes her activities but does not specify the approximate date of the commentary’s completion.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The Elephant Vanishes is a short story. • It was written by Japanese author Haruki Murakami. • It was first published in Japan in 1980. • The story is narrated in the first person. • It is set in a suburban district of Tokyo. The student wants to indicate where the short story takes place. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The Elephant Vanishes is set in a suburban district of Tokyo."},{"id":"B","text":"The Elephant Vanishes was written by Haruki Murakami."},{"id":"C","text":"The Elephant Vanishes is told from a first person point of view."},{"id":"D","text":"The Elephant Vanishes was first published in Japan in 1980."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. It directly indicates the setting of the story, stating that The Elephant Vanishes takes place in a suburban district of Tokyo. Choice B is incorrect. It identifies the author but does not state where the story is set. Choice C is incorrect. It explains the narrative perspective but does not address the setting. Choice D is incorrect. It gives publication information but does not indicate where the story takes place.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1990, environmental activist Wangari Maathai launched a campaign to plant trees across Kenya to combat deforestation. The initiative faced skepticism and limited funding, but Maathai was persistent. She partnered with local communities and NGOs, expanding the campaign steadily over the next decade. _____ in 2004, the movement had successfully planted over 30 million trees nationwide. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Instead,"},{"id":"B","text":"Likewise,"},{"id":"C","text":"Finally,"},{"id":"D","text":"Additionally,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “Finally” logically signals that the movement planting over 30 million trees—following many years of effort and expansion—is the final, concluding event in the sequence described in the previous sentences. Choice A is incorrect because “instead” illogically signals that this achievement is an alternative to one of the events described in the previous sentences. It is the final event in the sequence. Choice B is incorrect because “likewise” illogically signals that this achievement is similar to one of the events described in the previous sentences. Instead, it is the final event in the sequence. Choice D is incorrect because “additionally” illogically signals that this achievement is merely another event described along with the events of the previous sentences. Instead, it is the final, concluding event in the sequence.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The rotation speed of planets is measured by the length of their day. • One Earth day lasts 24 hours. • A day on Jupiter lasts about 9 hours and 56 minutes. • A day on Venus lasts about 243 Earth days. The student wants to highlight the rotation period of Venus. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Planetary rotation speeds can be compared by examining how long a day lasts on each planet."},{"id":"B","text":"One Earth day lasts 24 hours, a unit often used when describing planetary rotation speeds."},{"id":"C","text":"Jupiter has a rapid rotation, completing one day in about 10 hours."},{"id":"D","text":"With a rotation period of about 243 Earth days, Venus has one of the slowest days in the solar system."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. It directly emphasizes Venus’s rotation period, stating that a day on Venus lasts about 243 Earth days, which is the key detail. Choice A is incorrect because it discusses planetary rotation in general and does not highlight Venus. Choice B is incorrect because it explains the length of an Earth day rather than emphasizing Venus’s extremely long day. Choice C is incorrect because it focuses on Jupiter’s rotation period, not Venus’s.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the study of artificial intelligence, computer scientist Melanie Mitchell argues that researchers should move away from describing AI systems as “thinking.” _______ she suggests that they use the term “pattern recognition” to more accurately capture what such systems actually do when processing data. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Nevertheless,"},{"id":"B","text":"Therefore,"},{"id":"C","text":"Instead,"},{"id":"D","text":"Meanwhile,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “Instead” logically signals that the idea in this sentence—that researchers should use the term “pattern recognition”—is an alternative to the idea mentioned in the previous sentence (describing AI systems as “thinking”). Choice A is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically signals that the idea in this sentence is true despite the previous claim that researchers should avoid describing AI systems as “thinking.” Instead, the use of “pattern recognition” is an alternative to that phrasing. Choice B is incorrect because “therefore” illogically signals that the idea in this sentence is a result or consequence of the previous claim. Instead, the use of “pattern recognition” is an alternative term. Choice D is incorrect because “meanwhile” illogically signals that the idea in this sentence occurs at the same time as the idea in the previous sentence. Instead, the use of “pattern recognition” is an alternative to the previously mentioned use of “thinking.”', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Zora Neale Hurston was an American anthropologist, folklorist, and novelist. • In 1935, she published Mules and Men, a major collection of African American folklore. • Her novel Their Eyes Were Watching God was published in 1937 by J. B. Lippincott. • Hurston conducted extensive anthropological fieldwork in the American South and the Caribbean. • She was a central figure of the Harlem Renaissance. The student wants to introduce Hurston’s 1935 folklore collection. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Before writing Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937), Zora Neale Hurston conducted fieldwork in the American South and the Caribbean."},{"id":"B","text":"A major figure of the Harlem Renaissance, Hurston produced both fiction and anthropological studies throughout her career."},{"id":"C","text":"Published in 1935, Mules and Men is Zora Neale Hurston’s influential collection of African American folklore."},{"id":"D","text":"Hurston’s 1937 novel Their Eyes Were Watching God was released by J. B. Lippincott and remains widely taught today."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The sentence directly introduces Mules and Men, noting both its 1935 publication date and its nature as Hurston’s important folklore collection. Choice A is incorrect. While it references Hurston’s research and a later novel, it does not introduce the 1935 folklore collection. Choice B is incorrect. The sentence describes Hurston broadly as a writer and anthropologist but does not introduce the 1935 collection. Choice D is incorrect. It focuses on her 1937 novel rather than introducing the 1935 folklore collection.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: ⦁ The ancient city of Teotihuacan in central Mexico flourished between the 1st and 7th centuries CE. ⦁ Its urban layout features a highly regular grid aligned with astronomical events. ⦁ Archaeologist Saburo Sugiyama is among the scholars who argue that Teotihuacan’s civic planning reflects a cosmological worldview. ⦁ This interpretation is known as the cosmology thesis. ⦁ Sugiyama points to the alignment of the city’s Avenue of the Dead with solar phenomena as evidence. The student wants to present the cosmology thesis to an audience unfamiliar with Teotihuacan. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"According to Sugiyama, the Avenue of the Dead was aligned with the sun to express religious symbolism."},{"id":"B","text":"The cosmology thesis is supported by the fact that Teotihuacan’s major thoroughfare aligns with solar events."},{"id":"C","text":"The cosmology thesis maintains that Teotihuacan’s meticulously ordered urban grid—designed in antiquity and aligned with astronomical phenomena—reflects a cosmological worldview."},{"id":"D","text":"Ancient Mesoamerican cities were frequently shaped by religious, political, and astronomical considerations."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it clearly defines the cosmology thesis while supplying essential context for readers unfamiliar with Teotihuacan. It explains both the city’s antiquity and the astronomical alignments that underlie the thesis, thereby accomplishing the goal. Choice A is incorrect. While it mentions solar alignment, it focuses narrowly on a single detail rather than presenting the broader cosmology thesis to an unfamiliar audience. Choice B is incorrect. It refers to evidence supporting the thesis but does not explain what the thesis asserts, making it insufficient as an introduction. Choice D is incorrect. It offers a general statement about Mesoamerican cities but does not introduce the cosmology thesis or describe Teotihuacan in particular.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • "The Kiss" is an oil-on-canvas painting with gold leaf, silver, and platinum by Gustav Klimt. • It was created between 1907 and 1908 during Klimt’s "Golden Period." • The painting depicts a couple embracing, with the man in a geometric-patterned robe and the woman in a flowing floral dress. • The man’s face is mostly hidden as he bends to kiss the woman’s cheek; her eyes are closed and her face is upturned. • The painting is housed in the Österreichische Galerie Belvedere museum in Vienna, Austria. The student wants to emphasize a contrast between the figures in Klimt’s painting. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"\"The Kiss\" shows a couple embracing, with elaborate robes and floral motifs typical of Klimt’s \"Golden Period.\""},{"id":"B","text":"While both figures are central to the painting, the man’s face is mostly hidden as he leans down, whereas the woman’s face is fully visible, with closed eyes and an upturned expression."},{"id":"C","text":"Gustav Klimt’s \"The Kiss\" was first exhibited in 1908 at the Kunstschau in Vienna, where it was purchased by the Austrian government."},{"id":"D","text":"The painting uses gold leaf, silver, and platinum, reflecting Klimt’s ornamental style influenced by Byzantine mosaics."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The sentence emphasizes a contrast between the figures, noting that the man’s face is mostly hidden while the woman’s face is fully visible with a specific expression. Choice A is incorrect. The sentence describes both figures but emphasizes similarities rather than a contrast between them. Choice C is incorrect. The sentence provides historical information about the exhibition and acquisition; it doesn’t emphasize a contrast between the figures. Choice D is incorrect. The sentence focuses on the materials and style of the painting rather than highlighting a contrast between the figures.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Mary Shelley was an English novelist who wrote Frankenstein. • Frankenstein was first published in 1818. • Many literary historians consider Frankenstein one of the earliest works of science fiction. • The novel helped establish key themes of the genre, including scientific ambition and its consequences. The student wants to identify a novel that is considered an early example of science fiction. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Frankenstein, published in 1818, is widely regarded as one of the earliest works of science fiction."},{"id":"B","text":"Mary Shelley was an English novelist who explored themes of scientific ambition."},{"id":"C","text":"Mary Shelley’s writing influenced many later authors in the development of the science fiction genre."},{"id":"D","text":"One eighteenth-century novel examined the dangers and possibilities of scientific discovery."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The sentence correctly identifies the title of a novel—Frankenstein—and uses relevant information from the notes to indicate that it is considered an early example of science fiction. Choice B is incorrect because it provides background about Mary Shelley but does not identify the title of a novel considered an early science fiction work. Choice C is incorrect because it gives information about Shelley’s influence on later writers but does not specify a novel that is viewed as an early example of science fiction. Choice D is incorrect because it vaguely describes a novel from the eighteenth century without naming the title or indicating that it is considered an early science fiction work.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1901, Italian inventor Guglielmo Marconi conducted one of the first successful transatlantic wireless telegraphy experiments. As Marconi’s team transmitted the signal, it traveled through the atmosphere across thousands of kilometers. _______ a receiver in Newfoundland detected the faint Morse code signal, confirming that long-distance radio communication was possible. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"For example,"},{"id":"B","text":"Next,"},{"id":"C","text":"Similarly,"},{"id":"D","text":"On the other hand,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “Next” logically signals that the action in this sentence—the receiver detecting the Morse code signal—occurred as the next step in the sequence following the signal’s transmission. Choice A is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that the action in this sentence is an example of the signal transmission described in the previous sentence. Instead, the signal detection is the next step in a chronological process. Choice C is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that the action in this sentence is similar to the signal transmission described in the previous sentence. Instead, it follows it in sequence. Choice D is incorrect because “on the other hand” illogically signals that the action in this sentence contrasts with the previous action of signal transmission. Instead, it logically follows as the next event in the process.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The Marine Fossil Survey Project is widely recognized for the scale of its specimen database. _______ the project now houses over 12,000 cataloged fossils, including several rare whale vertebrae discovered in remote coastal cliffs. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Above all,"},{"id":"B","text":"In fact,"},{"id":"C","text":"Nevertheless,"},{"id":"D","text":"Before,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “In fact” logically signals that the information in this sentence—the large number of fossils and rare specimens—emphasizes and supports the previous claim that the Marine Fossil Survey Project is known for the scale of its database. Choice A is incorrect because “above all” illogically suggests a ranking of importance, as though this sentence lists the most important point rather than providing specific evidence supporting the claim about the project’s large database. Instead, the details strengthen the previous idea. Choice C is incorrect because “nevertheless” wrongly signals a contrast, even though the information in this sentence reinforces rather than contradicts the claim about the project’s extensive collection. Choice D is incorrect because “before” incorrectly indicates a temporal sequence. The sentence is not describing something that occurred earlier in time; it provides concrete details supporting the claim about the size of the database.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Ancient Egyptian scribes used hieroglyphs to document administrative details such as crop inventories and tax records. _______ they may also have used hieroglyphs to convey abstract concepts and philosophical ideas, according to recent archaeological findings. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"As a result,"},{"id":"B","text":"In other words,"},{"id":"C","text":"In addition,"},{"id":"D","text":"For example,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “In addition” logically signals that the claim in this sentence—that Egyptian scribes may have used hieroglyphs to convey abstract concepts and philosophical ideas—is an additional point related to the previous statement about their use of hieroglyphs to record administrative details. Choice A is incorrect because “as a result” illogically signals that the claim in this sentence is a consequence or result of the previous information about the scribes recording crop inventories and taxes. Instead, it adds another function of hieroglyphs. Choice B is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals that this sentence is merely a paraphrase or restatement of the previous sentence about recording administrative details. Instead, it presents a new, additional use. Choice D is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that this sentence provides an instance of the previous information about recording administrative details. Instead, it introduces a different, additional purpose for hieroglyphic writing.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • In the 1950s, linguist Kenneth L. Pike developed “tagmemics,” a framework for analyzing language through hierarchical units of meaning. • Around the same time, linguist Zellig Harris advanced “transformational analysis,” which examined how sentences could be systematically converted into related forms. • Both approaches emerged from structural linguistics but expanded its scope by proposing systematic methods for describing linguistic patterns. • Tagmemics and transformational analysis were later applied to fields beyond linguistics, including anthropology and early computational language processing. The student wants to emphasize a similarity between tagmemics and transformational analysis. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Pike’s tagmemics provided a hierarchical method for analyzing linguistic units, influencing fields such as anthropology."},{"id":"B","text":"Both tagmemics and transformational analysis extended structural linguistics by introducing systematic frameworks for describing language patterns."},{"id":"C","text":"Transformational analysis, developed by Zellig Harris, focused on converting sentences into related structural forms."},{"id":"D","text":"Although tagmemics and transformational analysis were developed in the same decade, they diverged in their specific analytical procedures."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. It emphasizes a similarity between the two linguistic approaches: both methods expanded structural linguistics by offering systematic frameworks for analyzing language patterns. Choice A is incorrect because it describes tagmemics alone and does not highlight any similarity with transformational analysis. Choice C is incorrect because it explains one feature of transformational analysis but fails to connect it to tagmemics or emphasize any similarity. Choice D is incorrect because it explicitly highlights a difference, not a similarity, stating that the two approaches diverged in analytical procedures.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Sound travels through substances as waves that vibrate particles in the medium. • Two common types of mechanical waves are longitudinal waves and transverse waves. • In longitudinal waves, particles vibrate parallel to the direction the wave travels. • In transverse waves, particles vibrate perpendicular to the direction the wave travels. • Both types require a medium—such as air, water, or solids—to move energy from one place to another. The student wants to emphasize something that longitudinal and transverse waves have in common. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Longitudinal and transverse waves both require a medium to transfer energy."},{"id":"B","text":"In longitudinal waves, particles vibrate parallel to the wave’s direction of travel."},{"id":"C","text":"Transverse waves cause particles to vibrate perpendicular to the direction of the wave."},{"id":"D","text":"Although both types of waves move through matter, their particle motions differ greatly."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. It emphasizes a similarity between longitudinal and transverse waves: both need a medium to carry energy. Choice B is incorrect because it describes only longitudinal waves and does not identify a similarity. Choice C is incorrect because it describes only transverse waves, not a shared characteristic. Choice D is incorrect because it emphasizes a difference—their particle motions—not a similarity.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2018, linguists studying endangered Indigenous languages in the Amazon documented a ritual chant used by the Yawalapiti people during seasonal festivals. They noticed that the chant’s rhythm and repetition seemed to foster a sense of community among participants. _______ the linguists suggested that the structure of the chant helped reinforce social bonds and maintain cultural traditions. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Therefore"},{"id":"B","text":"Conversely"},{"id":"C","text":"Nonetheless"},{"id":"D","text":"Likewise"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Therefore” logically signals that the action described in this sentence—the linguists suggesting that the chant reinforces social bonds—is a result or consequence of the previous observation that the chant fostered a sense of community. Choice B is incorrect because “conversely” illogically signals that the action described in this sentence contrasts with the previous observation. Instead, the action is a result or consequence of that observation. Choice C is incorrect because “nonetheless” illogically signals that the action occurs despite the previous observation. Instead, the action is a result or consequence of that observation. Choice D is incorrect because “likewise” illogically signals that this sentence merely adds another similar detail. Instead, the sentence describes an action that is a result or consequence of the observation.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Many scientists believe that Nikola Tesla exaggerated the practicality of his “World Wireless System,” a plan to transmit electricity globally without wires. No one can deny, _______ that Tesla’s groundbreaking work in alternating current technology transformed the way electricity is generated and distributed. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"therefore,"},{"id":"B","text":"in the same way,"},{"id":"C","text":"in contrast,"},{"id":"D","text":"though,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “Though” logically signals that the claim in this sentence—that Tesla’s innovations transformed the way electricity is generated and distributed (“No one can deny” it)—is true despite the previous information about Tesla’s exaggerated claims regarding his “World Wireless System.” Choice A is incorrect because “therefore” illogically signals that the claim in the sentence is a result of the previous information about Tesla’s impractical idea. Instead, the sentence states that Tesla’s contributions were significant—even if his claim was unrealistic. Choice B is incorrect because “in the same way” illogically signals that the claim in the sentence is similar to Tesla’s exaggerated claim. Instead, the sentence contrasts Tesla’s exaggeration with his genuine scientific impact. Choice C is incorrect because “in contrast” illogically signals that the claim in the sentence directly opposes the previous information about Tesla’s exaggeration. Instead, the sentence emphasizes that Tesla made real contributions—even if his earlier claim was overstated.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Mary Anning was a pioneering English fossil collector from Lyme Regis. • In 1811, she uncovered the first correctly identified Ichthyosaurus skeleton along the Blue Lias cliffs. • In 1823, she discovered the first complete Plesiosaurus skeleton near Lyme Regis. • Both Ichthyosaurus and Plesiosaurus are Mesozoic marine reptiles. • Her 1811 Ichthyosaurus find significantly increased scientific interest in extinct marine fauna. The student wants to highlight the importance of Anning’s 1811 Ichthyosaurus discovery. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Mary Anning, an influential fossil collector from Lyme Regis, made several groundbreaking discoveries of Mesozoic marine reptiles."},{"id":"B","text":"Although she later uncovered a complete Plesiosaurus skeleton in 1823, Anning’s 1811 discovery of the first correctly identified Ichthyosaurus dramatically advanced scientific understanding of extinct marine life."},{"id":"C","text":"Ichthyosaurus and Plesiosaurus, two Mesozoic marine reptiles, were both discovered by Mary Anning during her early career in fossil hunting."},{"id":"D","text":"In 1823, Mary Anning discovered the first complete Plesiosaurus skeleton, an event that established her prominence within the scientific community."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. It centers the significance of Anning’s 1811 Ichthyosaurus discovery and explains why it was important: it advanced scientific interest in extinct marine species. This directly aligns with the student’s goal. Choice A is incorrect. Though it introduces Anning and her contributions, it does not specifically emphasize the 1811 Ichthyosaurus discovery. Choice C is incorrect. It mentions both fossil finds but treats them equally, failing to foreground the 1811 discovery or explain its significance. Choice D is incorrect. It focuses entirely on the 1823 Plesiosaurus find and therefore does not highlight the 1811 Ichthyosaurus discovery.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Knitted from sustainably sourced wool and hand-embroidered using a stitching method taught by the artisan’s Indian mother, ___________ so richly detailed and visually captivating that viewers feel compelled to trace the patterns with their fingers. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. the botanical quilts of Canadian textile designer Priya Kapoor are"},{"id":"B","text":"B. the Canadian textile designer Priya Kapoor creates botanical quilts that are"},{"id":"C","text":"C. when she creates her botanical quilts, Canadian textile designer Priya Kapoor makes them"},{"id":"D","text":"D. Priya Kapoor is a Canadian textile designer whose botanical quilts are"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject–modifier placement. This choice makes the noun phrase “the botanical quilts of Canadian textile designer Priya Kapoor” the subject of the sentence and places it immediately after the modifying phrase “knitted from sustainably sourced wool and hand-embroidered using a stitching method taught by the artisan’s Indian mother.” In doing so, this choice clearly establishes that the quilts—and not another noun in the sentence—are being described as richly detailed and visually captivating. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “the Canadian textile designer Priya Kapoor” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that Kapoor is knitted from sustainably sourced wool and hand-embroidered. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the pronoun “she” and the noun phrase “Canadian textile designer Priya Kapoor” after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that Kapoor is knitted from sustainably sourced wool and hand-embroidered. Choice D is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun “Priya Kapoor” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that Kapoor is knitted from sustainably sourced wool and hand-embroidered.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A study conducted by ecologist Dr. Elena Martinez at the University of California, Davis found that urban raccoons that forage in human garbage have elevated levels of a synthetic chemical, _____ due to its prevalence in plastic containers and packaging. Raccoons with these elevated levels were also found to exhibit higher stress hormone concentrations compared with raccoons in rural environments. bisphenol A (BPA), Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"bisphenol A, (BPA)"},{"id":"B","text":"bisphenol A (BPA)"},{"id":"C","text":"bisphenol A, (BPA),"},{"id":"D","text":"bisphenol A (BPA),"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of a supplementary element within a sentence. The comma after “(BPA)” pairs with the natural pause in the sentence to separate the supplementary element “bisphenol A (BPA)” from the rest of the sentence. This element specifies the chemical, and the comma indicates that the phrase could be removed without affecting the grammatical coherence of the sentence. Choice A is incorrect because the comma after “bisphenol A” is unnecessary and separates the element incorrectly from the parentheses. Choice B is incorrect because it fails to include the comma after the parentheses, which is needed to maintain proper separation of the supplementary element. Choice C is incorrect because the comma after “bisphenol A” is unnecessary; the parentheses around “BPA” already serve to set off the supplementary element from the sentence.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Dr. Amina Rahman of the University of Nairobi noted that drought conditions limit the availability of nitrogen in the soil, restricting maize growth. If maize were planted in drought-prone areas alongside nitrogen-fixing legumes, _______ Rahman aimed to determine. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"could the maize flourish."},{"id":"B","text":"the maize could flourish."},{"id":"C","text":"the maize could flourish?"},{"id":"D","text":"could the maize flourish?"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is end-of-sentence punctuation. This choice correctly uses a question mark to punctuate the interrogative clause “could the maize flourish,” which asks a direct question at the end of the sentence. Choice A is incorrect because a period cannot be used to punctuate an interrogative clause at the end of a sentence. Choice B is incorrect because the context requires an interrogative clause. The declarative clause “the maize could flourish” incorrectly suggests it was already known that the maize could flourish, whereas Rahman was investigating this. Choice C is incorrect because a question mark cannot be used with a declarative clause like “the maize could flourish” in this context.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'To support rural communities during the early 20th century, pioneering teacher Samuel Thompson introduced bilingual education in both English and French, an innovative ________ organized weekly cultural fairs showcasing local crafts, foods, and music, and created storytelling sessions highlighting regional folklore. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"approach at the time"},{"id":"B","text":"approach at the time;"},{"id":"C","text":"approach, at the time"},{"id":"D","text":"approach, at the time,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the coordination of multiple main clauses within a single sentence. This choice correctly uses a semicolon to join the first clause (“To support rural communities during the early 20th century, pioneering teacher Samuel Thompson introduced bilingual education in both English and French, an innovative approach at the time”) with the second clause (“organized weekly cultural fairs showcasing local crafts, foods, and music, and created storytelling sessions highlighting regional folklore”). Choice A is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence. The two main clauses are fused without any punctuation or conjunction, which is grammatically incorrect. Choice C is incorrect because the comma incorrectly separates the phrase “at the time” from the noun it modifies, creating a grammatical pause that is unnecessary and disrupts sentence flow. Choice D is incorrect because placing two commas around “at the time” makes it a nonrestrictive phrase, which is not needed here and interrupts the logical connection between the innovative approach and Thompson’s subsequent actions.', 'standard-english', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In retrospect, considering the rapid advances in physics and mathematics during the early 20th century, the emergence of quantum mechanics seems almost inevitable. It is perhaps unsurprising,_________ that both Erwin Schrödinger and Werner Heisenberg developed foundational models of the theory around the same time. Indeed, defying the notion of solitary discovery, their work exemplifies how transformative ideas often arise simultaneously in the minds of multiple thinkers responding to the same intellectual climate. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"however,"},{"id":"B","text":"then,"},{"id":"C","text":"moreover,"},{"id":"D","text":"for example,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “Then” logically signals that the claim in this sentence—that both Erwin Schrödinger and Werner Heisenberg developed foundational models of quantum mechanics around the same time—follows naturally from the previous idea that the emergence of quantum mechanics was almost inevitable given the rapid advances in physics and mathematics during the early 20th century. Choice A is incorrect because “however” illogically signals that the claim in this sentence contrasts with the previous information about the inevitability of quantum mechanics. Instead, the fact that Schrödinger and Heisenberg developed similar models supports, rather than contradicts, that idea. Choice C is incorrect because “moreover” illogically signals that this sentence simply adds another related fact about the development of quantum mechanics. Instead, it presents a logical consequence of the conditions mentioned earlier. Choice D is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that this sentence provides an illustration of the previous idea about the inevitability of quantum mechanics. Instead, it presents a conclusion that logically follows from that idea.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Michael Jackson’s Thriller (1982) remains the best-selling album in history, with over 104 million copies sold worldwide. • In 1984, Jackson won eight Grammy Awards in a single night—a record for the most Grammys awarded to one artist in one year. • During a 1984 Pepsi commercial shoot, a pyrotechnic malfunction caused burns to Jackson’s scalp; the incident paradoxically boosted Thriller’s sales by over one million copies. • Jackson often used sunglasses, surgical masks, and elaborate disguises in public as part of a longstanding effort to maintain personal privacy. • His signature “Moonwalk” was inspired by earlier performers but became globally iconic due to Jackson’s technically precise adaptation. The student wants to make a generalization about the kinds of phenomena scholars could investigate using these notes. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Analysts can examine how unforeseen public incidents, such as Jackson’s 1984 Pepsi-commercial injury, correlate with sudden surges in commercial success."},{"id":"B","text":"Michael Jackson’s public appearances, influenced by his penchant for masks and disguises, illustrate the extent to which he sought to shield himself from media intrusion."},{"id":"C","text":"The Thriller album’s record-breaking sales and Jackson’s unprecedented Grammy sweep demonstrate his dominance across multiple entertainment metrics."},{"id":"D","text":"Researchers may use biographical evidence to explore how artistic innovation, commercial reception, and celebrity management practices intersect within popular culture."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The sentence makes a generalization about the types of phenomena that scholars could study—namely, intersections among innovation, reception, and celebrity management—using the variety of information in the notes. This directly mirrors the reference question’s requirement: to generalize the kind of study possible. Choice A is incorrect. Though accurate, it focuses on a single event and its commercial aftermath rather than offering a general statement about the broader investigative domain. Choice B is incorrect. The sentence centers on Jackson’s privacy-related behaviors, not on generalizable categories of scholarly inquiry. Choice C is incorrect. This option summarizes specific achievements, not the broader methodological or conceptual scope of studies that could make use of such notes.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1842, Austrian physicist Christian Doppler observed that the frequency of light and sound waves changes depending on the relative motion of the source and the observer, a phenomenon now known as the Doppler effect. _______ this principle was later applied to explain the redshift of distant stars, providing a cornerstone for modern astrophysics. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Fittingly,"},{"id":"B","text":"Similarly,"},{"id":"C","text":"However,"},{"id":"D","text":"In other words,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Fittingly” logically signals that the information in this sentence about the application of the Doppler effect—to explaining the redshift of distant stars—appropriately honors or follows from Doppler’s original observation about the change in frequency of waves due to relative motion. Choice B is incorrect because “similarly” illogically suggests that the application of the Doppler effect is merely comparable to the original observation, rather than a natural extension or meaningful consequence of it. Choice C is incorrect because “however” illogically signals a contrast, implying that the application of the Doppler effect contradicts Doppler’s original findings, which is not the case. Choice D is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals a restatement or clarification of the same idea, whereas the sentence actually presents a significant application and consequence of Doppler’s discovery.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Had the stratification of Earth’s primitive silicate shell been governed exclusively by gravitational segregation—whereby high-density metallic constituents descended toward the proto-core while lithophile components ascended—the upper mantle would exhibit pronounced deficits in chalcophile and siderophile trace elements. Yet, empirical geochemical analyses reveal concentrations of these elements substantially exceeding such theoretical expectations. Thus, it is highly plausible that late-accreting extraterrestrial bodies—asteroidal or cometary in origin—delivered a significant fraction of the mantle’s anomalous siderophile inventory subsequent to core formation. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"That said,"},{"id":"B","text":"Thus,"},{"id":"C","text":"For example,"},{"id":"D","text":"Likewise,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “Thus” correctly signals that the claim in this sentence regarding late-accreting extraterrestrial bodies follows logically from the information in the previous sentences. The preceding sentences establish that siderophile and chalcophile elements in the upper mantle are more abundant than predicted by a purely gravitational segregation model. This sentence claims, logically, that these anomalous elements were delivered by extraterrestrial material after core formation. Choice A is incorrect because “that said” illogically signals that the information in this sentence represents an exception or caveat to the previous information about mantle geochemistry. Instead, it is a direct consequence of the prior discussion. Choice C is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that the information about extraterrestrial material merely exemplifies the previous observation about elemental abundances. Instead, it is a new claim that explains the anomaly. Choice D is incorrect because “likewise” illogically signals that the information about extraterrestrial material is merely similar to the previous statement about elemental abundances. Instead, it presents a logically deduced cause for the observed concentrations.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Insects are hexapod invertebrates with a chitinous exoskeleton and a three-part body. • They are the most diverse group of animals, with over one million described species. • Fossils from the Paleozoic Era show that some ancient insects reached wingspans of up to 70 cm. • These large fossils help scientists study early insect evolution and changing environmental conditions. • Many major insect groups appear to have coevolved with flowering plants. A student wants to highlight why the unusually large Paleozoic insect fossils are scientifically important. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to achieve this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Some ancient insects had wingspans of up to 70 cm, far larger than the insects found today."},{"id":"B","text":"Insects are the most diverse group of animals, with more than a million described species and a wide range of body forms."},{"id":"C","text":"Because they reached wingspans of up to 70 cm, the giant Paleozoic fossils provide important evidence about early insect evolution and past environmental conditions."},{"id":"D","text":"Many major insect groups seem to have coevolved with flowering plants, which contributed to their overall diversity."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. It directly states why the fossils matter: their enormous size offers scientific insight into early insect evolution and ancient environmental conditions, which aligns with the student’s goal of emphasizing significance. Choice A is incorrect. While it accurately describes the fossils’ size, it does not explain why they are important. Choice B is incorrect. This option discusses insect diversity broadly but does not mention the fossils or their significance. Choice D is incorrect. Although true, this statement addresses coevolution with flowering plants, which is unrelated to the significance of giant Paleozoic fossils.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: ⦁ Nan Madol is an ancient city built on a series of artificial islets off the coast of Pohnpei in Micronesia. ⦁ Scholars believe construction of the site began around the 12th century. ⦁ LIDAR (Light Detection and Ranging) is a remote-sensing technology that uses pulsed laser light to generate detailed topographic data. ⦁ Archaeologist Patrick Nunn employed airborne LIDAR surveys to examine the region surrounding Nan Madol. ⦁ Nunn’s survey revealed previously undocumented causeways and structural foundations extending beyond the known boundaries of the site. The student wants to introduce Nunn’s findings to an audience unfamiliar with Nan Madol. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Nunn used airborne LIDAR surveys to produce detailed topographic data of the landscape surrounding Nan Madol."},{"id":"B","text":"LIDAR, a remote-sensing technology that employs laser pulses to map terrain, has become increasingly useful to archaeologists in recent decades."},{"id":"C","text":"By conducting airborne LIDAR surveys, Nunn identified extensive, previously unknown causeways and foundations surrounding Nan Madol, an ancient Micronesian city built atop artificial islets."},{"id":"D","text":"Built beginning in the 12th century, the ancient city of Nan Madol once extended across numerous artificial islets and may have been connected by causeways."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. It introduces both Nunn’s discoveries and essential context about Nan Madol for readers unfamiliar with the site. It explains what Nan Madol is and conveys the significance of Nunn’s LIDAR-based findings, fulfilling the goal in the prompt. Choice A is incorrect. While it mentions Nunn’s use of LIDAR, it does not explain what Nan Madol is, leaving the audience without necessary context. Choice B is incorrect. Although it accurately defines LIDAR, it does not present Nunn’s research and provides no information about Nan Madol. Choice D is incorrect. It offers historical context about Nan Madol but does not mention Nunn’s work, so it fails to introduce his findings to an unfamiliar audience.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: ⦁ The metric system is the internationally standardized system of measurement used by most countries. ⦁ The Imperial system, still common in the United States, uses units such as inches, pounds, and miles. ⦁ Metric units are based on powers of ten, making conversion between units straightforward. ⦁ Imperial units are not decimal-based, which can make conversions more complicated and error prone. The student wants to explain a practical benefit of using the metric system. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The Imperial system employs units like inches and miles, which differ from the standardized units used internationally."},{"id":"B","text":"Although the Imperial system remains prevalent in the United States, most countries have adopted the metric system."},{"id":"C","text":"Because metric units are organized in powers of ten, converting between them is far simpler and less error prone than converting between Imperial units."},{"id":"D","text":"Developed as an internationally standardized system of measurement, the metric system is widely used for scientific and commercial purposes."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it directly identifies a practical advantage of the metric system—its decimal-based structure, which makes conversions easier and reduces the likelihood of errors. This advantage is explicitly supported by the notes. Choice A is incorrect. It merely describes aspects of the Imperial system without explaining any benefit of the metric system. Choice B is incorrect. Although it contrasts global usage patterns, it does not describe a practical advantage of the metric system itself. Choice D is incorrect. While it provides background on the metric system, it does not articulate a specific practical benefit, which the question requires.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Far beneath the ocean’s surface, researchers discovered bacteria that can digest plastic using specialized enzymes. • A global study by scientists at KAUST found these marine microbes are widespread and genetically capable of consuming PET (polyethylene terephthalate), used in bottles and fabrics. • Their ability comes from a structural feature on the PET-degrading enzyme called PETase, known as the M5 motif. • The M5 motif acts as a molecular “fingerprint” indicating the enzyme can break down PET. • The discovery sheds light on how these enzymes evolved from other hydrocarbon-degrading enzymes and adapted to a new human-made carbon source. The student wants to present the study of plastic-degrading bacteria and its conclusions. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Researchers at KAUST discovered that some marine bacteria possess enzymes capable of digesting PET plastic."},{"id":"B","text":"The M5 motif on PETase acts as a molecular fingerprint, helping scientists determine which enzymes can break down PET."},{"id":"C","text":"A large-scale global study by KAUST scientists revealed that marine bacteria are widespread and genetically prepared to consume PET plastic, indicating how these enzymes evolved to exploit human-made carbon sources."},{"id":"D","text":"Marine bacteria have evolved enzymes that digest PET plastic, including the distinctive M5 motif on PETase."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The sentence presents both the study and its conclusions, explaining that the KAUST global study revealed the bacteria are widespread and genetically capable of digesting PET, and it highlights the broader significance regarding enzyme evolution and adaptation to human-made plastics. Choice A is incorrect. While it describes the discovery, it doesn’t present the conclusions or broader implications of the study. Choice B is incorrect. The sentence explains the function of the M5 motif but focuses narrowly on methodology rather than the study and its overall conclusions. Choice D is incorrect. The sentence notes a finding about PETase and the M5 motif but doesn’t present the full study or the conclusions drawn from it.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Astronomers classify galaxies according to their overall structure. • Spiral galaxies contain rotating disks of stars, gas, and dust, with arms that wind outward from a central bulge. • Elliptical galaxies contain older stellar populations and lack the distinct spiral arms seen in spiral galaxies. • Spiral galaxies typically exhibit significant ongoing star formation. • Elliptical galaxies show little to no current star formation. The student wants to contrast spiral galaxies with elliptical galaxies. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Spiral galaxies are characterized by rotating disks with winding arms and active star formation, whereas elliptical galaxies lack spiral structure, consist largely of older stars, and show little to no ongoing star formation."},{"id":"B","text":"Astronomers classify galaxies by their overall structure, identifying spiral galaxies by their disks of stars, gas, and dust and elliptical galaxies by their different stellar populations."},{"id":"C","text":"Spiral galaxies contain rotating disks of stars, gas, and dust, and elliptical galaxies are composed mainly of older stellar populations."},{"id":"D","text":"Because spiral galaxies typically exhibit ongoing star formation, astronomers classify them differently from elliptical galaxies, which are notable for their overall structure."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. It directly contrasts spiral and elliptical galaxies by highlighting multiple opposing features from the notes—structure (spiral arms versus lack of arms) and star formation activity (ongoing versus minimal)—thereby fully accomplishing the student’s goal. Choice B is incorrect. Although it mentions both galaxy types, it emphasizes classification rather than clearly contrasting their defining characteristics. Choice C is incorrect. This choice lists one feature of each galaxy type but does not explicitly contrast them or integrate multiple relevant differences. Choice D is incorrect. This choice gestures toward a contrast but is vague and incomplete, failing to clearly distinguish the defining properties of spiral and elliptical galaxies.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The earliest sections of the Great Wall date to the 7th century BC. • The Qin dynasty (221–206 BC) unified these early fortifications into one defensive system. • Later dynasties expanded the wall, but the Ming dynasty (1368–1644) built the most famous and best-preserved portions. • The Ming sections include as many as 25,000 watchtowers. • Total fortifications extend approximately 21,196 kilometers across northern China. • The Great Wall served military, administrative, and trade-related purposes along the Silk Road. A student wants to emphasize how the scale of the Great Wall changed under different dynasties. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to achieve this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The Great Wall stretches for about 21,196 kilometers across northern China, featuring thousands of watchtowers and numerous fortified passes."},{"id":"B","text":"Although early walls date to the 7th century BC, the Qin dynasty unified them into a single defensive line, which later dynasties—especially the Ming—greatly expanded and strengthened."},{"id":"C","text":"The Ming dynasty constructed the most recognizable sections of the Great Wall, using bricks and stone instead of rammed earth."},{"id":"D","text":"The Great Wall not only protected China’s northern border but also helped regulate trade along the Silk Road."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. It directly highlights how the scale changed over time, noting the early walls, the Qin unification, and the later large-scale expansion by subsequent dynasties—information explicitly aligned with the student’s goal of tracing growth across periods. Choice A is incorrect. While factually accurate, it describes the wall’s overall size, not how it changed under different dynasties. Choice C is incorrect. It focuses only on the Ming dynasty, providing no comparison to earlier construction or growth across time. Choice D is incorrect. It addresses the purposes of the wall, not changes in scale or development across dynasties.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Political realist Hans J. Morgenthau argued that human nature is inherently egoistic and driven by animus dominandi, the desire to dominate. • Morgenthau claimed that international politics is fundamentally a struggle for power, with states acting to maximize their power in pursuit of national interest. • His theory was influenced by Thomas Hobbes and Niccolò Machiavelli, both of whom emphasized power and self-interest in political life. • Kenneth Waltz later developed neorealism, also called structural realism. • Waltz argued that international conflict results from the anarchical structure of the international system, not from human nature. The student wants to use a quotation to challenge Morgenthau’s human-nature-based explanation for international conflict. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Morgenthau believed that states act to maximize power because human beings have an inherent “desire to dominate.”"},{"id":"B","text":"Hobbes and Machiavelli influenced Morgenthau’s belief that power and self-interest drive political behavior."},{"id":"C","text":"Waltz argued that conflict arises from the “anarchical structure” of the international system, not from human nature."},{"id":"D","text":"According to neorealism, developed by Waltz, states compete for power because they operate in an international system defined by anarchy."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. Using a quotation from Waltz, the sentence challenges Morgenthau’s claim that international conflict stems from human nature by arguing instead that it arises from the “anarchical structure” of the international system. Choice A is incorrect. Although the sentence includes a quotation, it quotes Morgenthau himself and therefore reinforces—rather than challenges—his human-nature-based explanation for conflict. Choice B is incorrect. The sentence explains the intellectual influences behind Morgenthau’s theory but does not use a quotation to challenge his explanation for conflict. Choice D is incorrect. While the sentence explains Waltz’s neorealist view, it does not include a quotation, and the question specifically asks for an option that uses a quotation to challenge Morgenthau’s explanation.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In debates over artificial intelligence ethics, scholars are divided between consequentialists and deontologists. ______ there are those who argue that the outcomes of AI systems determine their ethical value, and those who insist that ethical rules should guide AI design regardless of outcomes. Philosopher Shannon Vallor aligns with neither position entirely. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Furthermore"},{"id":"B","text":"B. By contrast"},{"id":"C","text":"C. Similarly"},{"id":"D","text":"D. That is"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “That is” logically signals that this sentence clarifies the terms of the ethical debate introduced in the previous sentence by explaining the difference between consequentialists and deontologists. Choice A is incorrect because “furthermore” illogically suggests that the information in this sentence is merely additional to (and separate from) the discussion about the ethical debate. Instead, the information about consequentialists and deontologists clarifies the terms of that debate. Choice B is incorrect because “by contrast” illogically signals that the sentence contrasts with the previous sentence, when it actually explains the positions being debated. Choice C is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that the sentence is simply comparable to the previous sentence, whereas it provides precise clarification of the terms of the debate.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'According to a 2023 policy brief from the United Nations Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO), private firms accounted for over two‑thirds of all green‑technology patent applications submitted between 2000 and 2022—highlighting how commercial innovation dominates the field. _________ this shift in patent ownership has been heralded as the rise of a “private‑sector green innovation era.” Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Similarly,"},{"id":"B","text":"For this reason,"},{"id":"C","text":"Furthermore,"},{"id":"D","text":"Appropriately,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “Appropriately” logically signals that the information in this sentence—the characterization of the shift in patent ownership as the rise of a “private‑sector green innovation era”—follows naturally from and is consistent with the previous sentence, which explains that private firms accounted for over two‑thirds of all green‑technology patent applications. Choice A is incorrect because “similarly” illogically suggests that the second sentence is merely comparable to the first, rather than highlighting a logical consequence or fitting interpretation of the data. Choice B is incorrect because “for this reason” incorrectly implies a direct causal relationship; while the second sentence elaborates on the trend, it does not present a cause-and-effect argument. Choice C is incorrect because “furthermore” signals an additional piece of information, whereas the second sentence interprets or characterizes the significance of the trend described in the first sentence, rather than simply adding new data.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'With her immersive soundscape Tides of Memory, Japanese composer Aiko Morita manages to craft an experience that is both soothing and disorienting. _____ as listeners step into the dimly lit hall and hear the layered echoes of distant waves drifting through hidden speakers, they find themselves calmed yet unsettled—as though crossing into a dreamlike realm where time moves differently. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Second,"},{"id":"B","text":"Instead,"},{"id":"C","text":"Indeed,"},{"id":"D","text":"Nevertheless,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “Indeed” logically signals that the description in this sentence—the dim lighting, drifting echoes, and dreamlike atmosphere that leave listeners “calmed yet unsettled”—provides added emphasis supporting the previous sentence’s claim that Morita’s soundscape is “both soothing and disorienting.” Choice A is incorrect because “second” illogically suggests that this description is merely the next point in a list, rather than specific evidence reinforcing the earlier claim about the experience Morita creates. The details in the sentence elaborate on the same idea, not a numbered sequence. Choice B is incorrect because “instead” incorrectly implies that the description contrasts with or replaces the previous statement. In reality, the sensory details deepen and support the original idea of the soundscape’s dual emotional effect. Choice D is incorrect because “nevertheless” wrongly indicates a contrast, as though the description is true despite the earlier claim. Instead, the sentence provides vivid, specific support for the notion that the installation is simultaneously calming and unsettling.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In his 2012 book The Social Conquest of Earth, biologist E. O. Wilson challenged traditional views about the forces driving human behavior. ________ Wilson argued that instead of being shaped solely by individual genes, human societies develop through the combined influence of both individual and group‑level selection. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Similarly,"},{"id":"B","text":"Finally,"},{"id":"C","text":"Therefore,"},{"id":"D","text":"Specifically,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “Specifically” logically signals that the information in this sentence about Wilson’s argument—that, according to Wilson, human societies develop through the combined influence of both individual and group‑level selection, rather than being shaped solely by individual genes—provides specific, precise details elaborating on the more general information in the previous sentence about how Wilson challenged traditional views regarding the forces driving human behavior. Choice A is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that the information in this sentence about Wilson’s argument is merely comparable to, but separate from, the general statement in the previous sentence. Instead, it provides specific, precise details elaborating on that information. Choice B is incorrect because “finally” illogically signals that the information in this sentence indicates a last step or conclusion in a process, which does not match the elaborative relationship here. Choice C is incorrect because “therefore” illogically signals a causal relationship, suggesting that Wilson’s argument is a direct result of the previous statement, rather than an elaboration providing detailed explanation.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'When ocean water becomes polluted with excess nitrogen from agricultural runoff, it can be treated through mechanical aeration, which increases oxygen levels and reduces algal blooms.______ the water can be purified through bioremediation: specialized microorganisms metabolize the nitrogen compounds, converting them into harmless gases that dissipate into the atmosphere, thereby restoring the ecosystem’s balance. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Alternatively,"},{"id":"B","text":"Specifically,"},{"id":"C","text":"For example,"},{"id":"D","text":"As a result,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Alternatively” logically signals that the water purification method described in this sentence—bioremediation using microorganisms—offers an alternative to the previously described method (mechanical aeration). Choice B is incorrect because “specifically” illogically signals that the purification method described in this sentence specifies or elaborates on an aspect of the previously described method (mechanical aeration). Instead, bioremediation is an alternative to that method. Choice C is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that the purification method described in this sentence is an example of the previously described method (mechanical aeration). Instead, bioremediation is an alternative to that method. Choice D is incorrect because “as a result” illogically signals that the purification method described in this sentence is a result or consequence of the previously described method (mechanical aeration). Instead, bioremediation is an alternative to that method.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A whale’s streamlined body may seem fishlike, enabling it to glide effortlessly through the ocean. ______ whales are often mistakenly classified as fish, aquatic creatures that breathe through gills, when in fact they are mammals—warm-blooded animals that breathe air through lungs and nurse their young with milk. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"That being said,"},{"id":"B","text":"However,"},{"id":"C","text":"For instance,"},{"id":"D","text":"Hence,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “Hence” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that whales are often mistakenly classified as fish—is a consequence of the previous information about whales’ streamlined, fishlike appearance. Choice A is incorrect because “that being said” illogically signals that this sentence qualifies or contrasts with the previous information about whales’ fishlike bodies. Instead, it presents a consequence of that information. Choice B is incorrect because “however” illogically signals that this sentence contrasts with the previous information about whales’ fishlike appearance. Instead, it presents a consequence of that appearance. Choice C is incorrect because “for instance” illogically signals that this sentence provides an example supporting the previous information about whales’ fishlike appearance. Instead, it presents a consequence of that information.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'During a 2020 test flight, AeroNova’s experimental drone suffered a critical malfunction: its navigation system failed mid-air, forcing an emergency landing. Afterward, instead of minimizing the issue, AeroNova’s lead engineer publicly addressed the failure and explained the steps being taken to prevent future malfunctions. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Afterward,"},{"id":"B","text":"Additionally,"},{"id":"C","text":"Indeed,"},{"id":"D","text":"Similarly,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Afterward” logically signals that the events described in this sentence—the engineer’s public acknowledgment of the malfunction and explanation of preventive measures—occurred after the drone’s navigation failure and are part of a chronological sequence of events. Choice B is incorrect because “additionally” illogically signals that the events described in this sentence merely occurred in addition to the drone’s malfunction. Instead, they occurred after the malfunction and are part of a chronological sequence of events. Choice C is incorrect because “indeed” illogically signals that the events described in this sentence emphasize or reinforce a statement made in the previous sentence. Instead, they occurred after the malfunction and are part of a chronological sequence of events. Choice D is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that the events described in this sentence are similar to the drone’s malfunction. Instead, they occurred after the malfunction and are part of a chronological sequence of events.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The modern Olympic Games were revived in 1896 in Athens, Greece. • The Games feature sports from diverse cultural and historical origins. • In the 2016 Rio Olympics, the American gymnast Simone Biles won gold in the individual all-around event. • Artistic gymnastics, Biles’s sport, has roots in European gymnastic traditions from the 19th century. • In the 2020 Tokyo Olympics (held in 2021), the Japanese athlete Momiji Nishiya won gold in skateboarding. • Skateboarding originated in the United States in the mid-20th century. The student wants to emphasize a difference in the historical origins of the sports represented by these Olympic champions. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Simone Biles won gold in artistic gymnastics at the 2016 Rio Olympics, which has European origins, while Momiji Nishiya won gold in skateboarding at the 2020 Tokyo Olympics, which originated in the United States."},{"id":"B","text":"At the 2016 Rio Olympics, Simone Biles won gold in gymnastics, and at the 2020 Tokyo Olympics, Momiji Nishiya won gold in skateboarding."},{"id":"C","text":"Momiji Nishiya’s gold medal in skateboarding at the 2020 Tokyo Olympics highlights the popularity of the sport in Japan."},{"id":"D","text":"The Olympic Games feature sports from diverse cultural and historical origins, such as gymnastics and skateboarding."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The sentence emphasizes a difference in the historical origins of the sports by noting that artistic gymnastics has European roots, while skateboarding originated in the United States. Choice B is incorrect. While the sentence mentions the champions and their sports, it does not highlight a difference in the sports’ historical origins. Choice C is incorrect. The sentence focuses only on skateboarding and its popularity in Japan; it does not mention a comparison to another sport. Choice D is incorrect. The sentence generalizes Olympic sports’ diverse origins; it does not emphasize a difference between the two specific sports.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Traditional Japanese woodblock prints (ukiyo-e) were produced using handmade washi paper derived from mulberry bark. • Washi is prized for its tensile strength, absorbency, and durability. • Contemporary printmakers continue to produce ukiyo-e replicas using washi, though some incorporate synthetic pigments and chemical stabilizers. • Despite these additions, the core substrate in most replicas remains handmade washi. • Master printers argue that the structural integrity and visual quality of ukiyo-e replicas depend on the predominance of traditional materials. The student wants to make a generalization about the materials used in ukiyo-e replicas. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Washi, a traditional mulberry-bark paper known for its tensile strength, was historically essential to Japanese printmaking."},{"id":"B","text":"Although synthetic pigments and chemical stabilizers are sometimes incorporated, contemporary ukiyo-e replicas rely chiefly on traditional materials such as handmade washi."},{"id":"C","text":"Ukiyo-e prints, which originated in early modern Japan, were created using highly specialized tools and artisanal printing techniques."},{"id":"D","text":"Many master printers emphasize the visual superiority of handmade washi, arguing that without it the tactile qualities of ukiyo-e cannot be preserved."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. It makes a generalization about materials used in ukiyo-e replicas, stating that although some modern materials are incorporated, traditional materials—especially handmade washi—predominate, directly reflecting the notes. Choice A is incorrect because it focuses on the properties and historical use of washi but does not generalize about materials used in replicas. Choice C is incorrect because it gives contextual information about ukiyo-e’s origins and techniques but does not address the materials used in replicas. Choice D is incorrect because it reports printers’ opinions about the importance of traditional materials but does not make a broad generalization about the actual mixture of traditional and modern materials in replicas.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • In 1964, Murray Gell-Mann and George Zweig independently proposed the existence of quarks to explain the structure of hadrons. • Gell-Mann introduced the term “quarks” and developed the Eightfold Way, a classification system predicting their existence. • In 1968, experiments at the Stanford Linear Accelerator Center (SLAC) revealed point-like particles inside protons. • These experiments were conducted by Jerome I. Friedman, Henry W. Kendall, and Richard E. Taylor. • The results provided the first experimental evidence supporting the quark model. A student wants to highlight the contrast between the theoretical proposal of quarks and the later experimental evidence that confirmed their existence. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The 1968 SLAC experiments showed that protons contain point-like constituents, supporting a model earlier proposed by Gell-Mann and Zweig."},{"id":"B","text":"Physicists Friedman, Kendall, and Taylor conducted high-energy electron-proton scattering experiments that revealed the internal structure of protons."},{"id":"C","text":"The Eightfold Way, developed by Gell-Mann, was a classification system predicting quarks based on the observed behavior of hadrons."},{"id":"D","text":"Whereas Gell-Mann and Zweig theorized the existence of quarks in 1964, the SLAC experiments four years later provided the first experimental evidence confirming those predictions."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The sentence effectively contrasts the 1964 theoretical proposal of quarks with the 1968 experimental confirmation, clearly accomplishing the student’s goal. Choice A is incorrect. Although it connects theory and experiment, it does not explicitly contrast the theoretical proposal with the later confirmation. Choice B is incorrect. It describes the SLAC experiments but does not mention the earlier theoretical predictions, so it fails to contrast them. Choice C is incorrect. It details only the theoretical side—the Eightfold Way—and does not address experimental confirmation, so it does not create a contrast.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: ⦁ Both photosynthesis and chemosynthesis are processes that enable organisms to produce their own food. ⦁ Photosynthetic organisms use sunlight as an energy source. ⦁ Chemosynthetic organisms use chemical energy derived from reactions such as the oxidation of hydrogen sulfide. ⦁ Photosynthesis requires light but does not require hydrogen sulfide. ⦁ Chemosynthesis occurs in environments without sunlight, such as deep-sea vents. ⦁ Chemosynthesis does not require light but does require chemicals like hydrogen sulfide. The student wants to highlight a key distinction between photosynthesis and chemosynthesis. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Both photosynthesis and chemosynthesis enable organisms to produce food in their environments."},{"id":"B","text":"Photosynthetic and chemosynthetic organisms rely on external energy sources to power food-producing reactions."},{"id":"C","text":"Photosynthesis requires sunlight, and sunlight reaches Earth’s surface during the daytime."},{"id":"D","text":"Photosynthesis relies on light for energy, whereas chemosynthesis uses chemical reactions—such as the oxidation of hydrogen sulfide—instead."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. It directly emphasizes a clear distinction between photosynthesis and chemosynthesis: the former depends on light, while the latter depends on chemical energy such as hydrogen sulfide oxidation. Choice A is incorrect. Although true, it only states what the processes have in common; it does not highlight a distinction. Choice B is incorrect. It provides a broad similarity between the two processes, not the key difference the student wants to emphasize. Choice C is incorrect. While accurate about photosynthesis needing light, the second clause introduces irrelevant information (daytime sunlight) and does not contrast photosynthesis with chemosynthesis.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the decades after the Industrial Revolution, European manufacturing practices experienced a profound shift, driven largely by rising urban populations and expanding commercial markets. The increased production, distribution, and export of coal-powered machinery, __________ reshaped established regional industries into an interconnected global manufacturing network. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"in particular,"},{"id":"B","text":"alternatively,"},{"id":"C","text":"by comparison,"},{"id":"D","text":"second of all,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “In particular” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that the production, distribution, and export of coal-powered machinery reshaped regional industries into a global manufacturing network—provides specific, precise details elaborating on the more general information in the previous sentence about the profound shift in European manufacturing practices following the Industrial Revolution. Choice B is incorrect because “alternatively” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is being offered as an alternative option to the previous information about changes in European manufacturing. Instead, the role of coal-powered machinery is a specific, precise detail elaborating on that transformation. Choice C is incorrect because “by comparison” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is being compared to the previous information about manufacturing shifts. Instead, the increased production and export of coal-powered machinery provide specific, precise details elaborating on that shift. Choice D is incorrect because “second of all” illogically signals that the information in this sentence constitutes a second, separate point following an earlier enumerated point. Instead, the role of coal-powered machinery is not a separate claim but a specific, precise detail elaborating on the broader transformation described in the first sentence.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 2),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the mid-nineteenth century, steam locomotives were often called iron horses after the animal power they were gradually replacing. Known as the Age of Steam, this period in railway history is remembered for its engineering marvels and dramatic speed, its engines ________ by historians for their intricate machinery and polished metalwork. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"are highly valued"},{"id":"B","text":"had been highly valued"},{"id":"C","text":"highly valued"},{"id":"D","text":"were highly valued"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of verb forms in a sentence. The nonfinite past participle phrase “highly valued” is correctly used to form a supplementary element that modifies the main clause (“this period in railway history is remembered for its engineering marvels and dramatic speed”), describing notable features of the Age of Steam and why historians admire its engines. Choice A is incorrect because it results in a comma splice. Using the finite present-tense verb phrase “are highly valued” creates a second main clause in the sentence, and two main clauses cannot be joined with only a comma after “speed.” Choice B is incorrect because it results in a comma splice. Using the finite past perfect verb phrase “had been highly valued” creates a second main clause in the sentence, and two main clauses cannot be joined with only a comma after “speed.” Choice D is incorrect because it results in a comma splice. Using the finite past-tense verb phrase “were highly valued” creates a second main clause in the sentence, and two main clauses cannot be joined with only a comma after “speed.”', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Italian astronomer and physicist Galileo Galilei’s _______ widely celebrated during his lifetime (1564–1642) and in the years immediately following, had, by the time of their renewed examination by nineteenth-century scientists, been largely overshadowed by later developments in classical mechanics. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"discoveries were"},{"id":"B","text":"discoveries, were"},{"id":"C","text":"discoveries,"},{"id":"D","text":"discoveries had been"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of punctuation and verb forms within a sentence. This choice leaves the verb “celebrated” in its nonfinite past participle form to function within a supplementary element (“widely…following”). Offset by commas after “discoveries” and “following,” this supplementary element interrupts the main clause (“Italian astronomer and physicist Galileo Galilei’s discoveries…had…been largely overshadowed…”) with additional information about the discoveries’ reception during Galileo’s lifetime. Choice A is incorrect because it fails to offset the supplementary element (“widely…following”) with appropriate punctuation, and using the finite verb “were widely celebrated” results in an ungrammatical sentence. Choice B is incorrect because using the finite verb “were widely celebrated” results in an ungrammatical sentence. Choice D is incorrect because it fails to offset the supplementary element (“widely…following”) with appropriate punctuation, and using the finite verb “had been widely celebrated” results in an ungrammatical sentence.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Martin Scorsese, acclaimed American filmmaker and historian of cinema, directed the gritty crime drama Mean Streets in 1973; the psychological thriller __________ and the biographical epic Raging Bull in 1980, each film marking a new stage in his lifelong exploration of morality, violence, and redemption in American life. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Taxi Driver in 1976,"},{"id":"B","text":"Taxi Driver in 1976;"},{"id":"C","text":"Taxi Driver in 1976"},{"id":"D","text":",Taxi Driver in 1976,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of items in a complex series. It’s conventional to use a semicolon to separate items in a complex series that already contain internal commas, and in this choice, the semicolon after “1976” is correctly used to separate the second item (“the psychological thriller Taxi Driver in 1976”) and the third item (“the biographical epic Raging Bull in 1980”) in the series of Scorsese’s films. Further, the semicolon after “1973” in the first part of the sentence correctly separates the first item (“the gritty crime drama Mean Streets in 1973”) and the second item (“the psychological thriller Taxi Driver in 1976”) in the same series. Altogether, the punctuation in this choice results in a sentence that clearly and logically lists three distinct works directed by Scorsese. Choice A is incorrect because it fails to punctuate the complex series in a way that distinguishes Taxi Driver and Raging Bull as separate items, creating ambiguity about how many films are listed. Choice C is incorrect because without the semicolon, the sentence lacks clear separation between the second and third items in the complex series, making it difficult to parse the list. Choice D is incorrect because the comma after “D” disrupts the grammatical flow and incorrectly punctuates the appositive phrase, resulting in an ungrammatical construction.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Based on linguistic evidence, historians have long believed that the earliest written form of the Basque language appeared during the medieval period. However, after discovering inscriptions on pottery shards dated to 200 BCE, ______ may have existed far earlier than previously assumed. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"linguist Amaia Lasa has proposed that written Basque"},{"id":"B","text":"linguist Amaia Lasa’s proposal is that written Basque"},{"id":"C","text":"written Basque, linguist Amaia Lasa has proposed,"},{"id":"D","text":"the proposal linguist Amaia Lasa has made is that written Basque"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The convention being tested is logical subject placement and sentence structure following an introductory modifier. Choice A correctly provides a complete, logically ordered clause—“linguist Amaia Lasa has proposed that written Basque may have existed far earlier…”—that clearly identifies who made the claim and what the claim concerns. Choice B is incorrect because the construction “linguist Amaia Lasa’s proposal is that…” produces a wordier, less direct structure that interrupts the logical flow of the sentence. Choice C is incorrect because the placement of the noun “written Basque” immediately after the modifier “after discovering inscriptions…” illogically suggests that the language itself made the discovery. Choice D is incorrect because “the proposal linguist Amaia Lasa has made is that…” creates unnecessary repetition and awkwardness, making the sentence less concise and fluent.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The Library of Alexandria in ancient Egypt was one of the most renowned centers of knowledge in the ancient world. In 48 BCE, a fire _______ during Julius Caesar’s military campaign and destroyed thousands of invaluable scrolls. Though many attempts were later made to rebuild, the original library never recovered. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"breaks out"},{"id":"B","text":"will break out"},{"id":"C","text":"has broken out"},{"id":"D","text":"broke out"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of verbs to express tense. In this choice, the past tense verb “broke out” is consistent with the other past tense verbs (“destroyed” and “were”) used to describe the loss of the original library. Choice A is incorrect because the present tense verb “breaks out” is inconsistent with the other past tense verbs describing a historical event. Choice B is incorrect because the future tense verb “will break out” indicates an event that has not yet occurred. Choice C is incorrect because the present perfect tense verb “has broken out” suggests an action continuing to affect the present, which is not appropriate in this historical context.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Marine biologist Dr. Samuel Nguyen aimed to study whether octopuses can recognize individual humans. He first trained the animals to associate specific visual cues with food rewards. _______ he installed underwater cameras to record the octopuses’ reactions whenever a familiar or unfamiliar researcher approached their tanks. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Specifically,"},{"id":"B","text":"Next,"},{"id":"C","text":"For instance,"},{"id":"D","text":"In summary,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “Next” logically signals that the action described in this sentence—Nguyen installing cameras—is the subsequent step in his experimental procedure. Choice A is incorrect because “specifically” illogically suggests that the sentence elaborates on the previous training step rather than describing the next step. Choice C is incorrect because “for instance” illogically implies that the camera installation is an example of the training, rather than a sequential step. Choice D is incorrect because “in summary” illogically signals that this sentence concludes or summarizes the previous step instead of describing the next phase of the experiment.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Collaborating with the Kenyan Wildlife Service, Dr. Amina Njoroge studied rainfall patterns across the Rift Valley. She discovered that rainfall peaked in early April in the lowland savannas. At higher altitudes,____________ precipitation reached its highest levels in late April. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"in other words,"},{"id":"B","text":"for instance,"},{"id":"C","text":"on the other hand,"},{"id":"D","text":"in summary,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “On the other hand” logically signals that the information in the sentence—that precipitation at higher altitudes in the Rift Valley reached its highest levels in late April—contrasts with the previous information about rainfall in the lowland savannas peaking in early April. Choice A is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals that the information in the sentence is merely a paraphrase or restatement of the previous information about rainfall in the lowland savannas. Instead, the information about rainfall at higher altitudes contrasts with that information. Choice B is incorrect because “for instance” illogically signals that the information in the sentence exemplifies the previous information about rainfall in the lowland savannas. Instead, the information about rainfall at higher altitudes contrasts with that information. Choice D is incorrect because “in summary” illogically signals that the information in the sentence summarizes the previous information about rainfall in the lowland savannas. Instead, the information about rainfall at higher altitudes contrasts with that information.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'According to the Laffer curve theory, when tax rates become excessively high, government revenue eventually declines because individuals and businesses are disincentivized from earning or reporting income. __________ when tax rates are moderate, they encourage greater economic activity and compliance, thereby maximizing overall tax revenue and sustaining long-term fiscal growth. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Subsequently,"},{"id":"B","text":"Conversely,"},{"id":"C","text":"For instance,"},{"id":"D","text":"In other words,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “Conversely” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that moderate tax rates encourage greater economic activity and compliance—contrasts with the previous information about excessively high tax rates reducing government revenue. Choice A is incorrect because “subsequently” illogically signals that the information in this sentence occurs later in time than the decline in revenue described in the previous sentence. Instead, it presents an opposing situation, not a chronological one. Choice C is incorrect because “for instance” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is an example of the situation in the previous sentence, whereas it actually describes a contrasting economic condition. Choice D is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is a restatement or clarification of the previous idea, rather than a contrast to it.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Certain species of deep-sea squid use light-producing organs called photophores to communicate and attract prey. When specialized cells in the photophores react with chemicals in the squid’s tissue, bioluminescence occurs, producing a vivid glow. _______ when the squid inhibits the chemical reaction, the light disappears almost immediately. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"For instance,"},{"id":"B","text":"By contrast,"},{"id":"C","text":"Specifically,"},{"id":"D","text":"In conclusion,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “By contrast” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that the glow disappears when the chemical reaction is inhibited—contrasts with the previous sentence’s discussion of the processes that cause the squid to begin producing light. Choice A is incorrect because “for instance” illogically signals that the sentence exemplifies the previous discussion. Instead, it highlights an opposing or contrasting condition. Choice C is incorrect because “specifically” illogically signals that the sentence elaborates on or provides details of the previous description. Instead, it contrasts with the previous description of how the glow occurs. Choice D is incorrect because “in conclusion” illogically signals a summary of the previous sentence. Instead, the sentence presents a contrasting scenario rather than a conclusion.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • The venom of the Amazonian scorpion Brotheas amazonicus may contain a compound that helps treat breast cancer. • Breast cancer remains one of the leading causes of death among women. • Researchers at the University of São Paulo’s Ribeirão Preto School of Pharmaceutical Sciences (FCFRP-USP) identified a molecule in the scorpion’s toxin that attacks breast cancer cells similarly to a common chemotherapy drug. • The study involved collaboration with scientists from the National Institute for Amazonian Research (INPA) and Amazonas State University (UEA). • Findings were presented during FAPESP Week France in the Occitanie region of southern France. The student wants to present the study and its methodology. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The venom of Brotheas amazonicus contains a compound that attacks breast cancer cells similarly to a chemotherapy medication."},{"id":"B","text":"To explore potential treatments for breast cancer, researchers at FCFRP-USP, in collaboration with INPA and UEA, identified a molecule in the venom of Brotheas amazonicus."},{"id":"C","text":"Findings presented at FAPESP Week France showed that a molecule in scorpion venom may help treat breast cancer."},{"id":"D","text":"Breast cancer remains one of the leading causes of death among women, and researchers found a compound in Amazonian scorpion venom that might combat it."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The sentence presents both the study and its methodology, explaining that researchers at FCFRP-USP, working collaboratively with INPA and UEA, identified a molecule in the scorpion venom to explore potential treatments for breast cancer. Choice A is incorrect. The sentence summarizes the findings of the study; it doesn’t present the study or its methodology. Choice C is incorrect. While the sentence mentions the presentation of findings, it focuses on results rather than describing the study and methodology. Choice D is incorrect. The sentence highlights the significance of breast cancer and mentions the discovery, but it doesn’t convey the research process or collaborative methodology.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2020, a simulation created by planetary scientist Rafael Moreno and his colleagues demonstrated that the same volcanic eruptions responsible for shaping Mars’s Tharsis region—a vast plateau formed billions of years ago—also played a key role in altering the planet’s early atmosphere. _________ the simulation showed how sustained outgassing released heat-trapping compounds that gradually transformed Mars’s climate over millions of years. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Hence,"},{"id":"B","text":"However,"},{"id":"C","text":"Admittedly,"},{"id":"D","text":"Specifically,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “Specifically” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that sustained outgassing released heat-trapping compounds that gradually transformed Mars’s climate—provides specific, precise details elaborating on the more general information in the previous sentence about the connection between ancient volcanic eruptions and changes to Mars’s early atmosphere. Choice A is incorrect because “hence” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is a result of the information in the previous sentence about the role of volcanic eruptions in altering the atmosphere. Instead, this sentence offers specific, precise details expanding on that information. Choice B is incorrect because “however” illogically signals that the information in this sentence contrasts with the information in the previous sentence about how volcanic activity influenced atmospheric development. Instead, this sentence provides specific, precise details elaborating on that information. Choice C is incorrect because “admittedly” illogically signals that the information in this sentence introduces an exception or concession to the previous information about the relationship between volcanic eruptions and atmospheric change. Instead, this sentence provides specific, precise details elaborating on that information.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: ⦁ Olafur Eliasson is an Icelandic-Danish artist known for installations that explore light, perception, and natural phenomena. ⦁ He created The Weather Project in 2003. ⦁ The Weather Project featured a semicircular disc made of hundreds of lamps that created the illusion of a glowing sun. ⦁ Mist machines and mirrors enhanced the immersive atmosphere of the installation. The student wants to give a clear sense of what The Weather Project is like to viewers unfamiliar with Eliasson’s work. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Eliasson’s 2003 installation The Weather Project used lamps, mirrors, and mist to simulate atmospheric effects."},{"id":"B","text":"Olafur Eliasson, an Icelandic-Danish artist concerned with perception and natural phenomena, created The Weather Project."},{"id":"C","text":"The semicircular disc in The Weather Project consisted of hundreds of lamps arranged to resemble a radiant sun."},{"id":"D","text":"In The Weather Project, a 2003 installation by Icelandic-Danish artist Olafur Eliasson, a vast mist-filled hall and a lamp-lit “sun” reflected in mirrors combined to create an immersive atmospheric illusion."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it fully orients readers who do not know Eliasson: it identifies him, states when the work was created, and provides vivid details about the mist, mirrors, and sun-like disc that characterize The Weather Project. It presents a complete, descriptive sense of what encountering the installation is like. Choice A is incorrect. Although it mentions several elements of the installation, it does not identify Eliasson and thus fails to introduce the artist to an unfamiliar audience, making the description incomplete for the given goal. Choice B is incorrect. While it identifies who Eliasson is and that he created The Weather Project, it provides no descriptive detail about the installation itself, so it does not help readers visualize or understand the work. Choice C is incorrect. It describes only one component of the installation, the lamp-filled disc, without situating Eliasson or giving a broader picture of what the full experience of the work is like, making it insufficient for describing the installation to an unfamiliar audience.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Lewis Carroll’s Alice in Wonderland: Down the Rabbit-Hole. Alice was beginning to get very tired of sitting by her sister on the bank, and of having nothing to do: once or twice she had peeped into the book her sister was reading, but it had no pictures or conversations in it, “and what is the use of a book,” thought Alice, “without pictures or conversations?” Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To show that Alice is frustrated with having nothing engaging to do"},{"id":"B","text":"To explain why Alice enjoys reading books with her sister"},{"id":"C","text":"To describe the scenery by the riverbank"},{"id":"D","text":"To demonstrate how Alice has a long-standing habit of reading"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately states the main purpose of the text. The passage shows that Alice is “very tired of sitting… and of having nothing to do” and expresses her frustration with her sister’s book because it lacks pictures or conversations, which she finds entertaining. Thus, the main purpose of the text is to show that Alice is frustrated with having nothing engaging to do. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not indicate that Alice enjoys reading the book; in fact, she finds it uninteresting. Choice C is incorrect because while the setting is mentioned (by the bank), the text’s main focus is Alice’s feelings of boredom, not the scenery. Choice D is incorrect because the passage focuses on Alice’s current experience of boredom, not a habitual or long-standing reading practice.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Artificial light at night is known to affect animal behavior, though the extent to which these effects persist during daytime hours remains uncertain. Proposing that nocturnal light exposure alters animals’ circadian rhythms in ways that carry over into the following day, Lina Martinez and colleagues studied activity patterns in urban and rural populations of a migratory bird species. The researchers observed, however, that while nighttime activity differed significantly between the two populations, daytime activity levels were nearly identical. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It introduces an unresolved scientific question, outlines a hypothesis addressing that question, and then describes evidence that contradicts the hypothesis."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It presents a biological phenomenon that is poorly understood, describes a research team’s hypothesis about that phenomenon, and then reports findings that led the team to modify the hypothesis."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It explains a well-established theory, discusses alternative explanations for that theory, and then shows how a study confirmed one explanation over the others."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It summarizes a debated hypothesis, explains the methodology used to test it, and then presents results that support the hypothesis."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is correct because the text first raises an unresolved question about whether the effects of artificial nighttime light extend into daytime behavior, then presents a hypothesis proposing that such effects do persist, and finally describes observations showing that daytime activity did not differ, contradicting the hypothesis. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not indicate that the researchers refined or revised their hypothesis after the findings. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not discuss competing explanations or confirm any theory. Choice D is incorrect because although the hypothesis is tested, the results described do not support it.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Louisa May Alcott’s 1868 novel Little Women. Jo, one of the March sisters, is working to improve her writing. Jo’s ambition was to do something very splendid; what, she had no idea. “It’s genius, I suppose,” she said to herself, “but I don’t know what to do with it. I’m too young to be proper, and I’m too old to be careless.” She read all the books she could find, and kept a notebook full of hints and plans, scribbled at all hours of the day in a state of great excitement. Still, nothing seemed good enough. Each new story she started filled her with hope, and each one she finished struck her as not nearly what she had imagined. Yet Jo refused to give up, convinced that if she kept writing, the right idea would come. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To show Jo’s frustration with the kinds of books available to her"},{"id":"B","text":"To illustrate Jo’s persistent effort to develop her writing talent"},{"id":"C","text":"To explain why Jo is uncertain about what career she wants to pursue"},{"id":"D","text":"To describe the stories Jo considers her most successful work"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately describes the main purpose of the text: to illustrate Jo’s persistent effort to improve as a writer. The passage depicts Jo reading widely, filling a notebook with ideas, and repeatedly attempting new stories—even when her finished pieces disappoint her. These details emphasize both her ambition and her determination to continue writing despite setbacks. Choice A is incorrect because although the text mentions Jo reading “all the books she could find,” it does not suggest she is frustrated with the books themselves. The focus is on her own creative process, not the quality or availability of her reading material. Choice C is incorrect because while Jo expresses uncertainty about how to use her “genius,” the text does not explore different career paths or show her weighing options. Instead, it concentrates on her writing practice and perseverance. Choice D is incorrect because although the text mentions the stories Jo writes, it does not identify any as successful or admired. Rather, Jo believes that each finished story falls short of what she envisioned. The passage is concerned with her effort, not with celebrating completed works.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'During the early decades of the twentieth century, as federal land reforms reshaped patterns of settlement in the American West, educator and community organizer María Montoya played a crucial role in helping Mexican American families adapt to these changes. Many families faced uncertainty as traditional communal landholdings were fragmented, limiting access to farming and grazing resources. To support affected households, Montoya worked with local schools and civic groups to coordinate educational opportunities and secure alternative forms of employment for displaced residents, often arranging assistance before families were forced to relocate. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To introduce and illustrate Montoya’s significant role in assisting Mexican American communities during a period of social and economic transition"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To argue that federal land reforms disproportionately harmed Mexican American families compared with other groups"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To document the specific educational programs Montoya established in response to land redistribution policies"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To provide a general overview of the economic consequences of land reforms in the early twentieth-century American West"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is correct because the text’s primary purpose is to highlight María Montoya’s important role in supporting Mexican American families as their circumstances changed during a period of land reform. After briefly establishing the broader historical context, the passage focuses on Montoya’s actions—coordinating education and employment assistance—to show how she helped communities navigate transition. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not compare the experiences of Mexican American families with those of other groups or argue relative harm. Choice C is incorrect because, although education is mentioned, the passage does not detail specific programs or evaluate them. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not aim to broadly survey economic consequences but instead uses limited context to emphasize Montoya’s individual contributions.”', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from Charlotte Brontë’s 1847 novel Jane Eyre. Jane addresses her aunt, Mrs. Reed. “I am glad you are no relation of mine. I will never call you aunt again as long as I live. I will never come to visit you when I am grown up; and if anyone asks me how I liked you, and how you treated me, I will say the very thought of you makes me sick, and that you treated me with miserable cruelty. . . . You think I have no feelings, and that I can do without one bit of love or kindness; but I cannot live so: and you have no pity... I will tell anybody who asks me questions this exact tale. ’Ere I had finished this reply, my soul began to expand, to exult, with the strangest sense of freedom, of triumph, I ever felt. It seemed as if an invisible bond had burst, and that I had struggled out into unhoped-for liberty.” Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To reveal Jane’s intense emotional release as she confronts the aunt who has long mistreated her"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To describe Jane’s regret for weakening the family ties that once supported her"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To illustrate Jane’s growing admiration for the discipline imposed on her by the Reed household"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To explain why Jane believes that her future depends on leaving Gateshead immediately"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because the passage centers on Jane’s forceful denunciation of Mrs. Reed and her profound emotional liberation as she finally expresses the resentment she has long suppressed. Her declaration that an “invisible bond had burst” and her feeling of “freedom” and “triumph” demonstrate that the purpose of the text is to depict her dramatic emotional release as she confronts her aunt’s cruelty. Choice B is incorrect because the text contains no indication that Jane regrets weakening her family ties. In fact, she explicitly renounces those ties and expresses relief at asserting herself. Choice C is incorrect because the passage provides no evidence that Jane admires the discipline—or any aspect—of her upbringing at Gateshead. Instead, she denounces her treatment as “miserable cruelty” and emphasizes the absence of love and kindness. Choice D is incorrect because although the passage conveys Jane’s newfound sense of freedom, it does not state or imply that she believes her future depends on leaving Gateshead immediately. The focus is on expressing long-suppressed anger, not outlining her next actions.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Shifts in ocean temperature and acidity affect how far sound travels underwater, but the extent to which these changes alter deep-sea acoustic environments remains uncertain. Proposing that long-term warming and acidification trends would modify sound transmission not only in surface waters but also at depths below 1,000 meters, oceanographer Simone Baumann-Pickering and colleagues deployed hydrophone arrays across multiple Pacific basins. They observed, however, that despite substantial differences in surface conditions, deep-water sound absorption rates remained consistently high across sites, indicating little variation in sound transmission at depth. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It describes a phenomenon that has been difficult for scientists to quantify, outlines a hypothesis addressing that phenomenon, and then presents results that led researchers to revise the hypothesis."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It introduces an unresolved scientific question, presents a hypothesis formulated to address that question, and then reports an observation that contradicts that hypothesis."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It discusses a poorly understood environmental process, introduces multiple competing hypotheses, and then explains how researchers determined which one is most plausible."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It explains a hypothesis that has generated scientific controversy, describes how researchers evaluated it, and then presents evidence that supports the hypothesis."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately captures the overall structure of the text. The passage begins by noting that scientists do not yet fully understand how changing ocean conditions affect deep-sea sound transmission—an unresolved scientific question. It then describes Baumann-Pickering and colleagues’ hypothesis: that broad-scale warming and acidification would lead to measurable changes in sound propagation even at depths greater than 1,000 meters. Finally, the passage states that deep-water sound absorption remained uniformly high across all study sites, an observation that conflicts with the researchers’ hypothesis. Thus, the text presents an unresolved question, a hypothesis addressing it, and findings that contradict that hypothesis. A is incorrect. Although the text outlines a difficult-to-measure phenomenon and summarizes the researchers’ hypothesis, it does not indicate that Baumann-Pickering’s team subsequently revised their hypothesis. The passage simply states that their findings conflicted with the hypothesis, not that the researchers refined or modified it as a result. C is incorrect. The text does not discuss a process involving multiple competing hypotheses. It presents only one hypothesis—the idea that long-term physical and chemical changes should affect deep-sea sound transmission. It also does not suggest that the researchers evaluated multiple explanations in order to identify the most plausible one. D is incorrect. The passage does not begin by describing a controversial or widely debated hypothesis. Rather, it introduces a scientific question whose answer is uncertain and then explains a single hypothesis proposed by Baumann-Pickering and colleagues. Moreover, the data presented did not validate the hypothesis; instead, the findings contradicted it.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Researchers have investigated how Arabidopsis thaliana and other plant species respond when grown in simulants of lunar or Martian regolith. In one experiment, scientists planted Arabidopsis seeds in simulated lunar soil samples and, as a control, in terrestrial volcanic-ash soil. The seeds in all treatments germinated successfully. However, plants grown in the regolith simulant showed reduced root growth, lower biomass, and increased accumulation of red-pigmented compounds compared to the control group—signs of physiological stress, which molecular assays later confirmed. In another line of research, different species (such as wheat) were grown on Martian regolith simulant (MMS-1), sometimes with additives like vermicompost. These studies found that while plants can survive in Martian simulants, their growth is often limited unless supplemented with organic matter or beneficial microbes; for example, vermicompost helped wheat growth more in Earth soil than in pure simulant. A more recent study focused on fava bean (Vicia faba) grown in the same Martian regolith simulant over multiple planting cycles. The researchers observed that after repeated growth cycles, the regolith substrate’s fertility improved: pH decreased, mineral weathering increased, and nutrients became more bioavailable, suggesting that long-term cultivation could enhance the substrate’s suitability for crops. Which choice best states the main purpose of the passage?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It describes methods of improving Martian regolith for agriculture, like adding vermicompost or microbes."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It reports scientific findings from experiments testing how plants grow in lunar and Martian soil simulants."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It argues that pure extraterrestrial regolith is inherently unsuitable for crop production without repeated amendments."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It explains how red-pigmented compounds in Arabidopsis serve as a bioindicator of stress in off-world soils."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The passage summarizes a series of experiments in which researchers examined how Arabidopsis, wheat, and fava bean responded to growth in simulated lunar and Martian regolith. It then discusses the findings of these studies, including evidence of stress responses in Arabidopsis, reduced growth in wheat unless supplemented with organic matter, and gradual improvement of the Martian simulant over repeated planting cycles. Choice A is incorrect. The text doesn’t primarily describe methods for improving Martian regolith. Although it briefly mentions that vermicompost or microbes can aid plant growth, this is presented as part of the experimental results, not as the central purpose of the passage. Choice C is incorrect. The passage does not argue that extraterrestrial regolith is inherently unsuitable for crop production. In fact, it notes successful germination in lunar simulant and highlights that repeated growth cycles improved the Martian simulant’s fertility. Choice D is incorrect. The text does not focus on red-pigmented compounds as a bioindicator; this detail is simply one of several stress markers mentioned for Arabidopsis. The passage’s main purpose extends beyond this single observation to report findings from multiple studies involving different species and simulants.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Zora Neale Hurston’s 1937 novel Their Eyes Were Watching God. Janie Crawford is reflecting on the blossoming of a pear tree in her grandmother’s garden. It was a spring afternoon in West Florida. Janie had spent most of the day under a blossoming pear tree in the back-yard. She had been spending every minute that she could steal from her chores under that tree for the last three days. That was to say, ever since the first tiny bloom had opened. It had called her to come and gaze on a mystery. From barren brown stems to all of this glory in only a few days now. According to the text, what is true about Janie’s interaction with the pear tree?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. She began visiting the tree only after it was in full, glorious bloom."},{"id":"B","text":"B. she neglected her daily responsibilities entirely to stay by the tree."},{"id":"C","text":"C. She was drawn to the tree by the rapid change in its physical appearance."},{"id":"D","text":"D. She believes the tree is the only beautiful thing in West Florida."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it is directly supported by the text. The narrator notes that Janie saw the tree transform from "barren brown stems" to "glory" in "only a few days," and describes the process as a "mystery" that called her to gaze upon it. This indicates she was motivated by the rapid seasonal change. Choice A is incorrect because the text states she had been there "ever since the first tiny bloom had opened," which was before the tree reached its full "glory." Choice B is incorrect because while Janie spent as much time as she could "steal from her chores," the phrasing implies she still had chores to attend to, rather than neglecting her responsibilities entirely. Choice D is incorrect because the text focuses specifically on Janie''s appreciation of the pear tree; it does not provide any evidence that she views the rest of West Florida as lacking beauty.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Issey Miyake was a world-renowned Japanese fashion designer celebrated for his innovative "Pleats Please" line. His garments featured permanent, heat-set pleats that allowed for both architectural structure and freedom of movement. A student researcher claims that Miyake’s fascination with pleating and folding fabric was rooted in his childhood fascination with the traditional Japanese art of origami (paper folding): ______ Which quotation from a biographical study of Miyake would most effectively support the student’s claim?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. \"Miyake’s designs were often displayed in art museums rather than traditional boutiques, reflecting his belief that clothing should be treated as a form of sculpture.\""},{"id":"B","text":"B. \"The designer frequently recalled watching his mother fold paper into intricate birds and flowers, a process of transforming flat surfaces into three-dimensional forms that he later sought to replicate using polyester fabric.\""},{"id":"C","text":"C. \"In 1993, Miyake launched a collection that used a new technique where the garment was cut and sewn first, then placed between layers of paper and fed into a heat press to create permanent folds.\""},{"id":"D","text":"D. \"While many European designers focused on tailoring clothes to fit the curves of the human body, Miyake was more interested in the space between the body and the fabric.\""}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it provides a direct, causal link between Miyake’s design aesthetic (pleating/folding) and his "childhood fascination" with origami. It mentions his mother’s influence and the specific process of "transforming flat surfaces into three-dimensional forms," which supports the student''s claim perfectly. Choice A is incorrect. While it describes his work as "sculpture," it does not mention the influence of his childhood or the specific art of origami. Choice C is incorrect. This provides a technical description of how the pleats were made in 1993, but it does not address the inspiration or the childhood roots of the design choice. Choice D is incorrect. This describes Miyake’s general design philosophy regarding the "space between the body and the fabric," but it lacks any specific mention of folding or origami.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1891, a fossilized shell of a freshwater mussel, dating back approximately 500,000 years, was discovered in Java, Indonesia, at a site inhabited by Homo erectus. The shell features a series of etched zig-zag grooves that appear intentional and structured. While many paleoanthropologists believe that symbolic representation and abstract thought only emerged with Homo sapiens 100,000 years ago, one researcher asserts that the Java shell is evidence that Homo erectus was also capable of creating symbolic engravings. The researcher notes that the grooves were made with a shark tooth tool and that "the precise geometry of the angles indicates that the markings were not a byproduct of butchery, but rather a deliberate act of graphic expression." Which finding, if true, would most directly weaken the researcher’s claim?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Microscopic analysis of fossilized animal remains found at the same Java site revealed similar zig-zag patterns that were determined to be the result of crocodiles'' teeth scraping across bone during feeding."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Experimental recreations using modern shark teeth on fresh mussel shells demonstrate that a high level of manual dexterity is required to produce straight, deep incisions in the shell’s surface."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Other mussel shells found at the Java site lack any markings, suggesting that the etched shell was a unique occurrence rather than a common cultural practice among the population."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Chemical testing of the Java shell indicates that the grooves were made when the shell was fresh and still possessed its original organic coating, rather than being etched into the fossilized surface later."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it provides a "taphonomic" (natural) explanation for the markings. If identical zig-zag patterns are found on other remains and are proven to be the result of a natural process (crocodile feeding), it suggests that the "deliberate geometry" observed on the shell might also be an accidental byproduct of natural forces rather than intentional "graphic expression." Choice B is incorrect because it focuses on the "manual dexterity" required to make the marks. While this confirms Homo erectus had the physical ability to make them, it does not address whether the marks were symbolic or accidental; if anything, it might slightly strengthen the idea of intentionality. Choice C is incorrect. The rarity of an artifact does not disprove its function. A single piece of evidence is still evidence of a capability, even if that capability was not widespread. Choice D is incorrect. This finding confirms the marks were made during the lifetime of the hominid (500,000 years ago) rather than being modern forgeries. This would strengthen the researcher''s claim by confirming the antiquity of the artifact.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In many bird species, the incubation of eggs requires a consistent thermal environment to ensure embryo survival. Ecologists have long observed that "cavity nesters"—birds that build nests inside tree hollows or rock crevices—produce fledglings with higher survival rates than "open-cup nesters" do, due to the stable microclimate and protection from predators provided by the cavity. Consequently, some researchers hypothesized that cavity-nesting species would exhibit a higher degree of "clutch size plasticity," meaning they would be able to successfully raise a larger number of eggs per nesting attempt across a wider variety of environmental temperatures than open-cup nesters can. Which finding, if true, would most directly support the researchers’ hypothesis?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. In a study of several hundred avian species, open-cup nesters were found to migrate longer distances on average than cavity-nesters to find optimal seasonal temperatures for breeding."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Cavity-nesting species typically utilize a wider variety of lining materials, such as feathers and fur, than open-cup nesting species do to further insulate their eggs."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Data showed that cavity-nesters maintained a consistent number of successfully hatched eggs regardless of fluctuating ambient temperatures, whereas open-cup nesters saw a significant decrease in hatched eggs as temperatures deviated from the seasonal average."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Observations revealed that while cavity nests provide more protection from rain, they are significantly more likely to be infested by parasitic mites than open-cup nests are."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it provides direct evidence of "clutch size plasticity" and thermal stability. If cavity-nesters maintain a consistent hatch rate "regardless of fluctuating ambient temperatures" while open-cup nesters do not, it supports the idea that the cavity environment allows the birds to maintain reproductive success (clutch size) across a wider range of conditions. Choice A is incorrect. While migration habits are interesting, they do not provide evidence regarding the "clutch size" or the "plasticity" of the nesting attempt itself. Choice B is incorrect. This describes a method of insulation (the materials used) but does not provide evidence of the result of that insulation—namely, whether it actually allows for larger or more stable clutch sizes as hypothesized. Choice D is incorrect. This finding identifies a disadvantage of cavity nesting (parasites). It does not address the researchers'' hypothesis concerning environmental temperature and reproductive plasticity.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Global trade has grown increasingly uncertain due to shifting policies, shipping disruptions, and geopolitical risks. Firms in industries heavily exposed to international trade respond by reshoring production and investing in automation, despite the costs. This increases productivity but has little impact on employment, likely because automation simultaneously creates and displaces jobs. Evidence suggests that automation can help such firms counteract the negative effects of trade policy uncertainty. Rapid advances in technologies like generative AI are expected to further facilitate automation and encourage reshoring in uncertain trade environments. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Although reshoring is costly, firms exposed to international trade often automate and bring production back home under trade uncertainty, offsetting some negative effects."},{"id":"B","text":"Although automation can both create and eliminate jobs, firms in trade-exposed industries are likely to reduce employment when trade policies are uncertain."},{"id":"C","text":"Although trade policy uncertainty reduces investment and production, firms less dependent on international trade are most likely to automate and reshore production."},{"id":"D","text":"Although advances in technologies like AI make automation easier, reshoring production remains prohibitively costly for most firms."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it accurately captures the main idea of the passage. The text explains that firms heavily reliant on international trade respond to uncertainty by reshoring and automating production, increasing productivity while mitigating the negative effects of trade policy uncertainty. Employment changes remain limited because automation both creates and displaces jobs. Choice B is incorrect because the passage notes that employment changes are minimal, not that jobs are reduced. Choice C is incorrect because the passage emphasizes that more exposed industries, not less exposed, increase automation and reshoring. Choice D is incorrect because the passage focuses on how automation helps firms adapt to uncertainty, not on cost as a prohibitive factor.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Satellite altimetry has long suggested that certain sectors of the East Antarctic Ice Sheet (EAIS) are comparatively stable, with minimal ice-surface lowering over recent decades. However, using interferometric synthetic-aperture radar (InSAR) data to track millimeter-scale crustal deformation, Valentina Barletta et al. identified unexpectedly rapid uplift in regions near the Denman and Frost glaciers. Because crustal rebound rate increases when overlying ice mass has recently decreased, the team compared their geodetic findings with ice-mass estimates derived from NASA’s GRACE gravimetry mission. The overlap between anomalously high uplift and GRACE-detected mass loss indicates that the EAIS is responding not with uniform stability but with localized dynamic thinning, suggesting that _______. Which choice most logically completes the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"although the EAIS has traditionally been characterized as a sluggish, minimally responsive ice sheet, the regions showing pronounced rebound are undergoing accelerated basal freezing that counteracts recent surface mass loss."},{"id":"B","text":"contrary to the long-standing view that the EAIS’s mass balance varies only gradually, certain basins within the ice sheet are already experiencing significant reductions in ice load consistent with early-stage retreat."},{"id":"C","text":"the combination of uplift and GRACE-detected mass variations is insufficient to determine whether ice changes arise from basal melt, altered snowfall patterns, or plate-tectonic processes that operate independently of ice-sheet dynamics."},{"id":"D","text":"spatially concentrated crustal rebound around Denman and Frost glaciers is most plausibly explained by enhanced ice accretion, which increases local mass and therefore accelerates crustal uplift."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically follows from the passage’s discussion of crustal rebound and ice-mass loss in the East Antarctic Ice Sheet (EAIS). The text explains that although the EAIS has long been considered relatively stable, new geodetic evidence shows rapid uplift in specific regions. Because uplift increases when ice mass has recently decreased, and because GRACE gravimetry independently detects mass loss in those same regions, the overlap of these findings indicates that some EAIS basins are already losing ice. Therefore, it is reasonable to conclude that these basins are undergoing meaningful reductions in ice load consistent with early-stage retreat, contradicting the assumption of uniform long-term stability. Choice A is incorrect because basal freezing would add mass to the ice sheet rather than remove it. Ice accretion increases the load on the crust and would therefore suppress uplift, not accelerate it. The passage explicitly links the observed uplift to mass loss, contradicting the idea that accelerated basal freezing is occurring. Choice C is incorrect because the passage states that the InSAR uplift data and GRACE mass-loss measurements align, strengthening the interpretation that localized thinning is occurring. The text does not suggest that the evidence is insufficient or ambiguous; rather, it presents two converging lines of data pointing toward the same conclusion. Choice D is incorrect because uplift results from decreased ice mass, not from increased mass. Enhanced ice accretion would increase the load on the crust, leading to subsidence or reduced rebound—not the anomalously high uplift recorded by the researchers. Therefore, this explanation contradicts the basic geophysical mechanism described in the text.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'From a distance, the glass sculptures of contemporary artist Karen LaMonte appear to be delicate gowns, their folds and creases rendered with such precision that one might imagine fabric fluttering in a breeze. Upon closer inspection, however, the sculptures reveal themselves to be _______ forms that capture both the presence and absence of the human body. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"solid, and the"},{"id":"B","text":"solid, the"},{"id":"C","text":"solid; the"},{"id":"D","text":"solid. The"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between elements within a single independent clause. This choice correctly uses a comma to connect two closely related parts of one continuous thought: “the sculptures reveal themselves to be solid, the forms that capture both the presence and absence of the human body.” The comma smoothly links an appositive phrase (“the forms that capture…”) to the main clause. Choice A is incorrect because adding “and” creates a compound sentence structure that is grammatically incomplete; the phrase after “and” does not form a full independent clause. Choice C is incorrect because a semicolon must connect two independent clauses, but “the forms that capture…” is not one. Choice D is incorrect because placing a period before “The” produces a fragment; the phrase “The forms that capture both the presence and absence of the human body” lacks a main verb and cannot stand alone.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'As geologists have noted, Earth’s magnetic field has reversed hundreds of times over its history. These geomagnetic “flips” occur irregularly, sometimes separated by tens of millions of years, and scientists have yet to identify a consistent trigger. During a reversal, the field’s strength weakens dramatically, _______ charged particles from space can penetrate deeper into Earth’s atmosphere. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"meaning, that"},{"id":"B","text":"meaning; that"},{"id":"C","text":"meaning,"},{"id":"D","text":"meaning that"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between a main clause and a modifying phrase introduced by “meaning that.” This choice correctly omits any comma or semicolon, forming the grammatically and stylistically appropriate construction “the field’s strength weakens dramatically, meaning that charged particles from space can penetrate deeper into Earth’s atmosphere.” The phrase “meaning that…” functions as a continuation of the same sentence, not as a new clause. Choice A is incorrect because inserting a comma after “meaning” separates the modifying phrase from the clause it explains, disrupting sentence flow and grammatical structure. Choice B is incorrect because a semicolon incorrectly divides the sentence into two independent clauses; the portion following “meaning” is dependent. Choice C is incorrect because a comma after “meaning” creates a fragment (“meaning, charged particles…”), which lacks a connecting word to link it to the main clause.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 1, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Franz Kafka was a German-speaking writer born in Prague. • Kafka’s novella The Metamorphosis was first published in 1915. • The story explores themes of alienation and identity. • It is one of Kafka’s most widely studied works. The student wants to state the year The Metamorphosis was first published. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Kafka often wrote about characters who felt alienated."},{"id":"B","text":"The Metamorphosis was published in 1915."},{"id":"C","text":"Franz Kafka was a German-speaking writer from Prague."},{"id":"D","text":"Kafka’s widely studied works explore complex psychological themes."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The sentence indicates the year The Metamorphosis was first published—1915—which directly fulfills the student’s goal using relevant information from the notes. Choice A is incorrect because it provides thematic information about Kafka’s writing rather than the publication year of the novella. Choice C is incorrect because it gives background about Kafka’s identity but does not indicate when The Metamorphosis was published. Choice D is incorrect because it comments on the nature of Kafka’s works but does not state the publication year of the novella.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2016, environmental activist Afroz Shah organized a massive cleanup of Mumbai’s Versova Beach, where tons of plastic waste had accumulated over the years. _______ in 2018, his efforts inspired similar coastal cleanups across India and earned him a United Nations “Champion of the Earth” award. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Instead,"},{"id":"B","text":"For example,"},{"id":"C","text":"Later,"},{"id":"D","text":"In other words,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “Later” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that in 2018 Shah’s efforts inspired nationwide cleanups and earned him an award—occurs later in a chronological series of events than the previous information about Shah organizing the Versova Beach cleanup in 2016. Choice A is incorrect because “instead” illogically signals that Shah’s recognition and influence were alternatives to organizing the beach cleanup. Rather, these events occurred later—in a chronological sequence—after his initial cleanup effort. Choice B is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that Shah’s recognition and influence exemplify his 2016 cleanup itself. Rather, they are later outcomes of that event. Choice D is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals that Shah’s recognition and influence merely restate the previous information about the 2016 cleanup. Rather, they happened later in time as a result of it.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Edward Sapir is esteemed among linguists for his pioneering research on the relationship between language and thought. His studies are extensive and often emphasize the specific ways in which a language’s structure shapes the perception of its speakers. Instead of viewing grammar as a mere set of rigid rules, Sapir focuses on the "formal completeness" of a language, arguing that every language is a perfect system for expressing the world as its speakers see it. While Sapir’s theories were developed alongside early 20th-century anthropological movements, he utilized meticulous phonological analyses and native informant testimonies that make his descriptive linguistics highly distinctive. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It introduces a scholar and then explains some common characteristics of well-known work by that scholar."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It explains a specific linguistic methodology and then provides examples of contemporary researchers who use that methodology."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It describes a famous book and then compares it to a less successful publication from the same era."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It gives a subjective critique of a researcher and then suggests several reasons why the researcher’s theories have been largely disregarded."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is correct because it accurately reflects the structural organization of the passage. The first sentence introduces Edward Sapir as an esteemed figure in linguistics. The following sentences describe the defining features of his work, such as his focus on how language structure influences perception, his view of grammar as a "formal system," and his use of specific anthropological and phonological methods. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not provide examples of any other "contemporary researchers" who use Sapir''s methods; it focuses exclusively on Sapir himself. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not mention or describe a single "famous book," nor does it compare one publication to another. Choice D is incorrect because the text presents factual descriptions of Sapir’s work rather than a "subjective critique," and it never suggests his theories were "disregarded"—on the contrary, it describes him as "esteemed" for his "pioneering research."', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Universities are increasingly offering online degree programs alongside traditional in-person instruction. Through recorded lectures, discussion boards, and remote assessments, students can complete coursework without relocating or adjusting work schedules. Institutions benefit as well: online programs allow universities to enroll students beyond geographic limits and reduce the need for physical classroom space. However, expanding online education presents challenges, since maintaining academic integrity, ensuring student engagement, and providing adequate technological support can require significant investment and careful oversight. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It explains the historical development of higher education and then evaluates the long-term outcomes of recent reforms."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It introduces a growing trend in education and then explains how the trend creates both advantages and difficulties for institutions."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It compares two instructional formats and then argues that one is more effective than the other."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It describes a problem faced by universities and then proposes specific solutions to address it."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the text first introduces a trend—the increasing availability of online degree programs—and then explains how this trend benefits universities while also creating challenges related to quality control, student engagement, and infrastructure. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not trace the historical development of higher education or assess reforms over time. Choice C is incorrect because although online and in-person instruction are mentioned, the text does not compare their effectiveness or argue that one is superior. Choice D is incorrect because the passage identifies challenges but does not propose solutions or strategies for resolving them.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Large portions of the traditional medicinal knowledge held by indigenous groups in the Great Lakes region have become difficult for modern ethnobotanists to document fully. Much of what is understood today regarding these ancient botanical practices is derived from fragmentary historical records. For instance, a single sketch in a 19th-century field diary provides the only known description of a specific willow-bark preparation used by the Anishinaabe. A brief entry in a colonial trade ledger mentions a unique root-based dye utilized by the Menominee. Additionally, a passing reference in a collection of oral histories transcribed in the 1920s confirms the existence of a lost method for preserving seasonal berries using sphagnum moss. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The text outlines a persistent scientific mystery and then evaluates several competing theories that attempt to explain that mystery."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The text presents a broad historical circumstance and then provides particular instances that exemplify that circumstance."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The text argues that a specific cultural practice is superior to modern alternatives and then lists the reasons for that superiority."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The text introduces several prominent historical figures and then highlights the various ways in which their research methods differed."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because it most accurately describes the organizational flow of the passage. The first two sentences establish a general situation: that much of the medicinal knowledge of the Great Lakes region is difficult to document and is known only through fragmentary records. The remainder of the passage provides specific examples of these "fragmentary records"—a sketch in a diary, an entry in a trade ledger, and a reference in transcribed oral histories—to illustrate the general claim.Choice B is correct because it most accurately describes the organizational flow of the passage. The first two sentences establish a general situation: that much of the medicinal knowledge of the Great Lakes region is difficult to document and is known only through fragmentary records. The remainder of the passage provides specific examples of these "fragmentary records"—a sketch in a diary, an entry in a trade ledger, and a reference in transcribed oral histories—to illustrate the general claim. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not make a value judgment or "argue" that ancient botanical practices are "superior" to modern ones; it simply discusses the difficulty of documenting them. Choice A is incorrect because the difficulty of documenting historical knowledge is not framed as a "scientific mystery" requiring the evaluation of "competing theories." The text provides evidence of the knowledge, not theories to explain a mystery. Choice D is incorrect because while the text mentions different historical sources, it does not focus on "prominent figures" or compare their "research methods"; rather, it focuses on the artifacts they left behind as evidence of a lost tradition.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'JoAnn Falletta’s appointmentJoAnn Falletta has played a transformative role in American orchestral music. As the first woman to lead a major US ensemble, she has guided the Buffalo Philharmonic Orchestra through more than two decades of artistic growth, elevating its international profile. Under her leadership, the orchestra became a leading recording ensemble for a major classical label and later established its own record label. Falletta has also founded international music competitions, led historic international performances, and received numerous honors, including multiple GRAMMY Awards, reflecting both her individual achievements and the orchestra’s continued success. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To provide examples demonstrating JoAnn Falletta’s significance as a conductor and musical leader"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To argue that JoAnn Falletta’s accomplishments surpass those of other contemporary conductors"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To describe the recording strategies that helped modern orchestras gain global recognition"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To compare the Buffalo Philharmonic Orchestra’s success before and after"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because the text offers an overview of JoAnn Falletta’s importance by highlighting her historic leadership role, her impact on the Buffalo Philharmonic Orchestra, her international achievements, and her numerous awards. These details collectively serve to illustrate her significance rather than advance a specific argument. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not compare Falletta directly with other conductors or claim that she exceeds them. Choice C is incorrect because recording initiatives are mentioned only as part of a broader summary of her accomplishments, not as the central focus. Choice D is incorrect because although the text describes developments during Falletta’s tenure, it does not explicitly contrast the orchestra’s status before and after her leadership.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Many medieval stained-glass windows are missing sections of bright blue and red glass. This is because those colors were created using minerals that made the glass more _______ than other sections. The intense hues required chemical additives that weakened portions of the windows, making them especially vulnerable to damage over centuries of weather and war. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"expensive"},{"id":"B","text":"varied"},{"id":"C","text":"brittle"},{"id":"D","text":"decorative"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s description of how certain stained-glass colors were made. In this context, “brittle” means easily broken. The passage explains that the bright red and blue colors required mineral additives that weakened the glass, making those parts especially vulnerable to damage. This supports the idea that these sections were the most brittle. Choice A is incorrect because although rare minerals could make certain colors more expensive, the passage focuses on why the glass broke easily, not on its cost. Choice B is incorrect because “varied” means diverse or different in type. The text does not emphasize differences in style or color variety, but rather the physical weakness of these glass pieces. Choice D is incorrect because while stained glass is indeed decorative, the text explains that these specific colors were prone to breaking, which is unrelated to how decorative they are.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Much of what historians know about ancient maritime trade comes from indirect evidence rather than complete records. Many shipping logs, contracts, and cargo lists from antiquity no longer survive. Instead, researchers rely on fragments such as shipwreck remains, inscriptions, and scattered written references. For instance, amphorae recovered from Mediterranean shipwrecks reveal what goods were transported. A Roman inscription records merchants operating across North Africa. Additionally, references in classical texts mention trade routes connecting southern Europe and the Near East. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The text presents a historical mystery and then evaluates several failed efforts to resolve it."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The text outlines a scholarly disagreement and then argues in favor of one interpretation."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The text describes a general situation and then supports it with specific examples."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The text introduces several historical figures and then compares their individual contributions."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is correct because the passage first explains a general situation—that historians must rely on indirect evidence to study ancient maritime trade—and then illustrates that situation by giving concrete examples of the types of evidence historians use. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not frame the lack of records as a complex mystery or discuss unsuccessful attempts to solve it. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not present a debate or advocate for a particular interpretation. Choice D is incorrect because while historical evidence is mentioned, the passage does not focus on individual figures or compare their contributions.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Most people know that birds and bees help spread seeds and pollen as they fly from plant to plant. However, some plants use a much more explosive method to move their seeds. "Botanists refer to this dramatic process as ''ballochory.''" In ballochory, a plant''s seed pod builds up internal pressure as it dries out, eventually bursting open and launching seeds at high speeds. Biologist Dwight Whitaker and his team studied the "squirting cucumber" (Ecballium elaterium) and found that it can fire its seeds at speeds of up to 60 miles per hour, landing them many meters away from the parent plant. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined portion in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It identifies a specific problem that Whitaker’s team faced during their field research."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It introduces a scientific term that is used in the discussion that follows."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It explains the physical difference between a seed and a pollen grain."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It argues that birds and bees are less effective at spreading seeds than mechanical force."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately describes the function of the underlined portion in the text as a whole. The first two sentences introduce the idea that while animals help move seeds, some plants use an "explosive" method. The underlined sentence then provides the scientific term for this method: "ballochory." The text that follows explains how ballochory works (internal pressure causing pods to burst) and provides a specific example involving the squirting cucumber. Thus, the underlined portion introduces a scientific term that is used in the discussion that follows. Choice A is incorrect. The underlined portion presents a term used by botanists; it does not mention any "problems" or difficulties that Whitaker or his team encountered during their research. Choice C is incorrect. While the first sentence mentions both seeds and pollen, the underlined portion focuses solely on the name of a seed-dispersal process ("ballochory") and does not explain the physical differences between seeds and pollen grains. Choice D is incorrect. Although the text mentions that birds and bees help move seeds, the underlined portion does not make a comparison or an "argument" about which method is more effective; it simply provides the name for the mechanical method described in the passage.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from Langston Hughes’s 1922 poem “Dreams.” Hold fast to dreams For if dreams die Life is a broken-winged bird That cannot fly. Hold fast to dreams For when dreams go Life is a barren field Frozen with snow. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To argue that achieving dreams requires constant hard work"},{"id":"B","text":"To warn readers that letting go of dreams can make life bleak"},{"id":"C","text":"To describe how seasons affect the natural world"},{"id":"D","text":"To compare birds and fields as symbols of nature"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately states the text’s main purpose. The poem repeats the message “Hold fast to dreams” and uses negative images—like a “broken-winged bird” and a “barren field”—to show how bleak and empty life becomes when dreams are lost. Thus, the poem’s main purpose is to warn readers that giving up dreams can make life bleak. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not discuss hard work or the effort needed to achieve dreams. Instead, it focuses on the importance of holding on to dreams themselves. Choice C is incorrect because although the poem mentions a bird and a field, these images are metaphors illustrating the value of dreams, not literal descriptions of seasonal changes. Choice D is incorrect because the poem is not comparing aspects of nature for their own sake. Instead, it uses natural imagery to emphasize the emotional consequences of losing dreams.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Most microscopic organisms die quickly when their environment dries out because the loss of water causes their cellular structures to collapse. However, the tardigrade, a tiny eight-legged animal, has evolved a unique method to survive for decades without water. "When a tardigrade enters a dormant state, it produces a sugar called trehalose, which replaces the water in its cells and forms a glass-like shield that prevents the cell membranes from breaking." This process allows the tardigrade to remain in a state of suspended animation until it comes into contact with moisture again. Which choice best states the purpose of the underlined portion in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It describes the effects of a biological process that increases the survival time of an organism discussed in the text."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It details the specific environmental changes that prompted the research discussed in the text."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It presents a reason why the cellular collapse discussed in the text is impossible to prevent in nature."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It mentions a laboratory method that scientists plan to use in future studies of tardigrade DNA."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it accurately describes the function of the underlined portion in the text. The passage begins by explaining that most organisms die when they lose water. It then introduces the tardigrade as an exception that can survive for decades. The underlined sentence explains the "how": the production of trehalose sugar creates a protective shield. This directly describes the process that increases the longevity (survival time) of the tardigrade. Choice B is incorrect. While the text mentions environments drying out, the underlined portion focuses on the internal chemical reaction (the production of trehalose) rather than the external "circumstances" or "environmental changes." Choice C is incorrect. The underlined portion actually explains the opposite—it describes how cellular collapse is prevented by the trehalose shield, rather than arguing that it is "inevitable." Choice D is incorrect. The underlined portion describes a natural biological process that occurs within the tardigrade, not a "laboratory method" or a plan for "future studies" by human scientists.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Anton Chekhov’s 1886 short story A Day in the Country. A dark leaden-coloured mass is creeping over the sky towards the sun. Red zigzags of lightning gleam here and there across it. There is a sound of far-away rumbling. A warm wind frolics over the grass, bends the trees, and stirs up the dust. In a minute there will be a spurt of May rain and a real storm will begin. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To describe the way in which people prepare for an approaching storm"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To provide a detailed account of how lightning forms in the sky"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To convey the atmosphere and intensity of an approaching storm"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To explain the agricultural effects of May rain on crops"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it accurately describes the main purpose of the text. The passage uses vivid imagery—such as “a dark leaden-coloured mass,” “red zigzags of lightning,” and “a warm wind frolics over the grass”—to convey the intensity and atmosphere of the storm as it approaches. The overall effect immerses the reader in the sensory experience of the impending weather. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not mention people or any preparations for the storm. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not explain the scientific formation of lightning; it only describes its appearance. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not discuss crops or any agricultural impact of the rain.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Agricultural technology firms are increasingly marketing "precision farming" tools, such as GPS-guided tractors and soil sensors, to help farmers optimize their crop yields. By using these technologies, farmers can apply water and fertilizer with extreme accuracy, ensuring that resources are used only where they are most needed. This efficiency not only increases the farm''s total output but also significantly reduces the environmental impact of chemical runoff. Nevertheless, the transition to these high-tech systems poses a significant financial risk; the initial capital required to purchase and calibrate the equipment is often prohibitive for small-scale operations, and the specialized technical knowledge required to interpret the data can create a steep learning curve for traditional producers. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It proposes a solution to a long-standing environmental problem and then provides a chronological account of how that solution was developed."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It introduces a specific technological trend in an industry and then details both the positive outcomes and the practical obstacles related to that trend."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It evaluates the performance of two competing agricultural companies and then argues that one company’s approach is more sustainable than the other’s."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It describes a shift in consumer demand for organic produce and then explains how farmers have adjusted their growing techniques to meet that demand."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the text follows a clear pattern of introducing a trend—precision farming—and then exploring its dual nature. It first highlights the positive outcomes, such as optimized yields and reduced environmental harm, before transitioning to the practical obstacles, specifically the high costs and the technical expertise required for implementation. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not provide a chronological history or a timeline of how these technologies were created. Choice C is incorrect because the passage discusses a general category of technology rather than comparing the specific performances or sustainability records of two individual companies. Choice D is incorrect because the text focuses on the tools used for production efficiency and resource management rather than shifts in consumer preferences or the market for organic products.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A team including physicist Vito Mocella and computer scientist Brent Seales has studied charred scrolls from Herculaneum, carbonized in the AD 79 eruption of Mount Vesuvius. The scrolls are so fragile and tightly rolled that traditional methods could not open them safely. Using X-ray phase‑contrast tomography, the researchers were able to _______ Greek letters hidden inside the papyri without unrolling the scrolls. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"conceal"},{"id":"B","text":"obtain"},{"id":"C","text":"misplace"},{"id":"D","text":"abandon"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the Herculaneum papyri. In this context, “obtain” means gain or acquire. The text explains that the scrolls are too fragile to open physically, but the researchers used X-ray tomography to extract information about the Greek letters contained within. Therefore, the context indicates that the researchers were able to gain detailed information from the scrolls. Choice A is incorrect because “conceal” means to hide, which is the opposite of what the researchers accomplished. Choice C is incorrect because “misplace” means to lose or put in the wrong location, which makes no sense in this context. Choice D is incorrect because “abandon” means to give up or leave behind, which also does not match the context; the researchers did not leave the letters unread, but rather recovered them using a non-invasive technique.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Much of what scientists know about early Earth’s atmosphere comes from indirect evidence. Direct measurements from billions of years ago do not exist, so researchers must rely on limited traces preserved in geological materials. For example, certain sulfur isotope patterns in ancient rocks indicate low oxygen levels. Microscopic structures in fossilized soils suggest interactions between early microbes and the atmosphere. In addition, mineral compositions found in sedimentary layers provide clues about atmospheric conditions at the time they formed. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The text presents a scientific problem and then evaluates several unsuccessful efforts to solve it."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The text summarizes a scientific controversy and then argues for one explanation over others."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The text describes a general situation and then illustrates it with specific examples."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The text focuses on multiple scientific discoveries and then explains how they differ from one another."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because the passage first explains a general situation—that knowledge of Earth’s early atmosphere depends on indirect evidence—and then provides specific examples of the types of geological traces scientists use. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not frame the lack of direct measurements as a complex problem or discuss failed attempts to address it. Choice B is incorrect because no scientific debate or competing explanations are presented. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not compare differences among discoveries; instead, it uses them collectively to illustrate a single point.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Why do fireflies (Lampyridae) glow in the dark? "Biologist Marc Branham and his colleagues propose that while the light is now used to attract mates, it originally evolved as a warning signal to predators." By studying the evolutionary history of these insects, the researchers discovered that the chemical reaction used to produce light—called bioluminescence—appeared in fireflies at the same time they developed certain toxins that make them taste bitter. This suggests that the glow served as a visual reminder to birds and other hunters to stay away. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined sentence in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It identifies a specific predator that fireflies are unable to avoid."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It contradicts the evidence presented in the sentence that follows."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It provides an answer to the question in the previous sentence."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It explains that the question in the previous sentence is impossible to study."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it best describes how the underlined sentence functions in the text as a whole. The text begins with a question: why do fireflies produce light? The underlined sentence then presents a theory offered by researchers, indicating that Marc Branham and his team believe the glow first evolved as a warning signal to predators. The text then describes the evidence—the link between light and bitter toxins—that supports this theory. Thus, the function of the underlined sentence is to provide an answer to the question in the previous sentence. Choice A is incorrect because the underlined sentence does not name a "specific predator"; it mentions "predators" generally as part of a theory about why fireflies evolved to glow. Choice B is incorrect because there is no contradiction between the underlined sentence and the sentence that follows; both support the idea that the light is connected to a defense mechanism (warning predators about toxins). Choice D is incorrect because the underlined sentence directly provides an answer to the question based on research, rather than stating that the topic "is impossible to study." In fact, the rest of the passage describes how the team successfully studied the evolutionary history of the insects.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Ocean warming has been shown to affect the growth rates of coral reefs, but how far these effects extend into deeper reef layers remains uncertain. Suggesting that temperature differences at the surface would influence coral health throughout the reef structure, Maya Chen and colleagues measured coral density and calcification rates at varying depths across several reef systems in the western Pacific. The researchers found, however, that beyond shallow depths, coral growth declined to similarly low levels regardless of surface temperature conditions. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It describes a marine phenomenon that scientists do not fully understand, explains a research team’s hypothesis about that phenomenon, and then describes a result that prompted the team to revise the hypothesis."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It introduces an unresolved scientific question, presents a research team’s hypothesis related to that question, and then describes evidence that contradicts the hypothesis."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It discusses a biological process that is poorly understood, introduces multiple competing hypotheses about that process, and then explains how researchers determined which hypothesis was correct."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It explains a hypothesis that has been widely debated, describes how a research team tested the hypothesis, and then presents findings that confirm the hypothesis."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the passage first raises an unresolved question about how deeply the effects of ocean warming influence coral growth, then presents a hypothesis proposing that surface temperature differences affect coral health throughout the reef, and finally reports findings showing that coral growth at greater depths did not vary with surface conditions, contradicting the hypothesis. Choice A is incorrect because although a hypothesis and conflicting results are presented, the text does not indicate that the researchers revised or refined their hypothesis. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not mention competing hypotheses or conclude that one hypothesis was correct. Choice D is incorrect because the findings described do not support or validate the hypothesis but instead conflict with it.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Seasonal camouflage, which allows certain animals to blend into snowy winter or leafy summer environments, is often easy to identify in Arctic mammals such as the snowshoe hare. However, because this adaptation is present but less _______ in many bird species, wildlife biologists frequently rely on long-term field observations to determine whether those species undergo similar seasonal changes in coloration. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"recognizable"},{"id":"B","text":"decorative"},{"id":"C","text":"traditional"},{"id":"D","text":"valuable"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of seasonal camouflage in animals. As used in this context, “recognizable” means apparent or easy to perceive. The text indicates that seasonal camouflage is easy to identify in Arctic mammals but that biologists need long-term observations to determine whether certain bird species show similar changes. This context and the use of the word “less” before the blank suggest that, compared with mammals, seasonal camouflage in these birds is less recognizable. Choice B is incorrect because there is nothing in the text to suggest that seasonal camouflage is less decorative, or ornamental, in birds. The discussion focuses on how easy it is to perceive camouflage, not how aesthetically pleasing it is. Choice C is incorrect because “traditional” means something established by long custom. The text does not compare how customary or long-standing the adaptation is in different animals; it compares how easy the adaptation is to observe. Choice D is incorrect because “valuable,” meaning useful or important, would not make sense in context. The text is not about whether seasonal camouflage is more or less valuable in birds than in mammals but about how easily it can be recognized.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2012, astrophysicist Vera Rubin’s decades-long research on the rotation of galaxies gained renewed attention when newly digitized telescope data confirmed her earlier findings. Rubin had observed that stars at the outer edges of spiral galaxies moved just as quickly as those near the center—an observation that contradicted existing gravitational models. This unexpected pattern helped strengthen the case for dark matter, an invisible substance thought to make up most of the universe’s mass. The recent data review highlighted how Rubin’s careful observations played a key role in shaping modern astrophysics. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To compare Rubin’s findings with earlier astronomical theories"},{"id":"B","text":"To discuss Rubin’s contributions to the study of dark matter"},{"id":"C","text":"To explain the process of digitizing telescope data"},{"id":"D","text":"To show why astronomers disagree about galaxy rotation"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately states the main purpose of the text. After introducing astrophysicist Vera Rubin and the renewed attention to her work, the text focuses on describing how her observations about galaxy rotation contributed to the scientific understanding of dark matter. Thus, the overall purpose of the text is to discuss Rubin’s contributions to the study of dark matter. Choice A is incorrect because although the text notes that Rubin’s findings contradicted earlier gravitational models, it does not compare her work to specific prior theories in detail. Choice C is incorrect. While the text briefly mentions digitized telescope data, this detail is used only to explain why Rubin’s work received renewed attention—not to describe the digitization process itself. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not claim that astronomers disagree about galaxy rotation, nor does it discuss scientific debates; instead, it highlights the importance of Rubin’s discoveries.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Field observations—which involve researchers living within a community to document local practices—can provide scientists with a deep understanding of traditional knowledge. For her study on the medicinal properties of plants in the Amazon rainforest, ethnobotanist Elsa Rengifo therefore spent several months living with the indigenous Yagua people. "By doing so, she discovered specific ways that local plants are prepared to treat common ailments." This information allowed her to catalog dozens of species that were previously unknown to modern medicine. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined sentence in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It identifies a specific plant species that is found only in the Amazon."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It argues that Elsa Rengifo is an expert on South American international trade."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It describes a challenge that researchers face when traveling through the rainforest."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It describes how Elsa Rengifo benefited from using field observations in her study."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most accurately describes how the underlined sentence functions in the text as a whole. The text begins by explaining a general benefit of field observations: they help scientists understand traditional knowledge. It then explains that Elsa Rengifo used this method by living with the Yagua people. The underlined sentence confirms that this method worked for her, specifically by helping her learn how plants are used for medicine. Thus, the underlined sentence describes how Rengifo benefited from using field observations in her study. Choice A is incorrect because while the text mentions plants in the Amazon, the underlined sentence does not name or identify a "specific plant species" or provide a fact about where it is found. Choice B is incorrect because the underlined sentence focuses on the discovery of medicinal plant uses, not on "international trade" or Rengifo’s expertise in politics or commerce. Choice C is incorrect. Although the text mentions living in the rainforest, the underlined sentence focuses on a successful discovery made during the study, rather than a "challenge" or difficulty that researchers face during travel.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'During the mid-2000s, historians and archivists working on the Bracero History Archive digitized thousands of photographs, work contracts, and oral histories related to the Bracero Program, which brought Mexican laborers to the United States between 1942 and 1964. The project allowed researchers, students, and families to remotely access materials that had previously been scattered across multiple institutions, helping them to ________ the experiences of Bracero workers across different regions and time periods. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"misinterpret"},{"id":"B","text":"preserve"},{"id":"C","text":"disregard"},{"id":"D","text":"trivialize"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the Bracero History Archive. In this context, “preserve” means to maintain and safeguard historical materials for future use. The text indicates that the project enabled broad access to digitized documents and oral histories that had previously been difficult to locate, which reflects a clear effort to preserve the historical record of the Bracero Program. Choice A is incorrect because “misinterpret” means to misunderstand, which does not make sense in a context emphasizing improved access to reliable historical sources. Choice C is incorrect because “disregard” means to ignore, which contradicts the description of archivists taking extensive steps to collect and digitize materials. Choice D is incorrect because “trivialize” means to treat something as unimportant, which is the opposite of the project’s goal of documenting and honoring workers’ experiences.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2023, archaeologists excavating at the ancient Maya site of Chichén Itzá uncovered a previously unknown ceremonial pool hidden beneath layers of sediment. The pool contained pottery fragments, carved jade pieces, and traces of incense. These findings help researchers better understand the kinds of ritual activities that took place at the site. For instance, chemical analysis of the incense residues suggests that the Maya burned copal resin during ceremonies performed near the water. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To explain how Maya rulers organized their political system"},{"id":"B","text":"To describe the agricultural practices of ancient Maya communities"},{"id":"C","text":"To present a recent archaeological finding at Chichén Itzá"},{"id":"D","text":"To compare Maya religious ceremonies with modern rituals"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately describes the main purpose of the text. The text states that archaeologists in 2023 uncovered a previously unknown ceremonial pool at Chichén Itzá. It then describes what was found inside the pool—pottery fragments, jade pieces, and incense traces—and explains what these items reveal about Maya ritual practices. Thus, the overall purpose of the text is to present a recent archaeological discovery. Choice A is incorrect. Although the discovery was made at a major Maya site, the text does not provide any information about how Maya rulers governed or how their political system functioned. Choice B is incorrect. The passage does not mention farming, crops, or any agricultural activity; its focus is entirely on ceremonial artifacts. Choice D is incorrect. While the text refers to Maya ceremonies, it does not compare them with modern rituals or with any other cultural practices.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Astronomers recognize that the presence of liquid water and specific chemical compounds on icy moons can indicate potential habitability, though whether these conditions persist in the subsurface oceans of distant satellites remains uncertain. Hypothesizing that hydrothermal activity on Saturn’s moon Enceladus would result in a non-uniform distribution of organic molecules that is not confined to the plume discharge at the southern pole, Dr. Nozair Khawaja and colleagues analyzed data from the Cassini spacecraft’s Cosmic Dust Analyzer. They discovered, however, that the concentration and complexity of these organic compounds were virtually identical across different sampling altitudes and locations within the E-ring. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It describes a phenomenon that scientists do not fully understand, explains a research team’s hypothesis about that phenomenon, and then describes a finding that led the team to refine the hypothesis."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It explains a hypothesis that has been the subject of scientific debate, discusses how a research team tested that hypothesis, and then presents data the team collected that validate the hypothesis."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It discusses a process that scientists are somewhat unclear about, introduces competing hypotheses about that process, and then explains how a research team concluded that one of those hypotheses is likely correct."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It introduces an unresolved scientific question, presents a research team’s hypothesis pertaining to that question, and then describes an observation made by the team that conflicts with that hypothesis."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is correct because it most accurately describes the overall structure of the text. The passage begins by noting that while water on icy moons is a known indicator of habitability, its persistence in subsurface oceans is an "uncertain" or unresolved question. It then summarizes the team''s hypothesis—that organic molecules would be distributed non-uniformly (unevenly) throughout the moon''s environment. Finally, it presents an observation that contradicts this: the molecules were actually "virtually identical" (uniform) in their distribution, regardless of where they were sampled. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not mention the research team "refining" or changing their hypothesis based on the new data; it simply concludes with the finding itself. Choice B is incorrect because the text presents the hypothesis as a specific team''s premise rather than a "subject of scientific debate," and more importantly, the resulting data contradicted (rather than "validated") the initial hypothesis.Choice C is incorrect because the text only presents one hypothesis from Khawaja’s team; it does not introduce "competing hypotheses" or choose one over another.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Archaeologists at White Sands National Park recently discovered thousands of ancient human footprints, but many of these tracks are "ghost tracks" that are invisible to the naked eye under normal conditions. These footprints only appear briefly when the moisture content in the soil is exactly right, making them difficult to map. "To solve this, researchers used ground-penetrating radar (GPR), which sends radio waves into the earth to detect changes in soil density where the sand was once compressed by human feet." By using this technology, the team was able to reveal a 1.5-mile-long trail of footprints that had been hidden for over 10,000 years. Which choice best states the purpose of the underlined portion in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It describes the specific climatic conditions that cause the footprints to become visible to the naked eye."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It explains the mechanism of a technology used to identify a phenomenon discussed in the text."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It presents a reason why the footprints have remained perfectly preserved for thousands of years."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It identifies a new archaeological site where the team plans to conduct future research."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately describes how the underlined sentence functions in the text as a whole. The passage begins by introducing "ghost tracks"—footprints that are usually invisible. The underlined sentence explains how researchers found them: by using ground-penetrating radar (GPR) to detect density changes in the soil. Thus, the underlined portion explains the mechanism of a technology (GPR) used to identify the phenomenon (the footprints). Choice A is incorrect because the climate conditions (moisture levels) are mentioned in the sentence before the underlined portion, not within it. The underlined portion focuses on the radar technology. Choice C is incorrect because the underlined sentence focuses on how the tracks are detected today, not on the geological or environmental reasons why they were "preserved" over the last 10,000 years. Choice D is incorrect because the underlined sentence describes a technology currently being used at White Sands National Park; it does not mention or identify a "new archaeological site" for "future research."', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the late 1700s, the Chinese scientist Wang Zhenyi wrote a groundbreaking book titled The Explanation of a Solar Eclipse. "This work provides a remarkably accurate explanation of celestial mechanics, as she correctly describes the movement of the Earth, Moon, and Sun, and uses her own experimental models to prove how the Moon blocks sunlight." Her research was particularly extraordinary because she lived during a time when women in China were rarely given the opportunity to study formal science or mathematics. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined sentence in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It identifies some reasons why Wang Zhenyi’s scientific work is impressive."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It explains why Wang Zhenyi chose to focus on solar eclipses instead of lunar eclipses."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It details the specific obstacles Wang Zhenyi faced as a woman in the 1700s."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It argues that Wang Zhenyi’s models were used by other scientists across the world."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it best describes how the underlined sentence functions in the text as a whole. The text presents information about the scientific book written by Wang Zhenyi. The underlined sentence states that her work provides a "remarkably accurate explanation" and mentions that she "correctly describes" celestial movements and used "experimental models." These are all details that indicate her work was executed with great skill and intelligence. Thus, the underlined sentence identifies some reasons why the work is impressive. Choice B is incorrect. While the book is about solar eclipses, the underlined sentence does not explain why she chose that specific topic over others; it only describes the quality and accuracy of the explanation she provided. Choice C is incorrect. Although the sentence after the underlined portion mentions the lack of opportunities for women at the time, the underlined sentence itself focuses on her scientific achievements rather than her social obstacles. Choice D is incorrect. The underlined sentence describes the nature of Wang Zhenyi''s work and models, but it does not claim or "argue" that these models were used by other scientists globally.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Animal researcher Jane Goodall observed a chimpanzee in Gombe in 1960 that used sticks to extract termites from a mound. Skeptical colleagues had initially suggested to Goodall that the chimpanzee’s stick use might simply be _______ , but Goodall and her team showed that the chimpanzee was using the sticks intentionally as tools. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"intriguing"},{"id":"B","text":"obvious"},{"id":"C","text":"accidental"},{"id":"D","text":"observable"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Goodall’s study of a chimpanzee in Gombe. In this context, “accidental” means unplanned or unintentional. The text first describes Goodall’s study, which concerns a chimpanzee that is observed using sticks to extract termites from a mound. The text then mentions colleagues who are skeptical (that is, they have doubt) about Goodall’s findings, and finally describes how Goodall and her team responded to the skepticism of those colleagues. Given that the colleagues mentioned in the text expressed skepticism regarding Goodall’s findings, the best answer choice must be one that completes the text in a manner such that the skeptics’ opinion regarding the chimpanzee’s use of sticks disagrees with that held by Goodall and her team. Since Goodall and her team showed that the chimpanzee’s use of sticks was deliberate (that is, intentional), the skeptics’ opinion in this context must be that the chimpanzee’s use of sticks was unintentional, or accidental. Choice A is incorrect because the best answer choice is one that portrays skepticism, or doubt, of Goodall’s claim that the chimpanzee’s use of sticks was deliberate, or intentional. If the skeptics found the chimpanzee’s usage of sticks “intriguing,” or fascinating, this would not be at odds with the position of Goodall and her team; in fact, it is reasonable to believe that someone who agreed that the chimpanzee’s stick usage was deliberate would also find it intriguing. Choice B is incorrect because if the skeptics believed that the chimpanzee’s use of sticks was “obvious,” or evident, this would not be contrary to the observation of Goodall and her team that the chimpanzee’s use of sticks was deliberate: in fact, these opinions would be consistent with each other. Choice D is incorrect because if the skeptics believed that the chimpanzee’s use of sticks was “observable,” or visible, this would not conflict with the claim of Goodall and her team that the chimpanzee’s use of sticks was deliberate: instead, these positions would agree.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Charles Dickens’s 1838 novel Oliver Twist. Oliver is reflecting on why he might be allowed to join an errand outside the workhouse. They are sending a small group out to fetch supplies, and there is a chance I may be permitted to go. I am quiet and quick on my feet, and I have never caused trouble. While some of the boys whisper and quarrel, I keep to myself and do what I am told. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To describe how errands are usually handled at the workhouse"},{"id":"B","text":"To explain why the older boys are not chosen for the task"},{"id":"C","text":"To show why Oliver believes he might be selected to join the errand"},{"id":"D","text":"To compare Oliver’s behavior with that of children in other workhouses"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because the narrator lists the reasons Oliver thinks he may be chosen to go on the errand: he is “quiet,” “quick,” and obedient. These traits support his belief that he has a chance of being selected. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not describe the general procedure for errands; it focuses on Oliver’s personal expectations. Choice B is incorrect because although Oliver mentions that some boys “whisper and quarrel,” the text does not explain the overall selection process or specifically why older boys are excluded. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not mention other workhouses or make any broader comparisons; it deals only with Oliver’s situation.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The greater the ecological versatility and foraging strategies exhibited by a species, the more metabolically costly and anatomically elaborate its neural architecture is likely to be. _________ from a phylogenetic standpoint, species with narrowly constrained behavioral repertoires are predicted to invest minimally in cerebral development. The caste-specific roles of eusocial wasps offer a compelling framework to empirically investigate this postulate. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Subsequently,"},{"id":"B","text":"Besides,"},{"id":"C","text":"Nevertheless,"},{"id":"D","text":"Consequently,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “Consequently” logically signals that the claim in this sentence—that species with narrowly constrained behavioral repertoires are predicted to invest minimally in cerebral development—is a direct consequence of the previous sentence’s claim about the metabolic and anatomical costs associated with extensive neural architecture in species exhibiting diverse behaviors. Choice A is incorrect because “subsequently” illogically implies a chronological sequence rather than a causal relationship. Instead, the second claim is a logical consequence, not merely a later event. Choice B is incorrect because “besides” illogically suggests that the second claim is an additional, separate point. In reality, it follows causally from the first claim. Choice C is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically signals contrast or contradiction. Instead, the second claim reinforces the causal logic established in the first sentence.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • Canang Sari is a daily offering created in Bali, Indonesia, for the past 1,000 years. • The offerings are made from woven palm frond baskets filled with colorful flowers, incense, and sometimes food scraps. • Women are primarily responsible for weaving and creating the offerings. • The placement and contents of each offering carry symbolic meaning, including prayers to Hindu deities and expressions of gratitude or selflessness. • Many Balinese, including those who do not follow the Hindu faith, participate in the tradition today. The student wants to emphasize the duration and purpose of the Canang Sari tradition. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Canang Sari baskets are made of woven palm fronds and contain colorful flowers, incense, and sometimes food scraps."},{"id":"B","text":"Women in Bali are responsible for creating Canang Sari, and the offerings are placed carefully to symbolize prayers to various deities."},{"id":"C","text":"For the past 1,000 years, Balinese people have participated in the daily creation of Canang Sari to honor traditions, express gratitude, and offer prayers."},{"id":"D","text":"Canang Sari offerings are visible throughout Bali, including on doorsteps, temples, and sidewalks, where tourists can also assist in crafting them."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The sentence emphasizes both the duration (the practice has been carried out for the past 1,000 years) and the purpose (to honor tradition, express gratitude, and offer prayers) of the Canang Sari tradition. Choice A is incorrect. While the sentence describes the contents of Canang Sari, it doesn’t address the duration or purpose of the tradition. Choice B is incorrect. While the sentence mentions the role of women and the symbolism of the offerings, it doesn’t indicate the long history (duration) of the tradition. Choice D is incorrect. While the sentence notes the locations of Canang Sari and tourist participation, it doesn’t emphasize the duration or the cultural purpose of the practice.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes: • A 2016 analysis examined global trends in glacier mass balance across major mountain regions. • Researchers measured changes in glacier thickness using satellite altimetry and ground-based observations. • The study found that, between 2003 and 2009, glaciers worldwide lost an average of 275 gigatons of ice per year. • The Himalayas experienced comparatively moderate loss rates, averaging about 12 gigatons per year. • Alaska had the fastest regional loss rate, with glaciers losing approximately 50 gigatons of ice per year. • Despite regional differences, researchers concluded that glaciers across all studied regions were shrinking. The student wants to present an overview of the study’s findings. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The 2016 analysis used satellite altimetry and ground-based observations to measure changes in glacier thickness."},{"id":"B","text":"Glaciers in Alaska lost ice at a much faster rate than those in the Himalayas, with annual losses of around 50 gigatons compared to 12 gigatons."},{"id":"C","text":"Although the Himalayas and Alaska showed different annual ice-loss rates, glaciers worldwide lost an average of 275 gigatons of ice per year during the study period."},{"id":"D","text":"Despite variations in regional melt rates, the study concluded that glaciers in all examined mountain regions were shrinking."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The sentence provides an overview of the study’s findings by emphasizing the general conclusion that, although melt rates varied across regions, all examined glaciers were losing mass. This reflects the study’s broad takeaway rather than focusing on specific regions. Choice A is incorrect. The sentence identifies the study’s methodology but does not summarize any findings and therefore fails to present an overview. Choice B is incorrect. The sentence compares ice-loss rates for Alaska and the Himalayas, discussing only two regions, and does not offer an overview covering the global results of the study. Choice C is incorrect. Although it mentions both regional differences and the global average loss rate, the sentence focuses on specific numerical findings rather than summarizing the study’s key overall conclusion that all glacier regions were shrinking. Additionally, it highlights only two regions rather than synthesizing findings across the entire dataset.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Several studies have proposed that standing rather than sitting enhances attention and cognitive control, but such claims warrant careful scrutiny. A case in point: In a series of replication experiments, Emilie E. Caron and her colleagues reexamined earlier findings suggesting that posture improves performance on tasks such as the Stroop test and visual search. Using larger sample sizes with sufficient statistical power, the researchers expected to observe the same posture-related advantages previously reported. Instead, they found that any effects of posture were minimal or nonexistent, indicating that standing does not reliably enhance attention across these tasks. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To argue that earlier studies of posture and attention relied on flawed experimental designs that later research corrected"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To present a replication study in order to dispute the theoretical explanations proposed in prior posture research"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To describe how increasing sample size can reveal subtle cognitive effects that smaller studies often miss"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To discuss a recent study as an example of why claims about posture’s effects on cognition should be treated cautiously"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is correct because the text uses Caron and colleagues’ replication study to illustrate why claims about posture improving cognition should not be overstated. The passage begins by signaling skepticism toward broad claims about posture’s cognitive benefits and then presents the replication study as a “case in point,” showing that previously reported effects were weak or absent when tested more rigorously. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not accuse earlier studies of being flawed; it notes that the replicated effects were smaller or nonexistent, not that the original methods were invalid. Choice B is incorrect because, although theoretical explanations are mentioned implicitly, the primary purpose is not to refute those theories but to urge caution in interpreting posture research. Choice C is incorrect because sample size is discussed only as supporting context, not as the main focus or takeaway of the passage.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from Cormac McCarthy’s 1985 novel Blood Meridian, or, the Evening Redness in the West. The scene describes a group of men watching a campfire. “The flames sawed in the wind and the embers paled and deepened and paled and deepened like the bloodbeat of some living thing eviscerate upon the ground before them and they watched the fire which does contain within it something of men themselves inasmuch as they are less without it and are divided from their origins and are exiles. For each fire is all fires, and the first fire and the last ever to be.“ Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To emphasize the men’s profound connection to the elemental power and history embodied by the fire."},{"id":"B","text":"B. To convey the immediate, physical danger the fire presents to the men watching it."},{"id":"C","text":"C. To describe the men’s deep regret at being separated from the comforts of their homes and previous lives."},{"id":"D","text":"D. To illustrate the men’s determination to understand the scientific properties of combustion."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately describes the main purpose of the text, which is to show the fire as a symbolic representation of humanity itself, suggesting a fundamental, existential connection between man and fire. The text begins with a description of the fire''s physical appearance, comparing the pulsing embers to "the bloodbeat of some living thing eviscerate upon the ground," which gives the flames a raw, visceral life of their own. This sets up the central, philosophical claim that the fire "does contain within it something of men themselves inasmuch as they are less without it and are divided from their origins and are exiles." The final sentence, "For each fire is all fires, and the first fire and the last ever to be," elevates the specific campfire to an eternal, universal symbol, stressing its deep and historical significance to the men watching it. Choice B is incorrect because the text focuses on the symbolic, existential relationship between the men and the fire, not on any immediate or practical threat the fire might pose. The description of the flames is highly metaphorical and contemplative, not a warning of physical danger. Choice C is incorrect because while the text mentions men are "divided from their origins and are exiles," the purpose is not to highlight a feeling of regret or homesickness. Instead, the text uses this sense of exile as a condition that establishes the men''s profound, almost spiritual, kinship with the fire. The focus is on the nature of their current existence and their bond with the flame, not on longing for the past. Choice D is incorrect because the text’s language is intensely metaphorical and poetic, dealing with themes of origins, exile, and human nature. There is no indication that the men are attempting to analyze the "scientific properties of combustion"; their engagement with the fire is spiritual and philosophical, not empirical.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Consumption of nuts and seeds has been linked to a range of health outcomes, though the overall strength and consistency of these associations across diseases and study designs has been unclear. To address this uncertainty, Rajiv Balakrishna and colleagues conducted an umbrella review synthesizing evidence from systematic reviews and meta-analyses examining associations between nut and seed intake and outcomes such as cardiovascular disease, cancer, diabetes, and mortality. They found that, compared with low or no consumption, higher intake of nuts was consistently associated with reduced risk of cardiovascular disease and all-cause mortality, with generally moderate-quality evidence, although associations with diabetes incidence were mixed. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It describes a well-established dietary recommendation, explains why recent evidence has challenged that recommendation, and then presents findings that overturn earlier conclusions."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It introduces uncertainty about the health effects of a dietary behavior, presents a research team’s hypothesis intended to resolve that uncertainty, and then reports results that contradict that hypothesis."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It identifies an unresolved question regarding health outcomes, describes a research approach used to address that question, and then summarizes findings that partially resolve it."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It presents multiple competing explanations for observed health outcomes, evaluates the evidence supporting each explanation, and then determines which explanation is best supported by the data."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately describes the overall structure of the text. The text begins by explaining that consumption of nuts and seeds has been associated with various health outcomes, but that the overall strength and consistency of these associations across diseases and study designs remains unclear, presenting an unresolved question. Next, the text describes the research approach used to address this uncertainty, explaining that Balakrishna and colleagues conducted an umbrella review synthesizing evidence from systematic reviews and meta-analyses examining multiple health outcomes. Finally, the text states that the researchers found that higher nut intake was consistently associated with reduced risk of cardiovascular disease and all-cause mortality, though associations with diabetes incidence were mixed, thereby partially resolving the uncertainty introduced at the beginning of the passage. Thus, the text identifies an unresolved question regarding health outcomes, describes a research approach used to address that question, and then summarizes findings that partially resolve it. Choice A is incorrect. Although the text supports dietary recommendations to consume nuts and seeds, it does not describe a previously well-established recommendation that has been challenged or overturned by new evidence; instead, it summarizes evidence addressing uncertainty about the strength and consistency of health associations. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not present a specific hypothesis formulated by the researchers that is later contradicted by their findings; rather, it reports results from a comprehensive synthesis of existing evidence, which largely supports beneficial associations. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not present or evaluate multiple competing explanations for observed health outcomes. While the umbrella review assesses a broad body of evidence, it does not compare alternative explanatory hypotheses or determine which explanation is best supported by the data.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Standard historical narratives of the Harlem Renaissance—the profound flowering of African American intellectual and artistic life in the 1920s—"frequently prioritize the contributions of male litterateurs and high-profile visual artists," casting the era as a primarily aesthetic and masculine phenomenon. Historian Laura Helton has argued, however, that if scholars redirect their inquiry toward the archival labor and "mobile libraries" established by Black women librarians like Regina Andrews, a more complex picture emerges. This shift reveals that the movement was as much a grassroots effort in information science and community literacy as it was a revolution in the fine arts. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined portion in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It outlines a prevailing trend in the historiography of the Harlem Renaissance that the text suggests has been largely abandoned following the publication of Helton’s research."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It points to a specific group of Harlem Renaissance figures that the text implies were favored by earlier historians because of the researchers'' personal artistic preferences."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It summarizes the traditional framework for evaluating the Harlem Renaissance, which the text argues leads to an inaccurate assessment of the movement''s ultimate social impact."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It describes a typical focus in studies of the Harlem Renaissance that, according to the text, masks the multifaceted nature of the movement’s actual objectives and participants."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most accurately describes how the underlined portion functions in the text as a whole. The passage begins by noting that standard narratives "frequently prioritize" male writers and artists, which creates a specific, limited view of the era (an "aesthetic and masculine phenomenon"). The text then introduces Laura Helton’s work, which suggests that focusing on "comparatively low-profile" archival and library work reveals a different side of the movement (information science and community literacy). Thus, the underlined portion describes a common scholarly focus that obscures the diversity of the movement''s actual work and participants. Choice A is incorrect. Although the underlined portion identifies a trend in historiography, the text does not state that this trend has been "largely abandoned." It only suggests that Helton''s work provides a necessary alternative perspective to a still-prevalent narrative. Choice B is incorrect. While the underlined portion identifies a group (male artists) that has been overemphasized, the text does not discuss the "personal artistic preferences" of the historians who created those narratives. Choice C is incorrect. The underlined portion does summarize a traditional framework, but the text’s critique is not about the "effectiveness" or "ultimate social impact" of the movement. Instead, it focuses on the nature of the movement''s activities (literacy and archiving versus just fine arts).', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Doro, the central figure in Octavia E. Butler’s 1980 novel Wild Seed, is a selective breeder of humans with extraordinary abilities, a role that, in Butler’s fiction, is not _________: numerous characters across her Patternist series are engaged in shaping or influencing human evolution. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"infallible"},{"id":"B","text":"atypical"},{"id":"C","text":"lucrative"},{"id":"D","text":"tedious"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Octavia E. Butler’s character Doro. As used in this context, “atypical” would mean uncommon or not representative. The text states that “numerous characters across her Patternist series are engaged in shaping or influencing human evolution,” which shows that Doro’s role is not unusual within Butler’s fiction—other characters share similar abilities or responsibilities. Therefore, the role is not atypical. Choice A is incorrect because “infallible” means incapable of making mistakes or being wrong, which does not make sense in this context. The sentence is not describing whether Doro’s role is error-free, but rather whether it is common in Butler’s works. Choice C is incorrect because “lucrative” means profitable or financially rewarding. The text does not discuss money or imply that Doro’s role involves profit, so this word does not logically complete the sentence. Choice D is incorrect because “tedious” means boring or monotonous. The text focuses on how common this type of character is in Butler’s Patternist series, not on whether the role is uninteresting. Thus, “tedious” would not logically fit the context.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', '"Modern sloths, such as the three-toed sloth, are characterized by extremely sedentary lifestyles and highly localized foraging patterns," which had led some paleontologists to hypothesize that the Megatherium, a massive extinct ground sloth, may have similarly occupied restricted territorial boundaries. Because teeth grow continuously and assimilate oxygen isotopes (18^O and 16^O) from the water and plants an animal consumes, each increment of tooth dentin serves as a geochemical record of the specific climatic and geographic conditions of the animal''s habitat. Recent analysis of the oxygen isotope ratios in the dental increments of a Megatherium specimen from the pampas of South America indicates that rather than remaining in a single location, the animal underwent significant seasonal migrations over hundreds of kilometers in response to fluctuating rainfall patterns. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined statement in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It identifies a behavioral trait observed in extant species to explain the basis of a research hypothesis that is later contradicted by evidence in the passage."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It presents a characteristic common to certain animals in order to suggest that another animal likely lacked that characteristic, a view that is confirmed by data described later."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It describes a similarity in the movements of several species to demonstrate why a specific chemical analysis failed to provide conclusive results about a prehistoric animal."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It introduces a pattern of behavior to provide a context for a theory about the evolutionary advantages of that behavior that is developed further in the text."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it accurately describes the function of the underlined statement in the passage. The underlined statement establishes that modern sloths have sedentary, localized foraging patterns. The text explains that this observation led researchers to hypothesize that the extinct Megatherium might have behaved similarly. However, the passage then describes how oxygen isotope analysis of a Megatherium tooth actually showed the animal moved across vast distances. Therefore, the underlined statement explains why researchers entertained a possibility that was eventually disproven by the isotopic data. Choice B is incorrect. While the statement presents a characteristic of modern sloths, the text does not suggest that the Megatherium "likely lacked" it from the start; rather, the researchers hypothesized that the Megatherium did have the trait. It was only the subsequent data that showed the animal lacked it.Choice C is incorrect. The underlined statement describes the behavior of modern sloths, but the text does not suggest that the isotope analysis "failed" to produce results. On the contrary, the method provided very clear evidence that allowed researchers to determine the animal''s migration patterns.Choice D is incorrect. While the underlined statement mentions a behavioral trait (localized foraging), the rest of the passage is concerned with whether the Megatherium shared that trait, not with explaining the evolutionary origins or advantages of the trait itself.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2022, researchers with the Event Horizon Telescope (EHT) collaboration released the first image of Sagittarius A*, the supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way. The result confirmed decades of astrophysical modeling and demonstrated that black holes can be studied not only through their gravitational effects on nearby stars but also through radio interferometry that synthesizes data from observatories across the globe. To _______ the persistent atmospheric noise and timing irregularities involved in combining signals from antennas on different continents, the EHT team used atomic clocks and advanced calibration algorithms, enabling a level of resolving power equivalent to a telescope the size of Earth. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"exacerbate"},{"id":"B","text":"counteract"},{"id":"C","text":"invalidate"},{"id":"D","text":"advertise"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s explanation of how the EHT team addressed sources of error in their astronomical observations. The passage explains that atmospheric noise and timing irregularities are problems in combining radio signals across continents. It then describes techniques—atomic clocks and calibration algorithms—that allow the team to achieve extremely precise measurements. In this context, “counteract” means to act against or reduce the effect of, which accurately reflects the researchers’ effort to mitigate those observational challenges. Choice A is incorrect because “exacerbate” means to worsen, and the EHT team’s use of precise instrumentation and algorithms is described as improving measurement quality, not making noise and irregularities more severe. Choice C is incorrect because “invalidate” means to negate or render unsound, which would imply the researchers caused the observational data to become useless; this contradicts the passage, which emphasizes that the methods enabled successful imaging of Sagittarius A*. Choice D is incorrect because “advertise” concerns public promotion, which has no logical connection to a technical procedure for correcting noise in radio astronomy measurements.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Examining early-twentieth-century urban redevelopment in Detroit, archaeologist Krysta Ryzewski studied archival records and material remains associated with the construction of Michigan Central Station and Roosevelt Park. Ryzewski found that the City Beautiful–inspired project was a deliberate place-making effort that displaced a working-class neighborhood characterized by poverty, immigrant populations, and residential transience. She argues that the park’s ornamental landscape conceals this history of displacement and that the prolonged struggle surrounding the project reflects broader inequalities embedded in industrial-era urban planning. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To describe an unexpected outcome of Detroit’s City Beautiful Movement that challenged prevailing views of urban planning success"},{"id":"B","text":"To discuss research examining how displaced Detroit residents resisted early-twentieth-century urban redevelopment initiatives"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To evaluate a scholarly interpretation of the architectural symbolism of Michigan Central Station and Roosevelt Park"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To summarize the findings of a study that explored how an urban beautification project contributed to community displacement"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is correct because the text provides an overview of a scholarly study detailing how an urban beautification project in early-twentieth-century Detroit led to the displacement of a working-class community. The passage summarizes Ryzewski’s findings and the factors she identifies—such as place-making goals and social inequality—without advancing an independent argument. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not frame the findings as unexpected or discuss changing perceptions of planning success. Choice B is incorrect because, although displacement is discussed, the text does not focus on organized resistance by residents. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not evaluate the scholarship or focus primarily on architectural symbolism but instead summarizes the study’s conclusions about displacement.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Although healthy plants are essential to human and animal well-being, the role of plant health in shaping food safety and food security has often been overlooked within the One Health literature. To illustrate how plant health is directly linked to public health outcomes, David M. Rizzo and colleagues present four case studies examining plant diseases, pests, and management practices that affect food availability and safety in different global contexts. Across these cases, the authors show that plant-related threats—such as crop diseases, toxin-producing fungi, food contamination, and pesticide misuse—can undermine both food security and human health, and that addressing these challenges effectively requires an integrated One Health approach. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It introduces an overlooked problem in a field of study, outlines a framework used to examine that problem, and then provides examples that demonstrate the framework’s relevance."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It describes a well-established scientific relationship, explains why recent evidence has challenged that relationship, and then presents findings that overturn previous conclusions."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It presents a debated hypothesis, explains how multiple research teams tested that hypothesis, and then evaluates which team’s findings are most convincing."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It discusses a phenomenon that scientists do not fully understand, proposes a specific hypothesis to explain that phenomenon, and then reports results that conflict with the hypothesis."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately describes the overall structure of the text. The text begins by explaining that although plant health is essential to human and animal well-being, its role in food safety and food security has often been overlooked within the One Health literature, thereby identifying a problem or gap in the field. Next, the text explains the framework the authors use to address this problem, describing how Rizzo and colleagues employ a One Health perspective and present four case studies to examine the links between plant health and public health. Finally, the text summarizes what these case studies demonstrate, namely that plant-related threats such as diseases, toxins, contamination, and pesticide misuse can undermine food security and food safety, and that addressing these threats effectively requires an integrated One Health approach. Thus, the text introduces an overlooked problem, outlines a framework used to examine that problem, and then provides examples that demonstrate the framework’s relevance. Choice B is incorrect. Although the text discusses the importance of plant health, it does not describe a previously well-established scientific relationship that has been challenged or overturned by new evidence; rather, it highlights an area that has been insufficiently emphasized in prior work. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not present a debated hypothesis or describe multiple research teams testing competing explanations. Instead, it summarizes a single review that uses illustrative case studies rather than hypothesis testing. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not propose a specific hypothesis about an unclear phenomenon or report findings that conflict with such a hypothesis. Rather, it presents examples that collectively support, rather than contradict, the value of the One Health approach.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'It is by no means _______ to acknowledge the influence of classical Persian music on contemporary composer Aida Shirazi’s work; indeed, Shirazi frequently incorporates traditional modal systems into her compositions. Still, several music historians argue that twentieth-century European avant-garde composers may have shaped her artistic approach even more profoundly. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"irrelevant"},{"id":"B","text":"straightforward"},{"id":"C","text":"excessive"},{"id":"D","text":"implausible"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the influences on Shirazi’s compositions. As used in this context, “irrelevant” means not connected or without importance. The phrase “It is by no means” sets up a meaning that is contradicted by the information that follows. Since the sentence explains that Shirazi explicitly uses traditional Persian modal systems, acknowledging that influence on her work is clearly meaningful. Therefore, recognizing that impact is by no means irrelevant. Choice B is incorrect because it would not make sense to say that recognizing Persian musical influence on Shirazi is not “straightforward,” or simple, when the text explicitly states that she frequently incorporates traditional modes into her compositions. Choice C is incorrect because calling such recognition “excessive,” meaning too much or overly large in degree, does not align with the text, which emphasizes that the influence is real and acknowledged, not exaggerated. Choice D is incorrect because describing that recognition as “implausible,” or not believable, would contradict the clear evidence given in the sentence that Shirazi incorporates Persian musical structures into her work.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The Crimean War (1853–1856) has a _______ place in historical memory in Russia and Europe, partly because it exposed the profound logistical and technological deficiencies of the Russian Empire and partly because it ultimately preserved the prewar equilibrium of power in the region: despite immense human and material costs, Russia’s territorial and strategic ambitions in the Black Sea remained only partially consummated. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"precarious"},{"id":"B","text":"indelible"},{"id":"C","text":"triumphant"},{"id":"D","text":"conspicuous"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the Crimean War’s significance in Russian and European historical memory. In this context, “precarious” means uncertain or insecure. The text emphasizes that the war revealed severe logistical and technological deficiencies in the Russian Empire and that, despite heavy human and material losses, it left the prewar balance of power largely intact and only partially fulfilled Russia’s ambitions. These factors suggest that the war’s place in historical memory is unstable or insecure—hence, precarious. Choice B is incorrect because “indelible” means lasting or permanent. The text implies that the war’s memory is complicated and not firmly established in historical consciousness, so “indelible” would conflict with this nuance. Choice C is incorrect because “triumphant” means marked by victory or success. Although the war concluded with only partial realization of Russia’s ambitions, the text emphasizes the enormous costs and limited gains, making “triumphant” inappropriate. Choice D is incorrect because “conspicuous” means obvious or prominent. The text highlights that the war’s outcomes and memory are ambivalent and partially overshadowed by other historical factors, suggesting its place is not particularly prominent.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Anthropologist Lee Berger and his colleagues examined the fossilized wrist and hand bones of Homo naledi. They found that these bones were _______ those of modern great apes such as chimpanzees and gorillas, indicating that H. naledi retained both arboreal adaptations and the capacity for forceful grips. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"surpassed by"},{"id":"B","text":"comparable to"},{"id":"C","text":"independent of"},{"id":"D","text":"obtained from"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the fossilized wrist and hand bones of Homo naledi. In this context, “comparable to” means similar to. The text states that the fossilized bones shared key characteristics with those of modern great apes that climb and use strong gripping motions, such as chimpanzees and gorillas. This similarity supports the conclusion that H. naledi retained arboreal adaptations and the ability to make forceful grips, so describing the bones as comparable to those of modern apes aligns with the scientific claim. Choice A is incorrect because “surpassed by” would mean that the fossilized bones were inferior to those of modern apes. That would not logically support the idea that H. naledi retained effective climbing and gripping abilities—abilities that require strong, well-adapted wrist and hand structures. Choice C is incorrect because “independent of” would suggest that H. naledi’s bones were unrelated to or uninfluenced by modern ape anatomy. If that were true, the researchers could not infer that the species retained climbing adaptations based on comparisons to modern apes. Choice D is incorrect because “obtained from” implies that the fossilized bones were taken from modern apes. Since Homo naledi lived hundreds of thousands of years ago, long before any modern species of great apes, the bones could not have been obtained from them.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', '“Does it match the sensor data?” This is the guiding inquiry for many marine biologists utilizing computer-generated imagery (CGI) to reconstruct the bathypelagic zone—the "midnight zone" of the ocean. Because humans cannot easily observe these depths, researchers often prioritize absolute mathematical fidelity, ensuring that the scattering of bioluminescent light from a Melanocetus johnsonii (black seadevil) precisely mimics the photon counts recorded by deep-sea probes. However, some visualizers, such as those at the Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute (MBARI), argue for a shift in perspective. Instead of asking whether the digital light perfectly replicates the raw sensor data, they ask whether the visualization effectively communicates the biological function of the light, such as its role in luring prey or warding off predators in the vast, opaque reaches of the trench. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined question in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It expresses a skepticism held by some researchers regarding the ability of current CGI technology to render the bathypelagic zone accurately."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It introduces a fundamental objective that a specific group of scientists prioritizes when developing digital models of deep-sea phenomena."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It highlights a common misunderstanding among the general public about the visual appearance of organisms in the midnight zone."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It represents the shifting priorities of visualizers who are moving away from data-driven accuracy toward educational storytelling."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately describes how the underlined question functions within the logic of the passage. The text starts with the question, “Does it match the sensor data?” and immediately identifies it as the "guiding inquiry" for researchers who prioritize "absolute mathematical fidelity" in their digital reconstructions. The passage then contrasts this with a different approach used by MBARI visualizers. Thus, the question serves to define the primary goal of the first group mentioned. Choice A is incorrect. While the text mentions that humans cannot "easily observe" these depths, it never suggests that the scientists are skeptical of the technology''s ability to be accurate. In fact, it describes them as "ensuring" that the CGI "precisely mimics" the data, suggesting they have confidence in the technical process. Choice C is incorrect. The passage focuses entirely on the methodologies and internal debates of scientists and visualizers. It does not mention the general public or any misconceptions they might hold regarding bioluminescence. Choice D is incorrect. This is a "reversal" trap. The underlined question represents the initial priority of data-driven accuracy, not the shifting priority toward storytelling. The "shifting" priority is represented by the second group mentioned later in the text, not by the underlined question itself.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In her examination of the Indian caste system, sociologist Manali S. Deshpande argues that although social differentiation exists in all societies, caste became especially consequential in India because multiple dimensions of identity—such as occupation, ritual status, and heredity—converged into a rigid hierarchy governing access to power, prestige, and resources. Deshpande traces how this system, legitimated through religious doctrine and enforced through ritualized social regulation, historically constrained occupational mobility and social interaction. She then explains that although legal reforms and economic change since independence have weakened the formal rigidity of caste, its influence persists unevenly, particularly in rural life and marital practices, making an assessment of caste’s contemporary social effects still necessary. Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It outlines several forms of social stratification in India and then compares the caste system to similar systems found in other societies."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It describes the historical origins of a social hierarchy and then argues that religious ideology was the sole factor responsible for its persistence."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It explains why a system of social differentiation became deeply entrenched, traces the mechanisms that sustained it, and then discusses how its influence has changed over time."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It presents a critique of a traditional social system and then proposes specific policy solutions to eliminate that system in contemporary India."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The passage first explains why caste became a powerful and entrenched form of social stratification in India, emphasizing the overlap of identity dimensions. It then traces the religious and social mechanisms that sustained the system and finally discusses how caste’s influence has shifted—rather than disappeared—in the modern period. Choice A is incorrect. Although the passage briefly acknowledges that social differentiation exists in all societies, it does not compare India’s caste system to stratification systems elsewhere. Choice B is incorrect. While religion is identified as an important legitimating force, the passage does not claim it was the sole factor responsible for the persistence of caste. Choice D is incorrect. The passage does not propose policy solutions or advocate specific reforms; it focuses on historical explanation and contemporary analysis.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Paleoclimatologist Nerilie Abram and colleagues analyzed ice cores from Antarctica and found that layers of volcanic ash can serve as a chronological marker for major eruptions, allowing researchers to create more precise climate timelines. In many cases, atmospheric temperatures show a measurable decline shortly before a volcanic event becomes _______ , as sulfur-rich gases begin to accumulate in the stratosphere. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"quixotic"},{"id":"B","text":"manifest"},{"id":"C","text":"redundant"},{"id":"D","text":"obsolete"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s explanation of volcanic events emerging in climate data. In this context, “manifest” means clear or evident. The text explains that researchers detected temperature declines shortly before volcanic eruptions become observable in the geological record, which means the eruptions are not yet fully evident but are about to become manifest. Therefore, the best completion will indicate that the eruption is about to become noticeable. Choice A is incorrect because “quixotic” means unrealistic or impractical. Volcanic eruptions are physical events, not aspirations or plans, so describing them as quixotic would not make sense. Choice C is incorrect because “redundant” means repetitive or unnecessary. Nothing in the passage implies that the volcanic event is repetitive or superfluous; instead, it refers to the eruption becoming detectable. Choice D is incorrect because “obsolete” means outdated or no longer in use. A volcanic event cannot logically be described as obsolete, since it is a geological process rather than a tool or custom that can fall out of use.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Solar physicists are certain that the Sun’s core facilitates nuclear fusion by converting hydrogen into helium at a temperature of approximately 15 million degrees Celsius. "They remain considerably less certain, however, regarding the precise mechanism that regulates the ''solar cycle''—the periodic reversal of the Sun’s magnetic poles—because this process is governed by deep-layer plasma dynamics that are currently inaccessible to direct observation." Physicist Mausumi Dikpati and colleagues recently explored whether kinematic dynamo models could utilize surface-level magnetic field data to predict the timing of the next solar maximum, but they ultimately determined that these models could not sufficiently account for the stochastic (random) turbulence within the solar interior to provide a reliable forecast. Which choice best describes the function of the second sentence in the overall structure of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It outlines a specific technical flaw in the kinematic dynamo models developed by Dikpati and colleagues."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It introduces a central hypothesis that was eventually validated by the findings of Dikpati and colleagues."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It identifies a scientific mystery that Dikpati and colleagues sought to resolve but were unable to."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It summarizes the critical feedback provided by other solar physicists regarding the research of Dikpati and colleagues."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it accurately describes the function of the second sentence within the logical flow of the passage. The first sentence presents a well-established fact about solar fusion. The second sentence introduces a significant unknown: the mechanism regulating the solar cycle. The third sentence then describes how Dikpati and colleagues attempted to address this unknown using kinematic dynamo models, though their attempt was unsuccessful. Therefore, the second sentence identifies the specific problem that the researchers intended to solve. Choice A is incorrect. The second sentence describes a broad scientific challenge (the inability to observe deep-layer plasma dynamics), not a specific flaw in the models used by the researchers. The mention of the model''s inability to account for stochastic turbulence appears in the third sentence, not the second. Choice B is incorrect. The second sentence does not present a hypothesis to be validated; rather, it identifies a gap in knowledge (a lack of certainty). Furthermore, Dikpati and colleagues did not validate a mechanism; they reached a negative conclusion about the predictive power of their models. Choice D is incorrect. The second sentence discusses the general state of uncertainty in the field of solar physics regarding magnetic poles. It does not mention or summarize any external reception or peer review of Dikpati’s specific study.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', '___________ the entrenched predilection in literary criticism for canonical texts, scholars have increasingly redirected their inquiry toward a previously marginalized corpus: transnational experimental narratives. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Perpetuating"},{"id":"B","text":"Counteracting"},{"id":"C","text":"Exemplifying"},{"id":"D","text":"Precluding"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion about literary criticism. In context, “counteracting” means acting against or mitigating. The text indicates that literary criticism has long favored canonical texts. It goes on to say that scholars have begun to study a previously marginalized corpus, which suggests that they are counteracting the entrenched predilection by redirecting attention to underrepresented works. Choice A is incorrect because “perpetuating” means continuing or reinforcing, which would contradict the text. Expanding study to marginalized texts does not reinforce a focus on canonical texts; it does the opposite. Choice C is incorrect because “exemplifying” means illustrating or serving as a representative example, which does not logically fit the idea of challenging an entrenched preference. Choice D is incorrect because “precluding” means preventing or making impossible, which is not implied in the text. Scholars are redirecting attention, not making canonical texts’ dominance impossible.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2023, digital humanist Dr. Lila Martínez unveiled an unprecedented, peer-reviewed virtual reality (VR) edition of Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz’s seventeenth-century poetic archives. Traditionally, peer review assesses the scholarly merit of print-based research, but Martínez’s “immersive critical edition” required evaluation from an unusual consortium of literary scholars, cognitive scientists, and VR designers. By integrating annotated manuscripts with interactive spatial environments that simulate the convent cells in which Sor Juana composed her works, the project offers a multidimensional framework for experiencing early modern literature. In doing so, Martínez’s edition challenges long-standing assumptions about how historical texts may be interpreted, curated, and disseminated within contemporary scholarship. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To argue that virtual reality technologies will eventually replace traditional literary scholarship"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To highlight how a new VR-based scholarly edition reconfigures established methods of engaging with historical literature"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To summarize recent debates over the historical accuracy of Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz’s surviving manuscripts"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To criticize the limitations of peer review when applied to emerging digital-humanities projects"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because the passage’s primary purpose is to emphasize the innovative nature of Martínez’s VR-based scholarly edition and how it reconfigures traditional interpretive practices. The text describes an “unprecedented” project evaluated by an atypical group of reviewers and explains how the integration of annotated manuscripts with interactive environments challenges assumptions about the study and dissemination of historical texts. These details support the conclusion that the text’s main aim is to highlight how this new edition reconceives established scholarly methods. Choice A is incorrect because although the text discusses VR’s role in the project, it does not argue that such technology will replace traditional scholarship. The passage focuses on methodological expansion, not technological supremacy. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not summarize debates regarding the historical accuracy of Sor Juana’s manuscripts. It references her work only to contextualize the VR edition, not to examine disputes about authenticity. Choice D is incorrect because while the passage mentions a peer-review process involving experts from multiple fields, it does not criticize peer review or present the process as inadequate; instead, it shows how the process was adapted to suit the project’s interdisciplinary needs.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The study of chronobiology examines how organisms’ internal clocks regulate behavior and physiology. In mammals, daily cycles such as sleep timing are controlled by a central pacemaker in the brain that responds to environmental cues like light. Until recently, researchers assumed that similar timing mechanisms in single-celled organisms operated through fundamentally different biochemical pathways. However, work by marine biologist Samar Basu and colleagues has shown that certain species of phytoplankton adjust their photosynthetic activity through a light-responsive protein complex that functions in ways strikingly similar to mammalian circadian regulators. Their findings suggest that despite vast evolutionary distance, both groups may rely on comparable molecular systems to maintain daily rhythms. What choice best describes the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To outline a laboratory technique used to track how single-celled organisms respond to light exposure"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To argue that phytoplankton behavior provides a reliable model for predicting mammalian sleep patterns"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To summarize research indicating that some time-keeping mechanisms in phytoplankton resemble those found in mammals"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To present evidence that environmental light affects photosynthesis more strongly in single-celled organisms than in mammals"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because the passage’s main purpose is to summarize a finding suggesting that certain molecular mechanisms that regulate daily rhythms in phytoplankton resemble mechanisms known from mammals. The passage explains how circadian regulation is understood in mammals, then introduces new research showing that phytoplankton use a light-responsive protein complex operating in a similar way. Together, these points highlight the surprising similarity between time-keeping systems across distant organisms. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not describe any laboratory technique. It mentions the existence of a light-responsive protein complex but gives no methodological detail about how researchers measured responses. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not claim that phytoplankton can model or predict mammalian sleep patterns. It focuses on similarities at the molecular level, not on using one species to make behavioral predictions about another. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not compare the degree to which light affects photosynthesis in different organisms. Instead, it emphasizes similarities in internal time-keeping mechanisms, not differences in responses to light.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', '"Widespread bioacoustic research has consistently demonstrated that chronic anthropogenic noise results in reduced reproductive success for songbirds, yet some urban populations of Great Tits (Parus major) have recently shown stable or even increasing fledgling counts in high-decibel environments." Behavioral ecologist Wouter Halfwerk and colleagues attribute this paradox to the species’ capacity—absent in less adaptable birds—to modulate the frequency and timing of their vocalizations to "niche-shift" away from low-frequency traffic noise, a behavioral plasticity that has obscured the physiological costs of noise in the aggregate population data researchers typically analyze. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined sentence in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It identifies a contradiction between established scientific findings and recent biological observations that the text later suggests is the result of a specific variable masking broader trends in existing data."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It explains a discrepancy between laboratory-controlled studies and field observations that the text goes on to claim is primarily due to the inherent flaws in the audio recording equipment used by researchers."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It presents a persistent disagreement among ecologists regarding the impact of urban noise that the text goes on to say is caused by researchers focusing on different avian species in different geographic regions."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It describes a recent outlier in a general biological pattern that the text goes on to explain is a result of researchers failing to account for the predatory habits of urban animals in their previous models."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately describes the function of the underlined sentence within the structural logic of the passage. The underlined sentence establishes a conflict: "widespread research" predicts one outcome (reduced success), but "recent observations" of Great Tits show the opposite (stable success). The passage then explains that this "paradox" is due to a "complicating factor"—behavioral plasticity (frequency modulation)—which hides the negative impacts in the broad data sets previously studied. This mirrors the structure of identifying a conflict and then providing the hidden reason for the data''s failure to predict it. Choice B is incorrect. While the underlined sentence does present a discrepancy, the text never mentions "laboratory-controlled studies" versus "field observations," nor does it suggest that any conflict is due to "flaws in audio recording equipment." The explanation provided in the text is biological (behavioral plasticity), not technical. Choice C is incorrect. The underlined sentence does not describe a "persistent disagreement" between two groups of researchers; rather, it describes a conflict between a general research finding and a specific, recent observation. Furthermore, the text does not attribute the difference to "geographic regions" but to the specific behavioral traits of the birds themselves. Choice D is incorrect. Although the underlined sentence identifies an exception (an outlier) to a pattern, the text does not explain this outlier as a failure to account for "predatory habits." Instead, it attributes the exception to vocal "niche-shifting" and behavioral plasticity that masks the costs of noise in the data.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2021, hip-hop artist and University of Virginia professor A.D. Carson released what has been described as the first peer-reviewed hip-hop mixtape/essay. Carson had previously challenged academic norms by presenting his doctoral dissertation as a multi-track rap album addressing themes such as justice, economics, language, and identity. For his later project, published by an academic press, Carson collaborated with other artists and subjected the work to scholarly evaluation, illustrating how hip-hop can operate as a medium for academic inquiry while engaging audiences beyond traditional scholarly circles. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To examine how peer review standards have been adapted to accommodate nontraditional academic formats"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To trace the development of one scholar’s efforts to integrate hip-hop into academic research"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To explain why a particular hip-hop–based academic work is notable for redefining scholarly practice"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To assess the cultural influence of hip-hop when used to address academic themes"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is correct because the text’s primary aim is to explain what makes Carson’s hip-hop project especially innovative as a form of scholarship. The passage emphasizes the combination of peer review, academic publishing, and musical form to show how the project redefines how scholarly work can be produced and shared. Choice A is incorrect because, although peer review is mentioned, the text does not analyze changes to peer review standards in general. Choice B is incorrect because the passage references Carson’s earlier work only to provide context, not to trace his career or development over time. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not evaluate the broader cultural impact of hip-hop but focuses on the scholarly significance of a specific project.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1953, molecular biologists James Watson and Francis Crick elucidated the structure of the DNA double helix. Scholars contend that Watson and Crick’s reliance on X-ray crystallographic data is _______ the explanatory power of their model in accounting for hereditary transmission: these empirical observations substantively undergirded the structural insights that revealed the mechanism of DNA replication. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"peripheral to"},{"id":"B","text":"manifest in"},{"id":"C","text":"scrutinized by"},{"id":"D","text":"complicated by"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Watson and Crick’s DNA model. In this context, “manifest in” means evident or apparent from. The text states that Watson and Crick relied on X-ray crystallographic data, and it emphasizes that these empirical observations substantively supported the structural insights of their model. This context suggests that the explanatory power of their model is evident in, or manifest in, the experimental data they used. Choice A is incorrect because “peripheral to” would suggest that the X-ray data were only marginally related to the model’s explanatory power, which contradicts the text’s description of the data as substantively undergirding the model. Choice C is incorrect because “scrutinized by” would imply that the explanatory power of the model was examined by the X-ray data, which is illogical—the data inform the model, not the other way around. Choice D is incorrect because “complicated by” would suggest that the X-ray data made understanding the model more difficult, which is inconsistent with the text’s assertion that the data supported and clarified the structural insights.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'According to historian Sheila Fitzpatrick, the industrial proletariat of Petrograd played a decisive role in the radicalization of the Russian Revolution in 1917. At the time, the Putilov Ironworks—the largest metallurgical factory in the empire—held massive defense contracts essential to the Russian war effort during World War I. The monarchy’s absolute dependence on the factory’s output for the Eastern Front granted the laborers significant institutional leverage: "strikers demanded not only wage increases but also the establishment of ''factory committees'' to oversee management, and the administration, terrified of halting production for the army, initially yielded to these terms." Consequently, the shop floor became a primary site where workers transitioned from economic grievance to political self-governance. Which choice best describes the function of the underlined portion in the text as a whole?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It elaborates on a claim about the influence of a specific group of workers made earlier in the text."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It provides an example of a broader shift in the global industrial economy discussed earlier in the text."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It identifies a significant exception to the general pattern of labor compliance observed during World War I."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It offers further details regarding the specific ethnic and social identities of the Putilov factory employees."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it accurately describes how the underlined portion functions within the overall structure of the text. The earlier part of the passage claims that the Putilov workers held "significant institutional leverage" due to the monarchy''s dependence on their production. The underlined portion then provides a concrete example of this leverage: the workers successfully demanded factory committees and higher wages because the administration was "terrified" of stopping war production. Thus, the underlined portion elaborates on the claim about the workers'' influence. Choice B is incorrect. While the text mentions the war effort, the underlined portion describes a specific instance of labor negotiation in a single factory, not a "broader shift in the global industrial economy." The passage remains focused on Petrograd. Choice C is incorrect. The underlined portion is used to support the claim that workers were radicalizing and asserting power, which is the "pattern" being described in the text, not an "exception" to it. Choice D is incorrect. While the underlined portion describes what the workers demanded, it does not provide information about their "ethnic or social identities," such as their background, age, or specific social class origins.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The study of chronobiology investigates how internal biological clocks regulate cycles such as sleep and wakefulness. In mammals, these rhythms are governed by a network of genes and proteins that respond to environmental cues like light, enabling the body to anticipate daily changes rather than merely react to them. Such clock-based mechanisms have long been considered a hallmark of complex vertebrate nervous systems. However, recent work by Marisol Vega and her colleagues indicates that certain reef-dwelling fish also rely on a comparable gene-regulated timing system to coordinate feeding and migration behaviors, even in environments where light cues are inconsistent. What choice best describes the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It explains how environmental conditions can disrupt daily behavioral cycles in marine animals."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It outlines a laboratory technique used to identify genetic activity related to timekeeping."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It summarizes evidence that timing mechanisms in some fish share important similarities with those found in mammals."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It compares the feeding patterns of reef fish and mammals in response to changes in light availability."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is correct because the text’s primary aim is to highlight research suggesting that biological timing mechanisms observed in mammals also operate in certain fish. The passage first establishes that gene-regulated internal clocks are well documented in mammals and then reports recent findings showing a similar system in reef-dwelling fish, thereby emphasizing a resemblance in underlying mechanisms across species. Choice A is incorrect because, although environmental cues are mentioned, the text does not focus on disruption caused by those conditions. Choice B is incorrect because no specific laboratory method is described; the passage reports findings rather than experimental procedures. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not compare behaviors across species in response to light but instead stresses shared internal timing processes.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 2, 3);
